<HEADLINE> Kohl: No More State Money for Holocaust Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl said
Friday that the German government would not offer any new money to
compensate for survivors of Nazi slave labour camps.
</P>
<P>
"I am unwilling to rethink (this) with regard to federal
coffers," he said, when being asked whether Bonn would join the
German private sector in funding Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
German companies, such as Allianz AG insurance, have showed
willingness to pay Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Bonn has so far offered about 100 billion
marks (56 billion U.S. dollars) in compensation for victims of
Nazi Germany since World War II.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
