<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jetlag Linked to Breast Cancer in Air Hostesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The higher rate of breast cancer
in air hostesses may be due to jetlag, an American scientist said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The link between air hostesses and breast cancer was revealed
three years ago when a Finnish study found that air hostesses in
Finland were almost twice likely to get breast cancer than women
in other jobs.
</P>
<P>
Several explanations have been put forward, including exposure
to radiation at high altitude.
</P>
<P>
But Dr Anthony Mawson from North Carolina, USA, suggested that
jetlag, by suppressing levels of the hormone melatonin, may be to
blame.
</P>
<P>
"Flight attendants with breast cancer should have more
work-associated exposure to jetlag, and lower melatonin than those
without breast cancer." Dr Mawson said in a letter to the Lancet
medical journal.
</P>
<P>
Melatonin, secreted by the pineal gland in the middle of the
brain, is associated with the body's sleep-wake cycle. When this
cycle is disturbed, as it can be severely with jetlag, less
melatonin is produced.
</P>
<P>
Experiments have shown that the growth of breast-cancer cells
is slowed by melatonin, and there is other evidence that melatonin
may be involved when normal tissue in the breast becomes
cancerous, through melatonin's influence on sex hormones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
