<HEADLINE> Cyprus Expresses Reservation at U.S. Raids on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government on Friday
expressed reservation at the U.S. missile attacks against
suspected terrorist bases in Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing here, government
spokesman Christos Stylianides said Cyprus believed that terrorism
should be dealt with on the basis of the international law and the
U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
"The Cyprus government considers that the best way to deal with
terrorism is on the basis of the principles of international law
and the provisions of the U.N. Charter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the U.S. had violated these principles through the use
of force, Stylianides replied: "It is not up to the Cyprus
government to be the judge of this. It is a matter for the
international bodies."
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the Cyprus government unequivocally any
form of terrorism, including the August 7 bombings of the
U.S. embassies in capitals of Kenya and Tanzania which killed over
250 people and injured 5,000 others.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that if there is a discussion on the
international arena on the issue, then the Cyprus government
will express its clear position.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. launched air strikes Thursday against what it called
terrorist facilities in Afghanistan and Sudan in retaliation for
the embassy bombings in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
