<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taking Care of Displaced Flood Victims Requires Massive Effort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Some 2.1 million people in Anhui,
Hunan and Jilin provinces have fled their homes to seek safety
from some of the worst flooding in China's history. But all of
them have found a place to live, food to eat and clothing to wear
thanks to endeavors of the central and local governments,
according to a source at the Ministry of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
East China's Anhui Province, one of the flood-hit areas, has
evacuated 822,000 people from flooded areas, a provincial official
announced here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the flood victims, who used to live in
islets and areas which are in floodwater, sought refuge with
relatives in both urban and rural areas. Others are living in
temporary shelters where they are provided with food and clean
water, the official said. Medical workers make regular visits to
their tents and 9 million yuan in medicine has been distributed,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has set up 2,700 tents and 21,000
shelters, and has converted 13,000 buildings used for other
purposes to house flood victims, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Cai Qihua, head of the provincial water conservation
department, said his province had spent 300 million yuan on
fortifying Yangtze River dikes and building 20 reservoirs. These
projects have helped reduce flood losses by 40.7 billion yuan this
year.
</P>
<P>
Floods have driven 1 million people out of their homes in 40
flooded counties and cities in central China's Hunan Province over
the past month, according to a provincial official.
</P>
<P>
At present, half the flood victims live in 180,000 tents or
temporary shelters, 200,000 live in houses made available by
government institutions and schools, and 300,000 are living with
relatives, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The provincial financial department has allocated 200 million
yuan of relief funds, 15 million kilograms of grain and 1.1
million articles of clothing to flood-affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in northeast China's Jilin Province, the government
of Baicheng city has earmarked 2 million yuan to build houses for
280,000 evacuees and spent another 1 million yuan to provide food,
a city official said.
</P>
<P>
The central and provincial governments have also reportedly
shipped 5 million tents, food and medicine to Baicheng.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
