<HEADLINE> Philippine Private Sector Urged to Help Fight Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada on Friday urged the private sector to help the government
generate jobs and ease poverty which would lift his pro-poor
campaign pledge from the level of rhetoric to concrete action.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on poverty alleviation, Estrada voiced confidence
that he can lead the nation out of the economic storm as long as
there are more people willing to work than just talk.
</P>
<P>
Estrada underscored the urgent need for the government and the
private sector to join forces in creating jobs in urban centers
and the countryside, in agriculture and industries, as a vital
component of his administration's policy to give the poor
opportunities to be self-reliant.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said his administration has begun sorting out 86 loan
programs and opening wider the credit windows of all government
financial institutions for small enterprises in order to create
more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Poverty has been a pernicious opponent, he said, noting that
effort by previous governments to fight it has failed to stop more
people from being driven into the poor house.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official statistics, the Philippines,
with a population of some 70 million, has a poverty incidence of
34 percent. Poverty alleviation has been listed as a top priority
for the Estrada administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
