<HEADLINE> Sudanese FM Visits Iraq After U.S. Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Foreign Minister
Mustafa Osman Ismail arrived here Friday following the U.S. air
raid on a Sudanese pharmaceutical factory.
</P>
<P>
But the Iraqi News Agency reported that the visit was
previously arranged and not prompted by the U.S. missile attack.
</P>
<P>
Ismail is expected to hold talks with Iraqi officials on
bilateral relations, Arab and international issues of common
concern, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here anticipated the U.S. air strike will be added to
the agenda of the talks.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. fired several missiles Thursday night at a
pharmaceutical factory in the Sudanese capital Khartoum in
retaliation for bombings of U.S. embassies in capitals of Kenya
and Tanzania on August 7.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. alleged that the factory was manufacturing chemical
weapons agents, which could be used by suspected Islamic militants
to launch new attacks against U.S. targets.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, Iraq, a sworn enemy of the U.S., has condemned
the U.S. strike. The ruling Iraqi Revolutionary Command Council
issued a statement to denounced the U.S. attack as a result of its
"rash, aggressive and dangerous policy."
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the attack "reflects the failures of
the U.S. foreign policy."
</P>
<P>
Sudan was one of the few Arab states that sided with Iraq
during the 1991 Gulf War sparked by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
</TEXT>
