<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Urges its Nationals to Leave Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- British government Friday urged
British nationals to leave Afghanistan and postpone travelling to
Sudan and Pakistan following Thursday's American air strikes
against alleged terrorist bases in Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The British Foreign Office said in a statement issued early
Friday: "For Afghanistan our advice has long been against travel.
In the recent days we have been strongly advising the few
remaining British nationals to leave Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Office also urged British citizens to "consider
whether their visits (to Sudan) are absolutely essential,"
advising all non-essential visits to be postponed.
</P>
<P>
"We are also advising Britons in Sudan to remain vigilant and
cautious, and to keep in close touch with us for updated advice in
the days ahead," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"For Pakistan, we are advising travellers against non-essential
visits. In particular, we are advising against travel to the North
West Frontier Province, Baluchistan and the Federally Administered
Tribal Areas," it added.
</P>
<P>
A BBC Television report said that some 30 people were killed
and hundreds of others were missing following the American missile
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
