<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Must Report Offshore Assets This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Revenue Minister Herb Dhaliwal
announced Thursday that Canadian residents will be required to
report foreign assets of more than 100,000 dollars (66,000
U.S. dollars) for 1998 tax returns by April 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Ottawa originally put that requirement in place in its 1995
budget, effective with returns filed this April for the 1997 tax
year.
</P>
<P>
However, faced with strong opposition from some Canadians,
especially those in the Asian community, Ottawa postponed the
requirement for one year.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's decision is said to be a compromise between the
revenue department's desire to combat tax havens and the concern
over privacy of some taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
Dhaliwal said there will be "streamlined procedures" for
verifying foreign-based income earned by Canadian residents.
</P>
<P>
The government has also changed "foreign asset reporting" to
"foreign income verification."
</P>
<P>
Under the new reporting method, taxpayers need only indicate
the range and location of investments for different categories of
assets by checking a box on a reporting form.
</P>
<P>
The department has dropped the requirement to provide detailed
descriptions for each investment.
</P>
<P>
The new measures, which include a five percent penalty based on
the costs of assets, will be reviewed after two years, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
