<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Condemns U.S. Air Strike on Sudan, Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry on
Friday expressed "serious worries" over U.S. air strikes on Sudan
and Afghanistan, while the State Duma, or lower house of
parliament, condemned the move as an aggression.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin, who was observing a naval exercise of
the Northern Fleet in the Barents Sea at the time, also expressed
indignation over the U.S. military action, said presidential
spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
However, Moscow's "joint work with the United States in the
struggle against terrorism, and the special services of the two
countries will continue," the Itar-Tass news agency quoted
Yastrzhembsky as saying.
</P>
<P>
Several people were killed and about 300 are still missing
following the destruction of a pharmaceutical factory near
Khartoum, capital of Sudan, by U.S. missiles on Thursday, Governor
Majzoub Khalifa of the Sudanese province of Khartoum said.
</P>
<P>
Initial reports said 15 people died in the bombing at a
training camp of Islamists near the Afghan city of Host on the
border with Pakistan, 165 kilometers south of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Foreign Ministry, in its statement, said the
bombings would "not bring the eradication of terrorism any closer,
but may create a dangerous precedent of resolving international
disputes in this way, thus undermining the legal framework of
international relations.
</P>
<P>
"In effect, while it does not address the essence of the
problem, such action can trigger a chain reaction whose
consequences cannot be predicted," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"A solid barrier to terrorism should be erected through
increased bilateral and multilateral interaction of countries,"
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"Russia resolutely condemned the recent acts of terrorism
against the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. Russian
President Boris Yeltsin condemned them as a brazen challenge to
the entire international community," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, in a special statement, said the U.S. air
strikes on two sovereign countries "were largely due to the recent
developments in the United States," a veiled reference to the sex
scandal involving U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
It also called on President Yeltsin to work out measures to
help avert a similar use of force in the future and reconsider the
advisability of Clinton's visit to Moscow scheduled for
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
