<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Regrets US Air Strikes in Afghanistan, Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Friday expressed
its disappointment over the air strikes launched by the United
States in Afghanistan and Sudan Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We are upset because the attack is said to have been allowed
by the U.N., but we don't know that the U.N. had given its
permission," Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad told a news
conference in Kangar, according to Malaysia's national news agency
Bernama.
</P>
<P>
"How do we know if they (The U.S.) won't attack us later. They
will say it's self-defense too," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on the air strikes which the U.S. said were
aimed at terrorist bases in Afghanistan and Sudan believed to have
been behind the bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania early this month, and on Washington's reported claim that
it was exercising its legal right to defend itself as provided for
by the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
"Who is the one who decides? If I can decide where I want to
attack, the world will be in chaos. If it's a big power, it can
attack anyone. It decides and it executes, making small countries
feel it's dangerous to live in this world. We (small countries) do
not dare to say anything. If we do we may be attacked," Mahathir
said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir described the U.S. action as passing sentence and
enforcing it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
