<HEADLINE> Ten Cambodian Parties Reject Election Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Ten Cambodian opposition
parties said Friday they have decided to reject the results of the
July 26 election because of alleged voting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
Main opposition parties, namely Funcinpec, Sam Rainsy Party,
and Son Sann Party joined the move with seven small political
parties, such as the Cambodian National Sustaining Party led by
Pen Sovann.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from the parties said in a joint statement that they
were committed to uniting all free democratic forces and did not
recognize the election results.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties have called for a protest march on
Sunday, demanding a solution to their charges of election
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
But the call was rejected by the Interior Ministry, saying that
most police have the day off and security cannot be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties alleged electoral fraud by the Cambodian
People's Party (CPP)-- which is led by government leader Hun Sen
who won the election -- and threatened to boycott the new
assembly, the parliament, which is to convene on September 24.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results from the National Election Committee
show the ruling CPP won more than 41 percent of the valid votes
cast, followed by the Funcinpec with 32 percent and the Sam Rainsy
Party.
</P>
<P>
The 10 parties are collectively credited with 50.33 percent of
the votes, said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
