<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Flood Situation Remains Rigorous in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The flood situation has not yet
eased in China, with the sixth flood crest on the Yangtze River
and the third one on the Songhua River moving downstream while new
floodwaters are possible on the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin's scheduled visits to Russia and Japan in
early September have been postponed because of the immensity of
the flood-control and disaster-relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
Major floods may hit the Yangtze again this weekend as
torrential rains have, since Wednesday, deluged seven prefectures
and cities in the northwestern areas of the Sichuan Basin, which
is located on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River, according to
the State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters (SFCDRH).
</P>
<P>
The sixth flood crest of the Yangtze passed Wuhan, capital of
central China's Hubei Province, at about 11 p.m. Thursday with a
water level of 29.43 meters.
</P>
<P>
The figure dropped slightly to 29.36 m at 2 p.m. today. SFCDRH
authorities say that the drop of water level was so insignificant
that flood-fighting will remain difficult.
</P>
<P>
According to latest reports, the third flood crest on the
Songhua river today passed Harbin, the largest heavy industrial
center in northeast China, at an all-time-high water level of
120.82 meters.
</P>
<P>
This level, accompanied by a flow rate of 17,400 cubic meters
per second, is 2.72 meters higher than the danger mark, and 0.77
meters higher than the 1957 record.
</P>
<P>
The swollen Nenjiang River has inundated 1,443 oil wells in
Daqing, China's largest oil field, and production by 282 wells has
been suspended for 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Some 400,000 soldiers and civilians are now working on the
flood-fighting front lines to protect the nine million residents
of Harbin. Banners bearing slogans such as "Defend levees to the
death" and "Protecting Harbin requires a life or death struggle"
are hanging from trees near the levees.
</P>
<P>
While millions of people are countering the flooding on these
rivers, the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region and the provinces of
Shaanxi, Shanxi and Henan along the Yellow River, have also been
busy repairing facilities to prepare for possible flooding.
</P>
<P>
Vice-President Hu Jintao has called on Party organizations at
various levels and Party members to play a backbone role in the
disaster-relief effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Flood Situation Remains Rigorous in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The SFCDRH is sending more materials to flood-ravaged areas
along the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze, the Nenjiang
and the Songhua rivers. By Wednesday, the headquarters had sent
200 million yuan worth of goods to the areas.
</P>
<P>
Domestic and foreign donations sent to the Ministry of Civil
Affairs and its sub-departments across the country have surpassed
1.06 billion yuan (130 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A large benefit performance for China's flood victims,
organized by the ministries of Culture and Civil Affairs, was held
at the Great Hall of the People this evening. The show included
performances by nearly 1,000 Chinese singers, dancers and movie
stars, including artists from Hong Kong, Taiwan and some foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
A similar event held Thursday by Beijing Television Station
reported the collection of 170 million yuan (20.48 million
U.S. dollars), which will be sent to the flooded areas as relief
funds.
</P>
<P>
A telephone survey in Beijing found that more than 88 percent
of the city's citizens have donated money or goods for flood-hit
parts of China and the rest say they want to make a donation.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai residents were sweating in oppressive heat, but still
doing their best to provide relief goods for flood-ravaged parts
of China. At least 160 trains carrying relief goods and more than
4,000 people have left Shanghai for flood areas.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs has pledged that every penny of
the funds raised will be used for the country's flood victims,
whose total number exceeds 240 million.
</P>
<P>
In a circular made public Thursday, the ministry told people to
give money and goods to local civil affairs or other departments
that are approved for receiving donations.
</P>
<P>
President and Party General Secretary Jiang Zemin made a phone
call on Thursday evening to Minister of Health Zhang Wenkang
inquiring about the spread and treatment of epidemic diseases in
the flood-hit areas, urging the ministry to do a good job of
treating and controlling diseases in the disastrous areas.
</P>
<P>
An official from the ministry has appealed to the public for
more potable water and water-purifying machines to be sent to the
flooded areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
