<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Friday:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- Dozens of American cruise missiles struck targets in
Afghanistan and the Sudan Thursday in what President Clinton
described as an act of self-defense against imminent terrorist
plots and of retribution for the bombings of American embassies in
East Africa two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
-- The most cherished axiom of American foreign policy is that
politics stops at the water's edge, meaning that political
opponents support the President when missiles are flying. Today it
mostly worked, but the challenge of President Clinton's latest
crisis crystallized when some critics uncharacteristically cried
foul.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Monica S. Lewinsky returned to the grand jury for the final
time Thursday to amplify her account of an extramarital affair
with President Clinton as new details emerged about his testimony
earlier this week and their conflicting versions of the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
-- Osama bin Laden, the Saudi-born Islamic militant whose
terrorist network was the target of U.S. missile strikes in
central Afghanistan, has spent the the past 15 months living about
200 miles south of the site of the attacks, using as his base a
fortified and heavily guarded hilltop compound outside the city of
Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Continued sanctions against Iraq were backed by the U.N.
Security Council after its regular 60-day review. The council
called Baghdad's suspension of cooperation with arms inspectors
"totally unacceptable," but the U.S. failed in a bid to threaten
Iraq with "severest consequences" in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
-- Germany's Social Democrats said tax reform and efforts to
ease unemployment would be their main goals if they defeat
Chancellor Kohl and his Christian Democrats September 27. Gerhard
Schroeder announced the platform as polls show some erosion of his
lead. 
</P>
