part of a strategy ordered by exiled Jose Ma. Sison, chairman of
the Communist Party of the Philippines (CPP), to increase their
mass base support.
</P>
<P>
The NPA, the arm wing of the CPP-led National Democratic Front
(NDF), has suffered a big drop in number since 1986 after the
military successfully launched its counter-insurgency operation.
</P>
<P>
From a high of 26,800 in 1986, the NPA strength went down to
about 6,000 at present, Castillo said.
</P>
<P>
Castillo said Sison, who has been living in exile in the
Netherlands since March 1986, used the Internet last year to call
on the CPP and the NDF to increase their mass base indoctrination.
</P>
<P>
"This is part of their new strategy to recruit new members to
join the NPA as the peace talks between the government and the
communists resume next month," Castillo said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that there is a slight increase in NPA-initiated
attacks in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
According to Castillo, the military clashed with a 70-man NPA
team for two hours in a remote village in North Cotabato province
on August 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Flooded Areas face Threat of Infectious Diseases (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua)-- The epidemic control situation in
China's flood-stricken areas is stable but infectious diseases
such as snail fever are threatening.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Minister of Health Zhang Wenkang while
addressing an emergency national conference on epidemic prevention
here this morning.
</P>
<P>
All major infectious diseases are now under control in the
flooded areas, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
In Hubei, Hunan, Jiangxi, Heilongjiang, Anhui, Jiangsu and
Jilin provinces and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, which
have suffered most from the floods, the average incidence of
epidemic diseases has even dropped slightly from last year, he
added.
</P>
<P>
But the health minister conceded that the incidence of
intestinal epidemic diseases has increased, with over 1,500 cases
of such diseases reported from the above-mentioned provinces and
region.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of dysentery, hepatitis and colds are also
slightly up compared with the same period last year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry is also greatly concerned about the health
of the people fighting the floods in areas with a relatively
high incidence of snail fever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flooded Areas Face Threat of Infectious Diseases (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 400 cases of snail fever infection have to date been
reported to the ministry from those areas. But experts have
expected more cases in the near future since snail fever has a
fairly long latent period of 40 days.
</P>
<P>
Zhang noted that the major problem for epidemic control in the
flood-stricken areas is a shortage of funds and medicines, adding
that the problem could become worse in the next three months,
usually the peak period for the spread of epidemics in China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, a large proportion of the office buildings
and equipment of the medical institutions in the flooded areas
has been lost in the flooding.
</P>
<P>
In late July, the Ministry of Health allocated 10 million yuan
(about 1.2 million U.S. dollars) to 18 provinces and autonomous
regions afflicted by natural disasters, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, epidemic control efforts in the eight provinces and
autonomous regions most severely hit by the summer flooding have
already cost local governments and medical institutions some
62 million yuan (about 7.5 million U.S. dollars) as well as medical
supplies worth over 250 million yuan (about 30 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the ministry has persuaded the municipalities
of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and the provinces of Hebei, Shanxi,
Zhejiang, Shandong and Guangdong to take immediate action to
provide medical assistance for the flooded regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
