<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Doctors Activated to Aid Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A team of 13 military doctors have
been activated to provide medical service for victims in the
flooding-ravaged area of east China's Anhui Province.
</P>
<P>
The medical officers, from the Electronic Engineering College
of the People's Liberation Army (PLA), have been working for five
days in Wangjiang County at the upper reaches of the Yuanjiang
River which experienced the worst flooding this decade.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday, they rowed a small boat to Pohu Village, ten km from
their base, and began operating a clinic to treat villagers.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Shengtao, a 70-year old farmer, said he had been
suffering from a serious cough for several days and had lacked
medicine and treatment.
</P>
<P>
A doctor told Cheng that his cold was the result of spending so
much time in the flood waters. After giving some medicine to the
old farmer, the doctor urged him to take it on time, drink more
water, and to keep warm while sleeping at night.
</P>
<P>
"I have experienced several flooding disasters in my lifetime,
this is the best service to the victims," Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with their work in hospitals, the doctors had a
difficult time in the poor village where they treated some
300 patients just in one morning.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
