<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollars Stumbles to Two-Month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar stumbled
to its lowest close against the U.S. dollar in over two months
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The domestic unit was sold off as Russia's economic problems
reached a crisis point and Asian currencies remained soft, Bank of
America foreign exchange dealer Andrew Le said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed the session at 58.75 U.S. cents,
down from 59.13 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the concern was now the unit would slide toward
58 cents, a level where the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) jumped
into the market to defend the currency in June.
</P>
<P>
In its quarterly statement on the economy released earlier this
week, the RBA acknowledged it had bought 2.6 billion of the
domestic currency (about 1.56 billion U.S. dollars) in June.
</P>
<P>
The central bank blamed a belief by market participants that
Australian authorities were happy to see the local currency
continue to fall and an increased hedge funds' profile in the
market for June's slide.
</P>
<P>
In a break from its recent strong correlation with the Japanese
yen, the Australian dollar found itself sold heavily not only
against the U.S. dollar but the yen itself in the latter part of
the week.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar slid lower to 83.93 yen, down from 84.52
previously, while against the German mark, the Australian dollar
was at 1.0564 marks from 1.0600. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
