<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Aims to Boost Ties With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President Nachagyn
Bagabandy said Friday that developing good-neighborly relations
and cooperation with China is high on Mongolia's foreign policy
agenda.
</P>
<P>
He said this when meeting with a visiting delegation of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), led by Dai Bingguo, head of the
International Liaison Department of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia is committed to develop the 21st century-oriented
friendly ties with China in accordance with the Friendship and
Cooperation Treaty signed in 1994, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Mongolian president also hopes his Beijing tour later this
year will enhance Mongolian-Chinese cooperation on economy and
trade.
</P>
<P>
Dai, a member of the CPC Central Committee, said the upcoming
visit by the Mongolian president would contribute to enhancing
Sino-Mongolian ties. He added that the CPC and the Chinese
government respects Mongolia's independence, sovereignty and
intergration of territory.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation began their visit on August 18.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia has enjoyed good economic links and trade with
China. Twenty percent of Mongolian exports flowed into China last
year. China has become the second largest trading partner of the
inland Asian nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
