<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People, Birds Lose Homes In Dongting Lake Area (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Standing on the dike, Zhang
Houyi, nearly 50 and a farmer in central China's Hunan Province,
can see neither his house, submerged by flood waters, nor the
summer migratory birds that used to fly through the sky like
clouds.
</P>
<P>
Serious floods inundated villages in the Dongting Lake area at
the middle reaches of the raging Yangtze River about a month ago,
and less than half of the summer migratory birds have come here
this year.
</P>
<P>
"Where are those birds, and where is the crane family which
spent 11 winters in my yard?" Zhang murmured.
</P>
<P>
In 1981, Zhang found the family of three cranes beside a pool
in front of his house. Zhang, the best hunter in the area and
someone who has bagged more than 100 wild ducks, didn't aim at the
cranes because he was touched by these beautiful birds which came
from the Ganges River valley in India where their habitats were
deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
He approached them carefully, offering them food and shelter.
The crane family gave birth to a new member each year for 11
years thereafter, and became friends of the Zhang family.
</P>
<P>
Zhang became a voluntary bird protector in 1984, after the East
Dongting Lake Nature Reserve was established. Since then, the
number of birds in the area had increased from about 4 million to
more than 10 million.
</P>
<P>
But with about one third of the 4,000-square-kilometer lake
developed into farmland, and an increasing number of factories
built around the lake, Zhang saw floods ravage his homeland more
frequently and more severely in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time, I realized that human activities should be
held responsible for the natural disasters," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President: Sudan Not to Submit to Tyrannical U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President General Omar
Bashir said Friday that the Sudan will not submit to the
U.S. tyrannical force, calling upon the Sudanese people to reject
the U.S. hegemony.
</P>
<P>
Bashir made the remark at a news conference held here following
an emergency session of the Sudanese National Security and Defense
Council to discuss the Thursday bombing of a Sudanese factory by
U.S. warplanes.
</P>
<P>
U.S. warplanes attacked the Al Shifa pharmaceutical factory on
the outskirts of Khartoum Thursday evening, injuring at least 10
people. Washington claimed that the factory makes chemical weapon
agents for terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Bashir visited the site of the bombardment right after the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Out in streets, the Sudanese masses joined in demonstrations
right after the attack.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators thrust into the U.S. embassy building in
Khartoum, pulled down the American flag, tore it to pieces and
stepped over it, shouting anti-US slogans.
</P>
<P>
Washington had ordered the closing down of the embassy on
August 8 and pulled out the whole staff.
</P>
<P>
Bashir also strongly denounced the U.S. Administration and
described it as ignorant and incapable of defining the sites it
was after. He indicated that hitting that factory obviously
demonstrated that information gathered by the U.S. was far from
being real.
</P>
<P>
He said the attacked factory is a well-known model in the
pharmaceutical industry and open to foreign visitors, describing
it as a pride of the Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Bashir underlined that the Sudan maintained the right to
complain to the United Nations, and would request the Security
Council to dispatch a fact-finding mission to examine the
badly-ruined factory.
</P>
<P>
He further reiterated that the Sudan maintained the right to
respond to the U.S. aggression. 
</P>
</TEXT>
