<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Hold Peace Talks on Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela is set to hold peace talks Saturday, which will
bring together presidents of the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC), Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is the culmination of two weeks' diplomacy of
South Africa to secure a peaceful solution to the conflict in the
DRC, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda were accused by DRC President Laurent Kabila
of backing rebels fighting him, but both countries denied the
charge.
</P>
<P>
In the past two weeks, South African Foreign Minister Alfred
Nzo and Defense Minister Joe Modise shuttled between South
Africa, the DRC, Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's peace efforts also involved phone calls between
Mandela, his deputy Thabo Mbeki, and Kabila and other regional
leaders, including former Tanzanian president Julius Nyerere.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki had reportedly worked throughout Wednesday night and
Thursday to try and secure the participation of all the leaders.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, who was firmly in favor of
military intervention, was also invited to the meeting in
Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Presidential aide Parks Mankahlana said there was an agreement
in principle from all the parties to attend the talks. But he
declined to name the venue for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The aide said that the peace talks will be followed by a
summit of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) in
Pretoria on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The summit is aimed at resolving the split within the SADC on
how to best deal with the crisis in the Great Lakes country.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has reportedly sent troops and military hardware to
Kinshasa to help Kabila quell the revolt.
</P>
<P>
South Africa has made clear that it does not believe in any
military solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
