<HEADLINE> China's Urban Air Quality Drops Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- China's urban air quality has
dropped slightly over the past week, according to the China
Environmental Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
The center's latest air-quality report said that as rainfall
decreased in north and northwest China from August 14 to 20, the
amount of some cities' suspended particles increased. However,
most cities enjoy good air quality.
</P>
<P>
Nine cities -- Zhuhai, Xiamen, Beihai, Guilin, Shantou,
Wenzhou, Nanning, Zhanjiang and Haikou -- enjoyed excellent air
quality during the period.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-one cities, including Shanghai, Beijing, Xi'an and
Nanning, reported good air quality.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou, Huhhot, Urumqi, Taiyuan, Lanzhou and Zhengzhou
suffered from slight air pollution over the past week, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's major problem was high levels of nitrogen oxide,
and five other cities all reported high levels of suspended
particles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
