<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Conference on Domestic Animal Ends in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Fourth Global Conference
on Conservation of Domestic Animal Genetic Resources ended here
Friday, with 49 papers presented on different aspects at the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
At the four-day conference, a total of 161 participants from 32
countries representing six continents presented their papers on
sustainable agriculture, genetic distance and molecular markers,
and breed identification and characterization, according to the
summary report of the conference.
</P>
<P>
Papers were also presented on conservation of domestic animal
diversity, role of women, eco-tourism and farm parks, evaluating
land race and feral populations of genetic resources, and historic
sites, livestock and poultry conservation and public education.
</P>
<P>
The conference was jointly organized by the Nepal Agricultural
Research Council and the Rare Breed International (RBI).
</P>
<P>
Keith Ramsey, president of RBI, told the press Thursday that
the biggest challenge facing the world in conservation of domestic
animal genetic resources was the loss of diversity, particularly
in the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the closing ceremony of the conference, Surya Nath
Upadhyay, secretary at the Nepali Ministry of Agriculture and
chairman of the conference, said that the conference would help
further identify and characterize the unidentified indigenous
animals, especially in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, RBI decided that the 5th global conference on
conservation of domestic animal genetic resources will be held in
Brasilia, Brazil, in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People, Birds Lose Homes In Dongting Lake Area (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The crane family has not returned since the winter of 1992,
which was also a flood year. At that time, Zhang said, a new
road was being built in the village and machines and vehicles were
roaring day and night.
</P>
<P>
"It's not suitable for the cranes", Zhang said regretfully.
</P>
<P>
The area of the nature reserve, which is wintering grounds for
some 16,000 migratory birds, has been dwindling due to the encroaching
human activity. Villagers around the lake no longer hear birds
singing around their homes.
</P>
<P>
The destroyed vegetation at the upper and middle reaches of
the Yangtze River can also be attributed to the worsening
environment, experts say, adding that it has also caused serious
soil erosion. About 100 million-cubic-meters of silt are deposited
in the lake every year. Moreover, hundreds of floodgates built
around the lake have interrupted fish reproduction and migration.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino and La Nina phenomena are believed to be the main
causes of the current flooding, but excessive exploitation of
nature by human beings should be blamed first, experts emphasize.
</P>
<P>
This area, known as a land of fish and rice, has more than
660,000 hectares of farmland and a population of over 10
million. It is estimated that the lake area has suffered a loss of
nearly 10 billion yuan (about 1.2 billion U.S. dollars) in the
flooding.
</P>
<P>
"The birds have to find new habitats, but it is more and more
difficult for them to find new living ground, and what about human
beings?" Zhang asks himself.
</P>
<P>
"After the flood recedes, I would like to tell people more
about environmental protection, and the relations among birds,
fish, floods, and human beings," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will allocate significant funding for
environmental protection in the Dongting Lake area, and it is also
considering transforming farmland back to the lake as part of a
comprehensive treatment program to restore the lake, official
sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
