<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former S. African President Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's former
president P.W. Botha was sentenced Friday to a fine of 10,000
Rand (1,600 U.S. Dollars) or 12 months in jail after being found
guklty of flouting a Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC)
subpoena.
</P>
<P>
Another 12 months' imprisonment was suspended for five years,
South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The sentence was handed down by Magistrate Victor Lugaju in
the George Regional Court in Western Cape province at the end of
a trial that lasted eight months.
</P>
<P>
Botha's lawyers immediately said their client intended to
appeal and that documents had already been drawn up for the
action.
</P>
<P>
Delivering the sentence, Lugaju said that Botha, who is 82
years old, was not in good health and was a first offender.
</P>
<P>
However, throughout the trial he had shown no remorse and had
been granted enough opportunity to resolve the matter amicably,
but had not done so.
</P>
<P>
Lugaju said the aggravating factors in this instance far
outweighed the mitigating factors, and that he considered the
sentence appropriate.
</P>
<P>
Botha was found to have contravened the founding act of the
TRC, the Promotion of National Unity and Reconciliation Act, by
ignoring a subpoena to attend a TRC hearing on the now-defunct
state security council, which he chaired in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The maximum punishment for snubbing the TRC is a jail sentence
of up to two years and/or a fine up to 20,000 Rand (3,200 U.S.
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Botha's lawyers argued that the subpoena was technically
flawed and that he had an agreement with TRC Chairman Desmond
Tutu that he could answer any of the TRC's questions in writing.
</P>
<P>
In his judgement, Lugaju said: "It is the unanimous finding of
this court that the accused's failure to appear was unlawful and
intentional, and therefore he is guilty as charged."
</P>
<P>
He rejected Botha's defense counsels' arguments that the
subpoena was invalid, that the TRC had acted in bad faith toward
him, and that there was an agreement between Botha and Tutu.
</P>
<P>
Acting TRC Chairman Alex Boraine welcomed the court ruling,
saying it showed that South Africa was now a society in which
nobody was above the law. Tutu is in north America.
</P>
<P>
In its response, the ruling African National Congress said
that Botha's conviction would send a clear message that no one
was above the law.
</P>
<P>
However, South African President Nelson Mandela's office said
it would not comment on the issue.
</P>
<P>
"It's a matter for the courts," Mandela's spokesman Parks
Mankahlana said.
</P>
<P>
About 50 demonstrators gathered outside the court before Botha
arrived Friday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
