talks are believed to have centered on the Congolese crisis and
steps being taken to stop it from escalating.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda, which helped DRC President Laurent Kabila oust late
dictator Mobutu Sese Seko, has been accused by Kabila's
government of backing the Tutsi-led rebellion which started on
August 2 in eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe Thursday accused Rwanda of
directly being involved in the efforts to topple Kabila, who came
to power 15 months ago.
</P>
<P>
While Zambia is a member of the four-nation reconciliatory
committee formed at the regional summit held on Agust 8 in
Zimbabwe. It has agreed with Zimbabwe and Namibia to conduct
military intervention in the Congolese crisis to help President
Kabila, disclosed Mugabe Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But up till now the Zambian government has remained silent on
whether or not the Zambian troops will join other countries in
the military intervention, which met strong objection from South
African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela proposed a peaceful and political solution to the
Congolese crisis and urged all warring factions to stop fighting
and talk.
</P>
<P>
As chairman of the 14-nation regional grouping, the Southern
African Development Community (SADC), Mandela said Thursday that
he planned a regional summit to discuss a peaceful end to the
rebellion in DRC, where the rebels have taken control of one
third of the territory and are threatening to capture the capital
Kinshasa by the end of this month. 
</P>
