<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Vows to Punish Those Responsible for Grenade Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Interior Ministry
has vowed to take tough action against the perpetrators of
Thursday night's grenade attack outside the ministry that killed
at least one person.
</P>
<P>
Khieu Sopheak, spokesman of the Interior Ministry, made the
remark Friday morning at a press conference held at the
information ministry.
</P>
<P>
The government and the interior ministry will do their best to
arrest those it has deemed ``killers'' and bring them to justice,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry will file charges in the municipal court
against those who entered the ministry compound without
permission, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Some people want to disturb the political atmosphere and
create a political crisis in Cambodia through legal or illegal
protests, various forms of violence, and attempt to change the
results of the July 26 election," he said.
</P>
<P>
The attack, which occurred just after 11 p.m. (1600 GMT) on
Thursday, killed at least one person. Gunmen opened fire and threw
a grenade outside the Interior Ministry gate.
</P>
<P>
The dead man was identified as Sieng Sean, a Cambodian driver
for the Japanese news agency Kyodo.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy, the opposition party leader, was in the National
Election Committee headquarters in the Interior Ministry compound
at the time.
</P>
<P>
The investigation is still under way.
</P>
<P>
The incident may affect the relatively peaceful post-election
calm and raise concerns about the future of the new government.
</P>
<P>
Two main opposition parties Funcinpec and Sam Rainsy Party also
held a joint press conference Friday afternoon to condemn
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Yahya, Funcinpec Parliamentarian, said he was concerned
about the safety of opposition political leaders. He believes that
someone wants to eliminate Sam Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
"So I came here just to show unity with Funcinpec and SRP. I
believe that at this time, the opposition party SRP and Funcinpec
are becoming stronger. We will at the end produce a lot of good
results for everyone," Yahya said.
</P>
<P>
Despite increasing international pressure to quickly form a new
coalition government, Funcinpec and the SRP continue to boycott
the results of the election and appear poised for a protracted
battle with the ruling CPP.
</P>
<P>
The two opposition parties insisted that Hun Sen, the incumbent
second prime minister and vice president of the CPP, not be named
prime minister of the new government. CPP officials say the
request is ludicrous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
