<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Strait Association Says Political Negotiations Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) says that Taiwan and the
mainland need to hold procedural talks on political negotiation as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Taiwan's Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF),
ARATS said it has helped settle hundreds of accidents that
involved loss of life and property across the Taiwan Strait, and
because ARATS is an authoritative non-government organization it
must assist relatives of Taiwanese who die on the mainland with
affairs afterwards.
</P>
<P>
When there was a boat accident on Qiandao Lake in Zhejiang
Province in March 1994, for example, ARATS invited relatives of
the victims and SEF members to Hangzhou, Zhejiang's provincial
capital, to provide them with information about the case.
</P>
<P>
Since this non-government exchange channel was established, it
has become common practice for the ARATS to be responsible for
providing assistance to relatives of Taiwanese compatriots.
</P>
<P>
ARATS says that it has always tried its best to safeguard the
rights and interests of compatriots on Taiwan and the mainland.
</P>
<P>
In the first meeting of ARATS' President Wang Daohan and SEF's
Chairman Koo Chenfu, ARATS made a proposal on the rights and
interests of Taiwanese investment on the mainland and
cross-straits tourism. But, ARATS says, SEF has always been
evasive and has continued to postpone talks on these matters,
using "judicial jurisdiction" and other politically sensitive
issues as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
ARATS explains, however, that things like "judicial
jurisdiction" need to be discussed in light of the 'One China
Principle' and that it is in fact political disparity that is the
obstacle in the way of cross-straits relations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Plans to Protect Environment of Bohai Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- the Chinese capital city of
Beijing plans to make huge investments in upgrading the processing
capabilities of its sewage plants in an effort to reduce the
amount of polluted water discharged into the Bohai Bay.
</P>
<P>
Home to a population of 13 million, the city discharges more
than two million tons of domestic and industrial waste water a
day, the bulk of which flows into the Bohai Bay, some 150 kilometers
southeast of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The foul waste discharged by major industrial cities on the
Bohai Bay has contaminated the maritime environment to such an
appaling extent that fish and shrimps have disappeared in
some areas of the bay.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the worsening situation, the city government has
speeded up construction of the Gaobeidian Sewage Plant, which is
intended to purify some one million tons of foul water daily by
September 1999 when it is scheduled to be completed.
</P>
<P>
Beijing also plans to set up a dozen sewage plants in
its suburban counties to facilitate purification.
</P>
<P>
"By the year 2010, more than 90 percent of the city's domestic
and industrial water will be treated before being discharged into
the Bohai Bay," said an official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
