<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Promises Measures to Protect Jewish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu cut short his holiday in the north Friday after
a Jewish settler was killed in Hebron, vowing to "do everything
possible" to protect Jewish settlers, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio reports said that Netanyahu will confer with his
security and intelligence advisers to discuss ways to strengthen
security measures in the Jewish neighborhood in the West Bank of
Hebron, where a 63-year-old rabbi was stabbed to death Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu added that he would "vehemently" demand that the
Palestinian National Authority fulfill their obligations to fight
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister was on his summer vacation in the northern
city of Tiberias.
</P>
<P>
The stabbing incident was the second of the type in less than a
month. Two Jewish settlers were ambushed and killed on August 4 in
a settlement near another West Bank town of Nablus.
</P>
<P>
Settlement leaders and some right-wing parliamentary members,
criticizing the government for not doing enough to protect Jewish
settlers, urged Netanyahu to halt the talks with the Palestinians
on the overdue Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Environment Minister Rafael Eitan called on the government
Friday to enlarge the Jewish neighborhood where the murdered
rabbi lived.
</P>
<P>
Following the death of the two Jewish settlers in the
settlement of Yitzhar earlier this month, the Israeli cabinet
decided to enlarge the settlement.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers have beefed up security measures along the
way from Hebron to Jerusalem along which the slain settler would
be brought for burial.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli soldiers bolstered the security in the Old
City of East Jerusalem in an effort to prevent any disturbance as
the Palestinians were planning a mass prayer ceremony on the
afternoon to mark the 29th anniversary of an arson attack on
Al-Aqsa Mosque.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that Israeli border policemen succeeded
in holding back about 100 Palestinians who tried to cross a
checkpoint in northern Jerusalem to stage a protest against the
burning of Al-Aqsa by an Israeli extremist 29 years ago. The
policemen were attacked by stones and bottles, the radio
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
