<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Develops New Asthma Pill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A new one-pill-a-day treatment
for chronic asthma sufferers is now available in Canada, the Globe
and Mail newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The new drug, produced under the brand name Singulair, reduced
asthma symptoms in half in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
"This is a Canadian success story, scientifically and
economically," said Andre Marcheterre, president of Merck Frosst
Canada Inc. which is marketing the drug.
</P>
<P>
The drug costs 2.06 Canadian dollars (about 1.34 U.S. dollars)
for a 10-milligram adult tablet, and 1.40 Canadian dollars (about
90 cents) for a five-milligram cherry-flavored chewable children's
dose.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.8 million Canadians suffer from the inflammatory
disease of the lungs and trachea; one-third of them are children.
</P>
<P>
Asthma is a major public-health problem. It kills 10 Canadians
a week and costs the health-care system more than 600 million
Canadian dollars (390 million U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
Asthma afflicts 150 million people around the world and is
increasing by as much as 50 per cent every 10 years, said the
newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
