<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Introduce Plan to End Yellow River Water Shortages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese hydropower experts
contend that power generated in southern China can help to
alleviate seasonal water shortages along the Yellow River in the
northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Water shortages have for many years interrupted the flow water
in many sections of the Yellow River during the dry season and
have had a detrimental impact on life and production in northern
China.
</P>
<P>
Liu Junfeng, general manager of the Ertan Hydropower
Development Corp. recently suggested that Yellow River power
stations should concentrate on storing water during the rainy
season, while Yangtze River power stations in the south should
transmit power to fulfill demand in the north.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Yellow River facilities would then be able to
dischange water during the dry season.
</P>
<P>
Liu's concept is supported by the massive plan to build dozens
of large power stations in the upper reaches of the Yangtze and
the Three Gorges Water Conservation Project which is under
construction in the middle reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
The first of the six 550,000-kw generating units of the Ertan
Hydropower Station, the largest water conservation project
scheduled for completion during this century, went on line last
week on the Yalong River, a Yangtze tributary.
</P>
<P>
A previous plan to divert abundant water from the south to the
north involved individual project costs of several hundred billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Liu's calculations indicate that each 100 million kwh of power
transmitted from the south during the flood season would add 10
billion cu.m. of water to the current Yellow River water level. He
also noted that a power transmission network could be completed at
a cost of several billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
"The key to the plan centers on establishing a national power
transmission network free of regional economic barriers," said
Liu, a water conservation expert with 30 years of experience.
</P>
<P>
The plan has attracted wide-spread attention and related
departments are preparing to conduct related studies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third Flood Crest Arrives in Harbin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- No major damage was reported
today when the third flood crest along the Nenjiang River arrived
in Harbin, the largest heavy industrial center in northeast China,
at noon today.
</P>
<P>
The water level hit 120.82 meters, 2.72 meters above the danger
level and 0.77 meters above the 1957 record. The city also
recorded a record flow rate of 17,400 cu.m. per second.
</P>
<P>
Levees surrounding Harbin, considered to be the best in
Heilongjiang Province, are designed to withstand 100-year
floods. Nonetheless, sandbags were the last major defense against
flood waters which rose one meter above the tops of
levees. Surging waters in the Songhua River seeped through the
primary and secondary embankments, with water levels as 20
centimeters covering many streets. Soldiers used plastic bowls
throw seepage water back into the river.
</P>
<P>
More than 300,000 soldiers and civilians battled surging water
by placing sandbags atop levees.
</P>
<P>
Banners bearing slogans such as "Defend levees to the death"
and "Protecting Harbin requires a life or death struggle" hung
from trees near the levees.
</P>
<P>
Streets near the Songhua River were filled with trucks hauling
plastic bags and stone to workers on Songhua River levees.
</P>
<P>
Volunteers supplied weary workers with food, including stuffed
buns, gruel and green beans, considered to provide relief from
the summer heat.
</P>
<P>
Daily life and production essentially continues as normal in
Harbin, a city located in close proximity to both the Songhua and
Nenjiang rivers, according to Luan Fang, general manager of a
local commercial center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
