<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Consumer Price Inflation Keeps Easing in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Consumer price inflation
maintained its easing trend in Hong Kong in July 1998, according
to the Consumer Price Index (CPI) figures released by the Census
and Statistics Department Friday.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year rate of increase in the Composite CPI was 3.2
percent in July, significantly lower than the 4 percent in June.
It was also the lowest monthly figure recorded since September
1986.
</P>
<P>
The lower year-on-year rates of increase in the CPI in July
than in June were mainly attributable to a decline in food prices
from a year earlier and to the continuing easing in private
housing rentals. In addition, the lower year-on-year rate of
increase in the prices of miscellaneous goods also contributed.
</P>
<P>
Analyzed by component, lower year-on-year rates of increase
than the overall average in July were recorded for durable goods
(0.7 percent in both the Composite CPI and CPI(A)); clothing and
footwear (1.2 percent in the Composite CPI and 2.1 percent in the
CPI(A)); meals bought away from home (1.9 percent in the Composite
CPI and 2.1 percent in the CPI(A)); and fuel and light (2 percent
in the Composite CPI and 1.6 percent in the CPI(A)).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prices of food (excluding meals bought away from
home) declined by 2.3 percent in the Composite CPI and 3.1 percent
in the CPI(A) in July over a year earlier, as the higher vegetable
prices in the summer of 1997 renders a higher base of comparison.
</P>
<P>
Taking the first seven months of 1998 together, the increase in
the Composite CPI averaged at 4.5 percent over the same period of
1997. The corresponding increases for the CPI(A), CPI(B) and Hang
Seng CPI were 4.2 percent, 4.5 percent and 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
For the 12 months ended July 1998, the Composite CPI was, on
average, 5 percent higher than that for the preceding 12-month
period.
</P>
<P>
Monthly consumer price indices are compiled on the basis of
expenditure patterns of relevant households and prices collected
currently in the month.
</P>
<P>
The CPI(A) is based on the expenditure pattern of about 50
percent of households in Hong Kong, which had an average monthly
expenditure of 4,000-15,999 HK dollars in 1994/95 (broadly
equivalent to 4,600-18,200 HK dollars at 1997 prices). The CPI(B)
is based on the expenditure pattern of the next 30 percent of
households, which had an average monthly expenditure of
16,000-29,999 HK dollars in 1994/95 (broadly equivalent to
18,200-34,600 HK dollars at 1997 prices). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
