<HEADLINE> Experts Share Insight Into Innovation, Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Chief Executive's
Commission on Innovation and Technology organized a workshop here
Friday on strengthening Hong Kong's technological infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Professor Chang-Lin Tien, the Commission's chairman, chaired
the three-hour workshop, at which four guest speakers made
presentations on the relationship between technological innovation
and industrial development in different economies.
</P>
<P>
Deng Nan, vice-minister of science and technology of China,
delivered a speech entitled "Science and technology: the key to
success in the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
She said the Chinese government has attached great importance
to innovation, which is the soul of a nation and the most critical
factor for a country's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Looking into the next century, China starts to build its own
innovation system, in which enterprises constitute the kernel and
driving force, and research institutions, intermediate agencies
and government play supporting roles, according to the
vice-minister.
</P>
<P>
Ji Fusheng, an official from the Chinese Ministry of Science
and Technology, spoke of the rapid development of information
technology in China and enormous opportunities it will bring to
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Professor C C Hang, deputy vice-chancellor of National
University of Singapore, shared with other participants insight
into the city state's strategies for strengthening the national
technological infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Shih Chin Tay, president of Industrial Technology Research
Institute of Taiwan, talked about the experience of Taiwan in
developing high-technology industry.
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, Professor Tien hoped that Hong Kong can draw
experience from other regions in mapping out its own development
strategies in technological innovation.
</P>
<P>
The commission, appointed by Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa in
March 1998, is now preparing an interim report to advise the
Special Administrative Region (SAR) government on policies related
to technology and industry.
</P>
<P>
The commission will submit the interim report to the chief
executive in September this year and to complete a final report no
later than June 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
