<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Offers Special Fund To Rescue Rare Monkeys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Finance has
decided to offer Deqin County, home of the Yunnan snub-nosed
monkey, an additional 3 million yuan (360,000 U.S. dollars) each
year to protect these endangered monkeys with human-like faces.
</P>
<P>
Before this decision, southwest China's Yunnan Province was
providing 8 million yuan (966.000 U.S.dollars) a year for the
monkeys in Deqin County.
</P>
<P>
So these monkeys have now become the lucky rare wild animal
enjoying top preferential treatment among other species of rare
wild animals in China.
</P>
<P>
A recent investigation reports that there are now only about
1,000 Yunnan snub-nosed monkeys in the world, and these live in 13
groups in the four Yunnan counties bordering the Tibet
Autonomous Region. Around 700 live in Deqin County.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that the preservation of the Yunnan snub-nosed
monkey in Deqin County is of great importance for the protection
of this endengered species.
</P>
<P>
An adult male monkey usually weighs over 20 kilograms and the
female is usually about half that weight.
</P>
<P>
The most striking feature of the monkeys is their slightly pink
face and red lips, most other monkeys have a red face.
</P>
<P>
Experts say fewer than 10 Chinese and foreign zoologists have
ever spotted Yunnan snub-nosed monkeys in the wild.
</P>
<P>
Zoologists believe that the study of the Yunnan snub-nosed
monkey may be of great importance to the study of species
evolution.
</P>
<P>
Since Deqin County is one of the poorest areas in China,
farmers often fell trees to sell and use for cooking. The
felling of the trees breaks the monkeys' food chain resulting
in a reduction of their number.
</P>
<P>
A 190,000-hectare nature reserve for the monkeys has been
established in Deqin County. It covers one-fifth of the county's
total area, and felling trees or hunting in this forests has
already been banned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Visitor Arrivals in July Show Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Visitor arrivals to Hong Kong
in July increased, for the first time this year, by 26.5 percent
compared with the figure for July 1997, according to figures
released by the Hong Kong Tourist Association (HKTA) here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Total arrivals for the month were 832,664, about 86,000 more
than the June figure and the biggest monthly total since last
December.
</P>
<P>
The highest increase in arrivals, by 150.8 percent, was
recorded from the Chinese mainland. This was due partly to the 30
percent increase in the tour group quota, which came into effect
on July 1 this year, the HKTA said.
</P>
<P>
Most other market regions also showed growth in July, with
arrivals from Australia, New Zealand and the South Pacific
combined up by 23.9 percent. Those from the Americas were up by
18.7 percent, from Europe, Africa and the Middle East combined up
by 11.8, and from Taiwan also up by 11.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Encouragingly, Japan arrivals increased by 11.7 percent, the
HKTA said.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from South and Southeast Asia fell by 16.6 percent.
Arrivals also fell by a large margin from the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Individual markets showing good growth in July included the
United Kingdom (up 37.6 percent), Canada (up 28.7 percent) and New
Zealand (up 25.6 percent). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Mainland Remains HK's Largest Re-export Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese mainland remains
the largest partner for Hong Kong's re-export trade, according to
re-export statistics for the first half of 1998 released by the
Census and Statistics Department of Hong Kong Friday.
</P>
<P>
Re-exports originating from the Chinese mainland accounted for
58 percent of Hong Kong's re-export value in the period.
</P>
<P>
Taking the two directions of trade flow as a whole but counting
only once the value of merchandises originating from and
re-exported back to the Chinese mainland, about 90 percent, or
510.7 billion HK dollars (65.5 billion U.S. dollars), of the total
re-exports going through Hong Kong in the first half of 1998 were
related to the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
It was noted that much of the re-export trade involving the
Chinese mainland is related to outward processing, as raw
materials and semi-manufactured goods are exported to the mainland
for processing, with the final products subsequently returned to
Hong Kong and then re-exported to overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
Re-exports accounted for 86 percent of the value of total
exports and 41 percent of the total value of external trade of
Hong Kong in the first half of 1998, according to the figures.
</P>
<P>
In the same period of 1997, the corresponding shares were
broadly similar, at 86 percent and 40 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Other main origins of Hong Kong's re-exports in the first half
of the year included Japan (11 percent), Taiwan (6.4 percent), the
United States (4.8 percent) and the Republic of Korea (3.5
percent).
</P>
<P>
The other main destinations included the United States (21
percent), Japan (5.5 percent), Germany (3.6 percent) and the
United Kingdom (3.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
Analyzed by commodity, increases in the value of re-exports to
the Chinese mainland were recorded for telecommunications, sound
recording and reproducing apparatus and equipment (by 26 percent);
cork and wood (by 57 percent); and photographic apparatus,
equipment and supplies, optical goods, watches and clocks (by 13
percent).
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, decreases in the value of re-exports to the
Chinese mainland were recorded for textiles (by 6 percent) and for
petroleum, petroleum products and related materials (by 16
percent). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
