<HEADLINE> Japan Trading House Goes Bankrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Tokyo District Court declared
on Friday that Okura and Company, a medium-sized Japanese trading
house, is bankrupt. This is the country's third largest corporate
failure in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Okura filed for bankruptcy with 288.3 billion yen (about 2.1
billion U.S. dollars) in group liabilities early in the day.
</P>
<P>
The trading house, listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange's First
Section, is the fourth listed Japanese company to go bankrupt this
year.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the bankruptcy at a press conference, Okura
President Yoshihiko Okura attributed his company's failure to
mountains of nonperforming real estate assets as a result of
aggressive real estate investment made during the bubble economy
of the late 1980s and difficulties in raising funds through bank
loans.
</P>
<P>
The company had 98 billion yen (about 68 million dollars) in
nonperforming assets, including those held by group companies, or
about one-third of their total assets in the last business year,
which ended March 31, Okura said.
</P>
<P>
According to private credit research agency Teikoku Databank,
the collapse of the bubble economy left Okura with huge investment
losses, forcing it into the red during the last six years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
