<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Soldiers Killed, Lebanese Civilian Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese civilian was wounded
by Israeli retaliatory bombardment on villages of south Lebanon
Friday after two Israelis were killed by guerrillas overnight, the
Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Amin Nadar, 70, was wounded by shrapnel of shells which
were fired by Israeli artillery troops onto the village of Arab
Salim in the Iqlim al Tuffah area facing the Israeli occupied
south Lebanon, a stronghold of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or
Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes raided the village of Agmeta and Tale Imliti
in the same area and fired air-to-surface missiles onto the
villages.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen Lebanese civilians have been killed and 72 others
wounded in south Lebanon so far this year in the clashes between
Israeli forces and Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli attacks came apparently as a retaliatory action
against a Hezbollah bomb blast which killed an Israeli soldier and
a construction worker on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The remote-controlled bomb set off when the car carrying the
victims was passing at Golea Shqif village in the edge of the
Israeli occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The deadly blast brought to 12 the number of the Israelis
killed in south Lebanon since the start of this year while 76
others were wounded during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Following the attack, Israeli senior army officials, including
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, Army Chief of Staff Shaul
Mofaz and northern front commander Lt. Gen. Ghabi Ashkinazi, held
an emergency meeting to assess the situation in south Lebanon and
its impact on Israel, the radio quoted Israeli media reports as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The new events came one day after Israeli Public Security
Minister Avigdor Kahalani threatened to strike Lebanon's
infrastructure facilities each time an Israeli soldier was killed
in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said that could force the Lebanese government to deploy army
on the borders to maintain security and prevent guerrillas from
using the south as a base to attack Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer self-declared
security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to protect its north from
cross-border attack by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Hezbollah has been fighting against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Heavy losses Israeli forces suffered in the south have sparked
heated debate in Israel over the value of continuing military
presence in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In April, Israeli cabinet endorsed the 20-year-old United
Nations 425 but conditioned the implementation of it on the
Beirut government guarantees for Israeli north security.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon flatly rejected the offer and demanded Israel leave its
south without any conditions as the resolution stipulated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
