<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nenjiang River Flood Threatens More Daqing Oil Wells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAQING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The swollen Nenjiang River has
inundated 1,443 oil wells in Daqing, China's largest oilfield, and
production in 282 wells has been suspended since August 12.
</P>
<P>
 The production breakdown has affected 13,455 tons of oil
output. The amount of crude oil transported out of Daqing,
however, has been steadily increasing. On Thursday, 154,626 tons
of oil was sent out, a relatively high daily transport.
</P>
<P>
Production in other oil wells here remain under pressure as
more roads and railways have been damaged by floodwater. Vehicles
loaded with oil exploration materials have had to take detours of
hundreds of kilometers in order to reach wells in Hailar and
Bei'an.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 oil wells under the No.4 Oil Exploration Plant
are now operating in water.
</P>
<P>
Oilmen in Daqing, which produces a third of China's crude
oil, are doing their utmost to maintain normal production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
