<HEADLINE> Iran Condemns U.S. Raids on Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Friday condemned the
United States for its attack on Sudan Thursday, terming it as a
move violating Sudan's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Tehran radio quoted the Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud
Mohammadi as saying that the U.S. raid on a Sudanese factory was a
measure against the Sudanese people and "we condemn it."
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi stated that Iran always condemns terrorists. However,
he said, no event could be used as a pretext for the U.S. to do
what it likes and to attack the Islamic lands.
</P>
<P>
He expressed regret that innocent people of Sudan and
Afghanistan were killed during the U.S. attacks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton ordered the military strikes on
alleged terrorists' bases or facilities in Sudan and Afghanistan
simultaneously Thursday, in retaliation for the explosions of
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the U.S. attack on a base of the Saudi dissident
Osma bin Laden in Afghanistan, the spokesman said that what
happened in Afghanistan was the result of the U.S. double standard
policy towards terrorism.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. police has helped create a suitable
circumstance for the growth of terrorism throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that anywhere the U.S. interest is threatened,
the Americans would react strongly, but anywhere others' interest
is threatened, their reaction would be another kind and even help
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that to fight against terrorism is possible only
through a clear and comprehensive international cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
