<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt Approves 2,400 Registered Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Federal Government has
approved 2,403 products as fit for human consumption, The Post
Express reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Out of the products registered by the National Agency for Food
and Drug Administration and Control (NAFDAC), 984 are human drug
products, 802 food products, 484 cosmetic products and 24
veterinary drug products, according to a government gazette.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted NAFDAC Director General Gabriel Osuide as
saying Thursday in Abuja, capital of Nigeria, that it was now
mandatory that such medicines, foods, drugs, chemicals and
packaged water products should have their NAFDAC registration
number printed on their labels.
</P>
<P>
By an agreement reached between the agency and the
manufacturers, he said, the registration number should be
progressively printed on the labels.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the registration number would guide consumers
and give them the assurance that the products they buy are
genuine and legal in the market.
</P>
<P>
The agency's main instrument of protecting public health is
product registration, Osuide said, adding that "in this way,
every manufacturer or importer of processed food, medicine,
cosmetics or packaged water, intended for Nigerian market, is by
law, required to register such product with the agency, before
the product can be lawfully manufactured, imported, distributed
or sold in the country."
</P>
<P>
Before a product can be accorded registration, he noted, it
must meet the requirement of documentation, evaluation of the
documents, analysis of sample of product before a registration
number is allocated to it.
</P>
<P>
This is the second approval of registered products in the West
African country since last year when the gazette listed 1,805
products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
