<HEADLINE> China to Build World's Highest Concave-Shaped Dam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- China has announced plans to
build the world's highest concave-faced dam, a Chinese official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The 325-meter high dam will be part the Jinping Hydro-Electric
power Station scheduled for construction along the Yalong River in
Sichuan Province, said Liu Junfeng, general manager of the Ertan
Hydro-Electric Power Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The structure, the highest dam of its kind in the world, will
fall 10 meters short of the height for a different style dam in
Russia, but the Russian dam is an earth and stone dam, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Jinping facility will have a designed capacity of 3.6
million kW and is one of 21 power stations planned for the Yalong
River. The design of the structure is scheduled for completion in
the year 2000, he added.
</P>
<P>
The first 550,000-KW generating unit of the Ertan
Hydro-Electric Power Station, with a designed capacity of 3.3
million kW, went on line on a trial base last week. The station
will be the largest hydropower project completed in China during
this century. The 240-meter high dam of the station is currently
the country's highest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Currency Stabilizes for Six Weeks Running </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian ctprency Kwacha has
relatively stabilized for six weeks running against the U.S.
Dollar as a result of 3.5 million Dollar supplied on the market
by the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) during the week
ending August 17.
</P>
<P>
And it is anticipated that the exchange rate of the Kwacha
against Dollar will remain static and the Zambian currency may
even appreciate slightly by the end of this month, Zambia Daily
Mail said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The latest weekly Treasury Newsletter of the Barclays Bank
indicated that banks counter rates are now in the range of
1920-1930 Kwacha and 1970-1975 Kwacha for buying and selling
respectively, compared to 1910-1925 Kwacha and 1965-1972 Kwacha
in the week ending July 20.
</P>
<P>
The Kwacha has in the recent months suffered a great deal from
the shortage of foreign exchange which pushed up demand and
eventually eroded the purchasing power of the local currency.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the situation is still not very good despite the
few Dollars that are now being offloaded on the market by ZCCM, the
traditional and biggest foreign exchange earner.
</P>
<P>
Donor inflows are still a pipedream as donors are reluctant to
release their pledged aid amounting to 5.3 billion Dollars until
the privatization of the ZCCM.
</P>
<P>
Inflows from donors to Zambia's central bank as at June 26
were nil with which the need to service the external debt
deprived the country of the much needed foreign exchange,
resulting in the erosion of the Kwacha's purchasing power and
sending inflation rates higher.
</P>
<P>
The Kwacha has this year depreciated by approximately 37
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
