<HEADLINE> URGENT: Former S. African President Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Former South African state
President Pieter Willem Botha was Friday sentenced to a fine of
10,000 Rand (1,600 U.S. dollars) or 12 months' imprisonment for
snubbing a subpoena of the Truth and Reconciliation Commission
(TRC), South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Handing down the sentence, George magistrate Victor Lugaju
said Botha at 82 was not in good health and was a first offender.
</P>
<P>
However, throughout the trial he had shown no remorse and had
been granted ample opportunity to resolve the matter amicably,
but had not done so.
</P>
<P>
Lugaju said the mitigating factors in this instance far
outweighed the aggravating factors, and he considered the
sentence to be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
He also sentenced Botha to a further 12 months' imprisonment,
suspended for five years. 
</P>
