<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Share Prices gyrated from
negative to positive territory on Singapore Stock Market Friday as
the benchmark Straits Times Industrial Index gained 10.3 points to
 end at 933.16 after moving on a downward slope for a week.
</P>
<P>
The total volume contracted to 189.13 million units worth
202.16 million Singapore dollars (about 115.52 million U.S.
dollars). Declines outnumbered advances by 202 to 91 with 296
issues unchanged.
</P>
<P>
M Res was the most active stock of the day with a turnover of
18.62 million units. It was followed by NBT which had 13.99
million stocks traded. MBF Cap was next with 13.76 million
counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 remained the top gainer of the day as it gained 1.2
Singapore dollars to end at 20.5 Singapore dollars. SPH edged up
20 cents to finish at 12.6 Singapore dollars. C &AMP; C inched up 16
cents to close at 3.32 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Genting was the biggest loser of the day as
it lost 36 cents to end at 3.18 Singapore dollars. Boustd S shed
30 cents to 1.2 Singapore dollars at close. Robinson also fell by
30 cents to end at 4.2 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said stocks ended higher on late buying of largely
property counters amid speculation about interest cut although
broad market once drifted lower in the day on light profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
Select shares picked up on rumors that the Development Bank of
Singapore (DBS) would lower its prime lending rate, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
But DBS said there was no such an announcement at present. The
average prime lending rate of Singapore's big four banks is now
7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Brokers noted that investors seemed to pay no attention to the
news that the United States carried out missile attacks overnight
on alleged terrorist bases in Afghanistan and Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
