<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. Africa Starts to Build Regional Road Networks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda, the
three members of the East African Cooperation, have started to
re-build the battered regional road networks with 62 billion
Shillings (some 1.04 billion U.S. Dollars) from foreign donors.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank and the European Union have agreed to offer the
money to help uplift the region's devastated infrastructure that
had been rendered almost worthless by the El Nino rains and lack
of maintenance, media here reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A report from the EAC secretariat based in the northern
Tanzanian town of Arusha said five major regional road corridors
and their feeder links, which connect most parts of the region,
have been identified for repair.
</P>
<P>
The move "intends to promote the regional trade and
investment, provide the required competitiveness to the regional
products through the reduction of transportation cost and
enhancing the overall transport safety," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The corridors, noted the 62-page report, also provides
required linkages and connectivity to areas of production,
markets and other modes of transport such as sea ports, railway
and airports.
</P>
<P>
Tourism in Kenya has also taken a back seat due to the
dilapidated road network.
</P>
<P>
As a result of politics and poor infrastructure, in 1997
earnings from the sector dropped from 24 billion Shillings in
1996 to 22 billion Shillings last year.
</P>
<P>
The cost of vehicle maintenance has increased threefold as
vehicles degenerate rapidly on the poor roads. Transport costs
have skyrocketed - pushing up prices of foodstuff and other
essential commodities.
</P>
<P>
The surface conditions of the targeted road networks are
generally poor. Those unpaved account for 8,668 km while paved
measures 6,605 km only, said the report.
</P>
<P>
To improve the region's road network to desirable standards
for trade, a total of 4,674 million Dollars will be required in
the next five years, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, says the EAC secretariat in the report,
rehabilitation of the sections of the Mombasa-Malaba road and its
branches will provide the quality of infrastructure necessary to
support Kenya's overall economy strategy.
</P>
<P>
The Mombasa-Malaba road is one of the most heavily trafficked
routes in Kenya - and the most battered - serving both domestic
and international traffic to and from Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi and
Zaire. Experts consider the road as one of the engines of EAC
transport network.
</P>
<P>
In Uganda, a joint task force set up to formulate an EAC
Development strategy on surface transport (1997-2000) identified
the Sironko-Namalu-Morinka-Moroto-Kenya border road as one of the
important feeder road linking to the whole region.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, the EAC secretariat will concentrate on the
232-km-long Mwanza-Biharamulo road which is part of the country's
national trunk road network.
</P>
<P>
The Lake Victoria circuit road network is given top priority
due to its strategic location. The secretariat expects its
rehabilitation will help boost agricultural production around the
lake region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
