<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Leader Calls for Research Despite Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B. J.
Habibie said Friday that research and technology development
activities should go on despite the current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Although we are facing heavy economic problems, research and
technology development activities must continue," the president
said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 20th anniversary celebration of the Agency for
Assessment and Application of Technology (BPPT) here, Habibie
stressed that it is important for a nation to have mastery of
technology to enable it to become equal with other nations.
</P>
<P>
"We realize that investments in research are very costly --
almost similar to investments in human resources. But I must
convince you that such investments will not go to waste," he said.
</P>
<P>
Returns would even be greater than the amount of investment,
said Habibie, who had chaired the agency for almost 20 years
before he became vice president in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Habibie became the country's president after former President
Soeharto resigned on May 21.
</P>
<P>
The president also stressed the importance of research in
solving present and future problems.
</P>
<P>
He further reminded BPPT researchers that the people need
technology to build low-cost houses and increase food production.
</P>
</TEXT>
