<HEADLINE> Romania's Economy Could Be Affected by Crisis in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The impact of the Russia's
financial crisis will be felt sooner or later by Romania's
economy, and the devaluation of the Russian ruble will cause
foreign capital to a flee from not only Russia but also
neighboring markets, the local daily Nine O'clock reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Analyzing the crisis in Russia and its impact on Romania's
capital market, Viorel Pana, a senator and director of the
Bucharest Stock Exchange, was quoted as saying that "the financial
crisis in Russia makes us approach a subject of utmost importance
regarding the domestic economy and the increase in Romania's
country risk rating in an international context which is not
favorable at all."
</P>
<P>
"Under these circumstances, a crisis of the magnitude witnessed
by Russia could not but have some repercussion on Romania's
economy; Also, since Western Europe is more scared of the Russian
than the Asian crisis in autumn," Pana said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pana proposed some solutions to avoiding the
aftershock of the Russian crisis, which included speeding up
privatization and restructuring, and dropping the 1.5 percent tax
on foreign investments in Romania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
