<HEADLINE> Chinese President Postpones September Visits to Russia, Japan-1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
scheduled visits to Russia and Japan in early September have been
postponed due to the immensity of the flood control and disaster
relief efforts in China.
</P>
<P>
The timetable for the visits will be rescheduled through
diplomatic channels between China and the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan informed Russian
ambassador Igor Rogachev and Japanese ambassador Sakutaro Tanino
of this decision during separate meetings with them here this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Tang also asked the two ambassadors to convey President Jiang's
letters explaining the postponements to Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings, Tang said that this summer, China has
continued to suffer from the most severe flooding of the Yangtze,
Songhua, and Nenjiang rivers since the founding of the People's
Republic of China in 1949. The flooding has inundated vast
regions, affected large numbers of people, and has lasted a very
long time, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that after two months, the disaster has still not
eased and in some regions the situation is deteriorating. The
floods are imposing serious threats to the life and property of
the people in the disaster-stricken regions, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Millions of Chinese service men and civilians are fighting
against the flood, Tang said, adding that China is fully confident
that, under the leadership of the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee with Jiang Zemin at the core, China can overcome the
difficulties and the disaster.
</P>
<P>
At present, however, it is necessary for President Jiang Zemin
to remain in the country to supervise the pressing flood fighting
and disaster relief efforts, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
After careful consideration, it was decided that President Jiang
put off his visits to Russia and Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
