<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Defense Force Leans Toward Opposition: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The commander of the
Lesotho Defense Force Thursday moved to allay rumblings within
the ranks of the army amid indications that the government was
losing the support of the military, The Star daily reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant-General Makhula Mosakeng, who has been accused of
involvement in corruption and the alleged rigging of the May 23
general election, urged members of the army to be wary of reports
aimed at "sowing confusion within the ranks of the army and
creating distrust of the leadership", said the paper.
</P>
<P>
This came after claims surfaced that senior government
officials had bought a farm for Mosakeng at Ladybrand in South
Africa's Free State province.
</P>
<P>
The farm was allegedly bought with funds from the army's
secret security fund to which Mosakeng, Prime Minister Pakalitha
Mosisili and Foreign Minister Tom Thabane are the only
signatories.
</P>
<P>
In a circular read verbatim on state-owned Radio Lesotho,
Mosakeng admitted that the farm had been bought but said it was
for the army's "breeding purposes".
</P>
<P>
Mosakeng's move came a day after signs that the army was
beginning to sympathize with opposition parties which had staged
a three-week day and night vigil outside King Letsie III's
palace, demanding the dissolution of the government.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted observers as saying that Mosakeng, as head of
military intelligence, had been compromised by claims that he was
also involved in the electoral fraud.
</P>
<P>
The army's intelligence unit is said to have played a pivotal
role in arranging logistics for the election.
</P>
<P>
Aspects of these logistics, particularly the voters' roll,
have been found to have been manipulated.
</P>
<P>
A South African forensic company, OF&AMP;A, has said the voters'
roll was not a legit and accurate document and therefore would
fail as a control measure for a free and fair democratic
election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
