<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reserve Bank of India Acts to Check Fall of Rupee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) took steps Thursday to check the free fall of the country's
currency, the rupee, and curb excessive speculation, including
hikes in the cash reserve ratio and in repo rates.
</P>
<P>
The measures included an increase in the cash reserve ratio
from 10 to 11 percent, a three percentage point rise in its daily
fixed repo rate and steps to curb speculation by importers,
according to press reports here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The measures were taken at a time when the rupee had plunged to
a historical low of 43.7 against the U.S. dollar in mid-day trade
Wednesday, largely reacting to a slew of external factors as well
as statements by Commerce Minister R. K. Hegde that there was
further room for the rupee to weaken.
</P>
<P>
The RBI medicine had a prompt impact on the exchange markets
with the rupee recovering to 42.7 for a dollar before closing at
42.8 Thursday, an appreciation of 70 percent over Wednesday's
close.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Times reported Friday that the RBI package has
four distinct strains: sucking out liquidity from the money
market, bumping up the forward premia, discouraging speculation
and inducing further foreign exchange inflows.
</P>
<P>
Attempt to drain out the excess through the increase of cash
reserve ratio, which takes effect on August 29, is expected to
suck out liquidity of over 50 billion rupees (about 1.2 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This, combined with a three percentage point increase in repo
rates from 5 to 8 percent, is expected to push up interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In terms of indirect measures, the RBI announced Thursday that
foreign institutional investors would be allowed to hedge 15
percent of their portfolio investment made before June 11.
</P>
<P>
The bank had earlier only allowed the investors to hedge their
incremental investments made after June 11.
</P>
<P>
The RBI hopes that this would induce foreign institutional
investors to start hedging their outstanding investments, meaning
that they would want to buy dollars forward at current prices to
avoid taking a depreciation hit when they liquidate investments at
a later date.
</P>
<P>
However, market players are skeptical about the efficacy of the
move, given that foreign institutional investors find present
levels of premia unattractive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
