<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghans Protest Against U.S. Missile Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of angry Afghans
took to the streets in southern Afghanistan on Friday morning to
protest against U.S. missile attack on their country, the
Associated Press of Pakistan (APP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The bazaars and shops in the Taliban's southern stronghold of
Kandahar remained closed in protest, Taliban sources were quoted
by the APP as saying.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators chanted slogans against the United States.
The people started gathering at Eidgah Chowk in the heart of the
town and later marched through the streets carrying banners and
Taliban flags.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators ended their march at the starting point of
Eidgah Chowk where a big public meeting was held. The speakers at
the meeting strongly condemned the missile attack on Afghan
territory. They vowed that no power on earth could force them to
hand over Osama bin Laden to the United States. They demanded that
the United Nations ensure that such attacks do not happen again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
