<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Lower in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed lower in Tokyo
Friday on reports that medium-sized trading house Okura and Co. filed
for bankruptcy due to financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell 93.21 points, or 0.61
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 15,298.20.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 5.16 points or 0.44 percent to 1,176.51.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went slightly up to an estimated 360
million shares from Thursday's 352.08 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The overall decline was minimized in part by a surge in banking
shares following news reports that the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan
(LTCB) will restructure itself ahead of a "bailout merger" with
Sumitomo Trust and Banking Co.
</P>
<P>
LTCB was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Okura, a Tokyo-based trading house specializing in steel products
and machinery, became the fourth company listed on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange to file for bankruptcy this year.
</P>
<P>
In reaction, steel shares plunged and firms with close ties to
Okura weakened.
</P>
<P>
But the overall downslide in stocks was apparently limited by
bargain-hungry public fund managers as the Nikkei drifted between
15,226.62 and 15,416.88, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,335 issues listed on the First Section, losers surpassed
gainers 672 to 396, with 213 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
