<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The net profits of Lebanon's biggest bank Banque
Libanaise Pour le Commerce (BLC) rose to 9.3 million U.S. dollars
in the second quarter of this year from 9 million dollars in the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to BLC's balance sheet released Wednesday, the
bank's total assets and liabilities in the second quarter of 1998
stood at 902 million dollars against 785 million dollars in the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
BLC reported a net profit of more than 18 million dollars at
the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Bank officials expect the net profits at the end of 1998 to be
slightly higher than those of last year.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese and Syrian businessmen have announced the
establishment of a joint shareholding corporation with a capital
of 10 million dollars, the Daily Star newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made on Wednesday in Damascus by the
Council of Syrian-Lebanese Businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which is aimed at boosting investment in the
agriculture, industry, tourism and transport, came after the two
countries finally agreed to carry out a four-year-old plan to
remove all customs duties on industrial products from the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The gross foreign reserves of the Lebanese central
bank climbed to 6.3 billion U.S. dollars in the first half of this
month, up around 10 million dollars than the same period of last
month, a bank report said.
</P>
<P>
But it didn't reveal net reserves.
</P>
<P>
Gross foreign currency reserves include deposits of commercial
banks with the central bank.
</P>
<P>
Gross foreign exchange reserves at the end of 1997 stood at 5.9
billion dollars compared with 5.8 billion dollars at the end of
1996.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Petroleum Hamdi Al-Banbi was
quoted in Friday's The Egyptian Gazette as saying that Egypt
produces 50 percent of its wheat crop needs and the target for the
immediate future is to become 75 percent sufficient in wheat
production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
