<HEADLINE> Pakistan Expresses "Indignation" at U.S. Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Friday expressed
"indignation" over U.S. overnight missile attacks on alleged
terrorist facilities in Pakistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. forces Thursday night attacked with cruise missiles
six sites in Afghanistan, located close to the Pakistani border,
which are believed to be the hideouts of anti-American Saudi
millionaire Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz said in a statement read in the
senate that he was not aware of any violation of his country's
airspace. However, "it is being investigated."
</P>
<P>
"Although the cruise missiles fly very low, so far the
government is not aware of any violation, " he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the attack on the sovereign Muslim state of Afghanistan
is a serious matter. "The attack of cruise missiles resulted in
loss of innocent lives, which is a cause of serious concern for
us."
</P>
<P>
The government of Pakistan, he said, "expresses its indignation
over the attacks" no matter what justifications are given.
</P>
<P>
"The people of Pakistan are justifiably outraged over the act,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister, reiterating Pakistan's stance over
international terrorism, said, "Pakistan is against terrorism. It
has been a victim of terrorism including state-sponsored
terrorism."
</P>
<P>
He said like in the past Pakistan will continue to support the
cause of fighting international terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
