<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Reopen Aquino-Galman Double Murder Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Joseph Estrada administration
Friday expressed willingness to reopen the Aquino-Galman double
murder case if a crony of the late President Ferdinand Marcos can
provide new evidence to the case.
</P>
<P>
In a press briefing, presidential spokesman Fernando Barican
told reporters that it has been the judicial practice not only in
the Philippines but in other countries that cases are reopened
whenever new evidence providing a new twist is presented.
</P>
<P>
Opposition senators Benigno Aquino and Rolando Galman were
killed on August 21, 1983, at Manila International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The assassination and disgruntlement against the government led
to a popular revolt in February 1983, in which the then President
Marcos was unseated and went into exile in the United States.
Aquino's wife, Corazon Aquino, succeeded Marcos as the president.
</P>
<P>
Marcos' crony, former Chief of Staff of the Armed Forces
General Fabian Ver, has reportedly applied for approval to return
to the Philippines and agreed to tell the truth about Aquino's
death.
</P>
<P>
"If there are new facts... then the Philippine government will
do that at the appropriate time," Barican said, responding to
queries on the possible reopening of the case.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada had already said his administration
will not block Ver from returning to the country, but added that
Ver will have to face the criminal charges filed against him.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, some local government officials gathered here
to mark the 15th death anniversary of Senator Aquino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
