<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Lowers Cash Ratio, Targeting High Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya (CBK)
has decided to reduce the average monthly cash ratio deposits by
financial institutions from 14 percent to 13 percent with
effective from September 1.
</P>
<P>
The reduction aimed at lowering current high interest rates
charged by the financial bodies, according to a CBK circular to
commercial banks and non-bank financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The circular also announced that the daily minimum cash ratio
deposits has equally been lowered to 10 percent from 11 percent
in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time the government is reducing the cash
ratio since the 1998/99 (July/June) budget was announced on June
11. Prior to the budget reading, the ratio stood at 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
The move also comes as part of the governmental efforts to
bring down prevailing high interest rates which tends to stifle
private sector borrowing and investment, analysts said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The interest rates have been blamed on heavy government
borrowing in recent years through the use of the Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has since June announced a series of
measures to curb the interest rates and restructure the huge
domestic debt, including the introduction of a two-year floating
rate bond and the reduction of cash ratios. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
