<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Community Service Center Serves Senior Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Retired doctors Li Suqing and
Huang Yunliang recently expressed delight with the unexpectedly
high quality of services and facilities offered by the Sunshine
Project, a new apartment complex for the aged.
</P>
<P>
The Community Service Center in Beijing's Dongcheng District
invited 500 elderly citizens, including Li and Huang, to spend a
week at the facility prior to the formal opening.
</P>
<P>
The center offers air conditioned apartments with
well-appointed bathrooms and other essential facilities, as well
as ample lighting.
</P>
<P>
Ren Aijun, an official with the Dongcheng District Civil
Affairs Bureau, said the center will open formally after all
invited guests have completed their one week visit.
</P>
<P>
Senior citizens are welcome to apply for apartments regardless
of how long they plan to live in the facility, said Ren.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for two years ago show that senior citizens aged 60
and above accounted for 13.13 percent of Beijing's total
population, with 272 homes for the aged in place by the end of
last year, according to today's edition of China Youth Daily.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of beds and other facilities in local homes for
senior citizens constitutes a major problem for fulfilling the
different needs of senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
The Sunshine Project enables elderly people to select
entertainment programs and find friends with similar
interests. The center offers chess and card rooms, calligraphy and
painting programs, a rehabilitation center and a school for senior
citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
