<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Backs U.S. Attacks on Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has expressed his strong support for the U.S. actions on
Thursday night against terrorists in both Afghanistan and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the President's Office Friday
morning said that as a regular victim of terrorism, Uganda
supports U.S. warplanes' operations and expresses gratification
at American attacks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright informed Museveni
of their actions in a telephone talk Thursday night, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
But it did not say the call was before or after U.S. planes
attacked their targets in Khartoum and a terrorist site 94 miles
(150 kms) south of the Afghanistan capital, Kabul.
</P>
<P>
She told Museveni those sites accommodated factories that make
explosives with which the terrorists make bombs and it is those
bombs that they use to carry out criminal and terrorist attacks
like the recent ones in Nairobi and Dar-es-Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said Uganda does not have diplomatic relations with
Sudan because of its terrorist behavior. He accuses Khartoum of
backing rebels of Lord's Resistance Army to fight against his
administration and to kill and abduct civilians.
</P>
<P>
The air strikes, carried out at 8:30 p.m. East African
Standard Time, were approved by U.S. President Bill Clinton who
said he had compelling information to prove the terrorists are
behind the east African bombings on U.S. embassies.
</P>
<P>
CNN reported that American citizens are divided over this
surprise attack. Some back Clinton's decision while many others
accuse him of putting U.S. citizens abroad at more risky
situation by these attacks and of using these attacks to divert
attention away from his sex scandal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
