<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grenade Man Identified in Nairobi, Two More Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The man who hurled a grenade at
security guards at the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi seconds before the
deadly bomb exploded on August 7 has been positively identified
as two more people arrested, Kenya's national newspapers said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Khalid Mohammed, a suspect held by the Kenyan-U.S. joint probe
team following the bomb raid, was picked out by three of eight
witnesses Thursday, according to a report from the Daily Nation
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The report said it now appears that only two suicide bombers
died in the blast, compared with earlier reports that all the
three bombers who drove to the embassy died.
</P>
<P>
"The man who was positively identified was slightly injured by
the August 7 blast but he escaped with minor wounds which have
healed. This is the man who jumped from the pick-up at the
parking bay of the embassy, hurled a grenade at the guards before
the bomb exploded," the report quoted a source as saying.
</P>
<P>
It said Khalid, who can not speak English or Kiswahili but
only Arabic, was identified by a guard and a civilian worker at
the embassy and a third witness. The witnesses also sustained
injuries from flying objects.
</P>
<P>
Director of the U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)
Louis Freech is expected to issue a statement about the bombing
probe before he leaves Nairobi for Washington at noon Friday.
</P>
<P>
He came here Thursday evening after a one-day visit to
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the investigators also raided offices of Mercy
Relief International Agency, a non-governmental organization, in
the Kenyan capital Thursday and arrested an Arab and a Sudanese,
the East African Standard newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said the plan to bomb U.S. embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania took three months to complete and bombers destined
for Kenya were dispatched through Somali and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
A senior government official who saw the confessions of
suspects was quoted by local media Friday as saying that an
Egyptian Islamic Jihad group, linked with Saudi millionaire Osama
Bin Laden, who now lives in Afghanistan, planned the attacks.
</P>
<P>
The car bomb attack at the u.s. embassy in Nairobi reportedly
killed 253 people and injured some 5,000 more.
</P>
<P>
A nearly simultaneous car bombing outside the U.S. embassy in
tanzania killed 10 people and wounded about 70 others.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton Thursday ordered air raids on
terror facilities allegedly used by Laden in Afghanistan and
Sudan in a clear revenge attack for the bombings.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the U.S.'s demand for Laden's extradition from
Afghanistan has been refused by the Taliban government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts on China's Energy Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Coal will occupy a major part of
China's energy early next century, but its importance will begin
to decline, and by 2050, China will have various energy sources in
coal, petroleum, natural gas, and nuclear and solar energy,
according to Xie Heping, president of China Mining University.
</P>
<P>
Xie told the China Association for Science and Technology's 3rd
Academic Conference of Young Scientists here today that coal's
dominant position in China's energy structure can not be changed
for a long time because of the low level of economic development.
</P>
<P>
Other analysts predict that coal will account for 65 percent of
China's total energy consumption in 2010, compared with the
present 75 percent. Petroleum will increase from 17 percent to
18.7 percent, natural gas, from 2 percent to 5.6 percent, and
hydroelectric and nuclear power, from 6 percent to 10.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Xie says that when China is more economically and
scientifically developed in the mid-21st century, it will reduce
the use of coal and petroleum, which are non-renewable sources.
</P>
<P>
He estimates that coal will account for 50 percent of China's
energy in 2050 and the use of petroleum will also decrease.
</P>
<P>
When China's per capita GDP reaches the level of developed
countries in the middle part of the next century, people will pay
more attention to the quality of life and the environment, and
China will develop more efficient and clean energy, Xie says.
</P>
<P>
But, he points out, China's current science and technology
level in the energy sector is still quite low, and environmental
problems caused by coal have been an important factor in China's
economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
He says that China needs to develop energy-saving technology
and products and to increase their use, improve the energy
structure, introduce advanced technology from foreign countries to
develop natural gas, and focus on renewable energy sources like
solar, wind, geothermal, and tidal energy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
