<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Wheat Production Drops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Shortfall in Kenya's wheat
production stands at 300,000 tons currently, Minister for
Research and Technology Andrew Kiptoon has said.
</P>
<P>
The east African state's total demand for wheat stands at
600,000 tons, which could not be met following a drop in the size
of wheat planting acreage from 150,000 hectares to 135,000, he
was quoted by Friday's Daily Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister told farmers and agricultural researchers at
Njoro, central Kenya, that the reduction was due to a shift by
wheat farmers to other crops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he urged more land especially in marginal areas to
be re-opened up for wheat growing.
</P>
<P>
With 80 percent of the country arid or semi arid, there is
need to intensify food production in potential land, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Kiptoon noted measures should be taken to ease the constraints
facing small-scale wheat farmers who have limited resources to
improve production and are yet to acquire technology.
</P>
<P>
He described agricultural research as the driving force in
achieving sustainable agricultural growth but regretted that only
0.4 per cent of Kenya's gross domestic product goes to research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
