<HEADLINE> Afghan Group Vows to Hit Back at U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- One of the militant groups hit
by U.S. missiles inside Afghanistan has vowed to retaliate against
the U.S. attacks on its base in Khost province of Afghanistan,
which it said is in fact a training camp for the Kashmiri
Mujahideen.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Harkat ul Mujahideen, Fazal-ur-Rahman Khalil, whose
organization has close links with Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden,
announced Friday that his organization would respond to the U.S.
"naked aggression" against Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said the camp provided training to Kashmiri Mujahideen (holy
fighters) who were fighting for freedom in Indian-occupied
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"Now it is our turn to give a tit-for-tat response to Americans
for killing innocent people in Afghanistan," Khalil said in a
telephone interview with the News Network International.
</P>
<P>
He said Karkat ul Mujahideen would not remain silent over the
brutal attack and would take revenge on the killings. "The
Americans should know that Osama bin Laden is not alone and every
Afghan and Kashmiri will emerge as Osama," he added.
</P>
<P>
Khalil said Harkat ul Mujahideen leaders have started
consultations to give a befitting response to the U.S. attack and
teach a lesson to the Americans for targeting innocent people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
