<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lethal Drink Kills 23 in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Twenty three people, including
three women, have died in the past three days in central Kenya
after drinking a chemical dubbed "Power Alcohol."
</P>
<P>
Among the killed are a policeman and a public health officer
said to be regular consumers of the drink, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported Friday
</P>
<P>
Four others, three of whom have lost their sight, have been
admitted at hospital. More than 20 have been treated and
discharged.
</P>
<P>
Nakuru District Commissioner John Litunda said that the
victims took "Power Alcohol" over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
He said one of the suspected sellers of the drink had been
arrested and a sample of the substance had been taken to the
Government Chemist for further analysis.
</P>
<P>
Litunda said the substance of the beverage, which he said was
used in industries, is siphoned from tankers destined for
neighboring countries and sold cheaply in Nakuru and Narok
districts.
</P>
<P>
Half a glass of the substance is sold at 10 Shillings (0.16
U.S. Dollar), said Litunda, adding that it smelt like methylated
spirit.
</P>
<P>
In September 1996, 24 Kenyans died and six others went
blind after taking a similar drink.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Aims to Post Balanced Budget by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Joseph Estrada administration
is confident of achieving a balanced budget, if not a surplus, by
the year 2000 despite fiscal constraints caused by the Asian
financial crisis, Budget Secretary Benjamin Diokno said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a report to President Estrada, Diokno said the government
aims to reduce its budget deficit from the estimated 40 billion
pesos (930 million U.S. dollars) this year to 17.9 billion pesos
(416 million dollars) next year.
</P>
<P>
"The progressive reduction may even translate to a budget
surplus by the year 2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government earlier projected a 70 billion-peso
(1.63 billion dollars) budget deficit this year, prompting the
president to enforce a series of austerity measures that are
expected to bring down the deficit to 40 billion pesos (about 1
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that the national government will register
a budget deficit during the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The Estrada administration is due to submit its 1999 budget
plan to the congress on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Diokno, the largest share of the 579.5
billion-peso (13.5 billion dollars) budget proposal will be
allotted to social services including education, health, poverty
reduction and housing reforms as Estrada promised in the May
presidential elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
