<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Leaves for Naval Exercises in Northern Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 21 (Xinhua) -- President Boris Yeltsin left
here Friday for northern Russia to watch a major naval exercise
while deputies in the State Duma, the lower house of parliament,
prepared to debate the country's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin was heading for Severomorsk in Murmansk Region for the
exercise of the Northern Fleet in the Barents Sea that will involve 50
warships, including the state-of-the-art Peter the Great
nuclear-powered missile cruiser.
</P>
<P>
The President, who had kept silent on the financial crisis
since Monday, might make a statement on the issue upon arrival at
the Murmansk airport, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The exercise will, among other feats, feature shooting and
deep-water launching of a missile aiming at a target on a testing
ground on the Kamchatka Peninsula in Far Eastern Russia.
</P>
<P>
At the State Duma, deputies are set to grill Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko and other top officials over the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Russian government and the central bank on Monday raised the
ceiling of the exchange corridor of the ruble from 6.3 to 9.5
rubles to the U.S. dollar, effectively devaluating the national
currency and throwing the stocks, bond and exchange market into
further upheavals. 
</P>
