<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bankruptcies, Liquidations in NZ Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Bankruptcies and liquidations
in New Zealand are rising sharply, according to the latest data
released by the Ministry of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
In the year to June, 2,974 people were declared bankrupt, up 21
percent from a year earlier while 1,074 companies were liquidated,
a 48-percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The rise in bankruptcies was caused by an increase in consumer
bankruptcies, with people getting into debt through personal
spending rather than business-related spending.
</P>
<P>
Consumer bankruptcies were up 42 percent in the year.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's insolvency service manager, Andrew Bridgman,
said the reason could be people getting into trouble with their
credit card bills.
</P>
<P>
Of the bankruptcies, 63 percent were at the request of the
debtor, a proportion that was also rising.
</P>
<P>
Bridgman said people were less shy about using the bankruptcy
option.
</P>
<P>
A crackdown on companies not paying their tax bills was the
main cause of increased liquidations, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the year to June 1997, only 43 percent of liquidations were
triggered by the Inland Revenue Department (IRD), but in the
following 12 months, the IRD petitioned for 63 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
