<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Networking Industry Revenue Up in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 20 (Xinhua) -- While global chip sales
decreased in recent months, revenue of the worldwide networking
industry gained a big increase in the second quarter, according to
a U.S. market analysis firm's report on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The industry, driven by the local area network (LAN) switch
market, earned 2.1 billion U.S. dollars during the period, up 78
percent from the second quarter a year ago, said Dataquest Inc.
</P>
<P>
LAN is a communications network that serves users within a
confined geographical area. It is made up of servers,
workstations, a network operating system and a communications link.
</P>
<P>
According to Dataquest's preliminary statistics, revenues of
LAN switches, routers and shared media hubs reached 4.1 billion
dollars, up 27.8 percent from the second quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The switch market has been driven by the demand for more
efficient use of bandwidth, Dataquest said.
</P>
<P>
Cisco Systems, a leading U.S. supplier of network switching
systems, continued to lead the LAN market, which grew by 168
percent in the second quarter, and Cisco's own share of this
market surpassed 40 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
