<HEADLINE> Representatives Agree to Expand Sister City Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from Chinese and
Japanese organizations today agreed to expand exchanges and
cooperation between sister cities in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The plan, unveiled during the closing ceremony of a three-day
meeting on sister cities, calls for expanding information,
personnel and technical exchanges, and introducing preferential
policies to promote cooperation between small and medium-sized
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Participants discussed wide-ranging issues, including prospects
for exchanges between sister cities, measures to deal with
problems related to rapidly ageing populations and urban
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
They also pointed to broad prospects for cooperation between
cities in areas such as urban planning and infrastructure
construction, personnel training and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xiaoxian, vice-president of the China-Japan Friendship
Association, told participants that local governments and relevant
organizations will intensify efforts to promote ties of cooperation
in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan have established relationship between 193 pairs
of sister cities since the Chinese port city of Tianjin and
Japanese city of Kobe established such ties some 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was sponsored by the China-Japan Friendship
Association and the Japan Council of Local Authorities for
International Relations.  
</P>
