<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Victims Well Cared For (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Enough food, boiled water,
temporary housing and access to medical care guarantee a basically
normal life and effective epidemic disease prevention for
flood-stricken areas in central and east China, according to
dispatches from Xinhua staff reporters on the flood-fighting front
lines.
</P>
<P>
 Hubei Province: Strict Epidemic Prevention Imposed
</P>
<P>
In Mengxi Township, Gong'an County, one of the hardest-hit
areas, over 300 epidemic-prevention personnel are busy encouraging
 local residents to drink boiled water and instructing them on the
use of disinfectants.
</P>
<P>
Bottled mineral water, a luxury for Chinese farmers, is now in
the homes of many flood victims. On August 18 alone, for example,
the township received 12,000 cartons of pure bottled water from a
leading provincial mineral water producer.
</P>
<P>
Between August 4 and 19, the county inoculated one million
people and distributed 20,500 kilograms of disinfectants.
</P>
<P>
Jingzhou City, which administers Gong'an, is using one-fifth of
its relief funds to prevent disease. Everyday, over 200 medical
teams from all over the country are at work on the flood-fighting
front lines.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi Province: Shelter and Food Keys to Relief Effort
</P>
<P>
Providing basic housing and food is the primary concern of
Jiangxi provincial flood relief authorities in their effort to aid
flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Jiujiang City, which one week ago experienced the Yangtze
River's worst embankment burst, has made use of schools, idle
workshops and warehouses to settle over 260,000 displaced
residents. In addition, 206,000 people have moved into improvised
huts and tents. At the same time, a large number of people have
gone to live with their relatives.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure food supply, the city has allocated about
6,000 tons of rice to replenish retail outlets. Ten temporary
grain supply outlets have been added in seven counties and
districts which have offered more than 12,500 tons of relief grain.
</P>
<P>
Hygiene is also a focus of attention. Sterilized water has
benefited over 2.83 million people, and free medicine has been
used to treat some 230,000 patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
