<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cost of Living Goes Up by 13 Percent in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The cost of living in Indian
cities increased by 13.1 percent in July compared with the same
period last year, according to data published by the Central
Statistical Organization here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chandigarh, a city in the northwestern state of Rajasthan,
topped the list of 59 cities and towns with the highest cost of
living and an inflation rate of 24.4 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
It was followed by Delhi with an inflation rate of 20.6 percent
based on consumer price index for urban non-manual employees which
measures inflation rates in urban centers among white-collar
workers.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index for Delhi shot up to 339 points in
July from 281 points the same month last year, showing a sharp
increase in the price of essential commodities.
</P>
<P>
The lowest rate of price increase was recorded in the hill town
of Shillong, capital of the northeastern state of Meghalaya, at
7.3 percent during the month.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of the current fiscal year (from April to
July), the average index grew by 10.2 percent and the all-India
index went up by 13.1 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rates in most cities in the southern region were
below the national average with that of Hyderabad, Bangalore,
Chennail, Madural falling below 13 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
