<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 07:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Lauds U.S. Strikes in Afghanistan, Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Israel has expressed its
support for the U.S. strike on "terrorist-related" bases in
Afghanistan and Sudan, saying it stood by Washington in its fight
against international terrorism, Israel Radio reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by his office late Thursday night,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu praised the
U.S. "particularly for choosing to hit the terror infrastructure
and terrorist bases in Sudan and Afghanistan," the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai also said he
supports U.S. President Bill Clinton and Secretary of Defense
William Cohen for what he called "the courageous decision and
action against terrorist targets."
</P>
<P>
"The war against terrorism, wherever it may be, is never
ending and vital to ensure security and stability in the world,"
Mordechai said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. military forces launched surprise attacks Thursday against
several sites in Afghanistan and Sudan in an effort to destroy
what the U.S. said were key bases used by terrorists believed to
have been involved in the bombings of two U.S. embassies in Africa
early this month.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear whether the U.S. informed Israel of its
intention before the attack, but an Israeli newspaper, Haaretz,
reported Friday that Israel has provided the U.S. with
considerable information on the international infrastructure of
Islamic terrorism following the terror attacks on the
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Labor Party leader Ehud Barak declared that his party supports
the U.S. in its "determined and vigorous struggle against
terrorism," saying terrorism constitutes "a constant threat to the
stability of the enlightened world and to innocent civilians."
</P>
</TEXT>
