<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Semiconductor Industry Urges Y2K Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The semiconductor industry
of the United States Thursday called on President Bill Clinton and
Congress to support an act that will enable U.S. companies to
share information about solutions for the Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the president and Congress, the Semiconductor
Industry Association (SIA), acting on behalf of the nation's
large chip manufacturers, urged quick passage of the "Year 2000
Readiness Disclosure Act," authored by representatives David
Dreier and Anna Eshoo.
</P>
<P>
The Dreier-Eshoo bill encourages companies to exchange Y2K
information without fear that the information will subsequently be
used against them as evidence in civil suits.
</P>
<P>
"With only 500 days left before the onset of the Y2K
phenomenon, the time for congressional action on this issue is
now," said the letter from the SIA based in California's Silicon
Valley and more than 50 other major business groups.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that the bill, which the SIA described as "Good
Samaritan," presents "the most effective approach to encourage
voluntary disclosure and will result in meaningful and necessary
information exchange."
</P>
<P>
In addition to urging quick passage of the bill, the SIA and
other business associations want Congress to address the broader
liability consequences of the Y2K problem. "The Congress also must
address the liability issues of Y2K to ensure a fair and equitable
resolution of any problems that surface after the year 2000," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The Year 2000 problem affects computer software that uses two
digits to represent the year in software date fields. When the
year 2000 arrives, these computer systems could interpret the year
as 1900. Considering its consequences and possible lawsuits, some
business leaders have called it not just a technical issue, but a
management issue, a political issue and a social issue.
</P>
<P>
"Even though the Year 2000 problem is primarily a software and
systems issue," the SIA letter said, "chip companies are doing
everything they can to address the problem in their own businesses
and on behalf of their customers."
</P>
<P>
At an online conference on the issue Wednesday, Dreier said
that he doesn't foresee the imminent passage of a bill to limit
companies' legal liability for problems caused by the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
Opposition to the bill, from the American Lawyers Association and
the Clinton administration, will hamper the bill's chances of getting
passed quickly, Dreier said.
</P>
<P>
"Some people out there are saying that the only thing that will
drive the solution to this problem is the threat of a lawsuit," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
