<HEADLINE> Five Pakistanis Killed in U.S. Missile Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- At least five Pakistanis were
killed and more than 10 others seriously injured Thursday night in
U.S. missile strikes on the afghan city of Khost bordering
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
An Islamabad-based spokesman for Harakat Ul Mujahideen, which
runs a military base in Khost for Kashmiris, told Xinhua that the
injured have been taken to a hospital in Pakistan's border town of
Miran Shah.
</P>
<P>
According to sources here, the base called Amir Muwaya was
previously known as Albabar during the Afghan war.
</P>
<P>
The United States launched missile attacks against what it said
was a complex of terrorists allegedly run by Saudi exile Osama bin
Laden about 150 kilometers south of the Afghan capital of Kabul
close to the Pakistani border.
</P>
<P>
The United States also attacked "terrorist" facilities in Sudan
Thursday night in retaliation of the August 7 bombings of U.S.
embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania. The
bombings were believed to be connected with Bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan-based Afghan Islamic Press (AIP) said earlier
Friday that at least 15 people were killed in the U.S. missile
strikes.


