PHNOM PENH -- A 45-year old driver for Kyodo News Serves was
killed in a grenade attack Thursday night outside the Cambodian
Interior Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The incident shattered the relatively peaceful post-election
calm and raised the concerns about the future of the new coalition
government. The attack followed a series of confrontations between
police and Sam Rainsy party supporters, who were attempting to
sleep at the Interior Ministry compound with election ballots,
witnesses said. (Cambodia-Grenade Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- A group of armed men shot at some foreign UN
officials in a mini-bus in the Afghan capital of Kabul, injuring
one early Friday only hours after U.S. missile strikes on alleged
Islamic training centers.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here Friday from Kabul, the
injured official, who was covered in blood, said he had been shot
and was taken to the offices of the International Committee of the
Red Cross for treatment. (Afghan-UN Officials)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Indonesian government Thursday opened the first
commercial court under the new bankruptcy law.
</P>
<P>
The new bankruptcy law, which took effect Thursday, is expected
to filter out inefficient businesses in an attempt to create a
feeling of security without ignoring the rights of debtors, Antara
News Agency Friday quoted Justice Minister Muladi as saying. It is
also aimed at paving the way for a resolution of the country's 64
billion U.S. dollars in corporate foreign debts.
(Indonesia-Bankruptcy Court) 
</P>
