<HEADLINE> Pakistan Closely Watches Situation After US Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The situation in the region
has become very volatile after the U.S. air strikes to eliminate
Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden inside Afghanistan, The Nation
quoted a senior defense official as saying Friday.
The U.S. on Thursday launched military strikes against what it
said was a complex of terrorist facilities allegedly run by Saudi
exile Osama bin Laden about 150 kilometers south of the Afghan
capital of Kabul close to the Pakistan border.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that the U.S. forces hit an Afghan town of
Khost Thursday night with Tomahawk cruise missile in a bid to
eliminate Laden who was allegedly involved in the bombings of the
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani defense official, whose name was not given, said
that the joint chiefs of staff committee will hold a meeting to
review the security situation which arose after this development.
Meanwhile, the spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, Tariq Altaf,
said Thursday night that Pakistan is closely watching the
situation, arising out of the military strikes on targets in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is fully alert to the situation to ensure the
security of its borders," said the spokesman.
The Nation said that the missile strikes are of great concern for
Pakistan as it could destabilize the region. 
