<HEADLINE> Polish Financial Market Troubled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Polish financial market has
suffered a series of turmoils in the wake of a drastic devaluation
of the Russian ruble.
</P>
<P>
The Polish zloty fell 2.05 percent Thursday against the
U.S. dollar to a record low of 3.6 to the dollar on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the zloty dropped one percent in the exchange rate
against the dollar on August 17, which was followed by another
wave of depreciation of 2.04 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic depreciation of the zloty, which remained sound in
the past few months, shocked Polish economists and triggered panic.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that foreign investors had withdrawn their
investments from Poland for fear the financial crisis in Russia
might affect eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the inflow of investment in the first half of the
year from Asian countries, foreign investment in Poland rose by
nearly three billion U.S. dollars to 26.5 billion U.S. dollars,
nine percent of which turned bad.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, foreign investors have been selling off
Polish treasury bonds and negotiable securities and then buying
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors have reportedly withdrawn a total of nearly
one billion dollars in capital.
</P>
<P>
Recent days have also seen a tumbling stock market. Stock
prices for 97 listed companies fell on August 17 while 105
companies suffered Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
