<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Strives to Keep Financial Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Kazakh financial market has
remained stable despite the impact of the Asian financial crisis
and the collapsing Russian banking market.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year Kazakhstan's balance of payments
were 280 million U.S. dollars in the red due to shrinking east
Asian markets and investment.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation of the Russian ruble also triggered fluctuation
in the financial market. By August 1, the Kazakh zenge had lost
2.25 percent of its value, settling at 78 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
However, because Kazakhstan has long been independent of the
Russian financial system and the ruble makes up only seven percent
of the foreign trade settlement, the Kazakh financial market on
the whole is free of turbulence and under control.
</P>
<P>
On August 19, the Kazakh government and the state bank issued a
joint statement attributing the sound market to high gold and
foreign currency reserves and the low rate of foreign capital in
its stock market.
</P>
<P>
The state bank has a total of two billion dollars in gold and
currency reserves, which is 40 times the foreign investment in the
stock market and more than enough to ensure a healthy money supply.
</P>
<P>
The economy is largely self-reliant and depends little on
foreign loans. Its annual repayment of foreign and domestic debt
accounts for only nine percent of the national budget.
</P>
<P>
The Kazakh government this year has taken a series of measures
to counter the fallout of the Asian and Russian financial crises
and achieve stable economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The government has reduced transportation fees for mineral and
finished products, lowered tariffs and prices for some imported
commodities and abolished the double value-added taxation imposed
on products made by other members of the Commonwealth of
Independent States.
</P>
<P>
The government has also carried out a stringent budget by
slashing the size of the civil service and freezing investment on
some non-essential projects.
</P>
<P>
In addition, to further protect the zenge, the state bank has
adopted the floating exchange rate and raised the discount rates,
the interest rate on loans and the securities buy-back interest
rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish President Signs Law on College Students Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Polish President Aleksander
Kwasniewski signed a law Wednesday requiring commercial banks to
provide low-interest loans to college students starting from
October 1, the new school year.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, college students with Polish nationality,
under the age of 25, are entitled to the loans for no more than
six years.
</P>
<P>
The National Education Ministry estimated that each student can
borrow 600 zloty(171.4 U.S. dollars) per month, with a total not
to exceed six times of the average pay of employees in the sectors
of national economy, at an interest rate lower than that of
commercial bank's
discount rate loans.
</P>
<P>
Students in public colleges, private colleges, evening schools
and correspondence schools all can apply for the loans, but have to
begin repayment in the first year after their graduation.
</P>
<P>
Loans will not be available to those who repeat class, drop
out or being expelled from school, but will be totally or
partially remitted for those from poor families or making high
grades.
</P>
<P>
There are 127,000 to be enrolled in colleges this year in
Poland, among whom 90,000 will get the loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
