<HEADLINE> Phnom Penh Takes up Fight Against Dengue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Phnom Penh health and
municipal authorities Friday began to mobilize the citizens to get
a thorough cleaning to prevent the dengue fever which is spreading
rapidly in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Chea Sophara, Phnom Penh's first deputy governor, and Health
Minister Chhea Thang will be among thousands of other Phnom Penh
citizens to clean up the environment.
</P>
<P>
The plan is to get city residents to fill in holes, cover water
jars and dispose of garbage around their homes that could collect
water and become breeding sites for mosquitos.
</P>
<P>
The Dengue fever is a disease spread by the bite of the "Tiger"
mosquito. The most effective way to prevent it is to keep areas
outside homes clean and destroy mosquito breeding sites.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is part of an internationally organized effort to
fight a dengue fever epidemic.
</P>
<P>
About 8,700 children have been admitted to hospitals and more
than two hundred have died since an outbreak in January, a Health
Ministry official told Xinhua Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The number could rise to more than 15,000 by the end of
this year's rain season, making it the worst dengue epidemic in
the country's history.
</P>
<P>
So far the worst-hi areas are Phnom Penh, and Kandal, Takeo,
Battambang and Kampong Cham provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
