<HEADLINE> Armed Group Members Surrender in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A total of 22 members of anti-
government armed groups laid down their arms to the government
last month, official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The armed group members, which include those from the ethnic
Kayin National Union (KNU) and the All Burma Students' Democratic
Front (ABSDF), "exchanged arms for peace" with the government at
different military command areas between July 1 and 18.
</P>
<P>
Both the KNU and the ABSDF have been reportedly operating on
the Myanmar-Thai border in armed opposition to the Myanmar
government.
</P>
<P>
In April, former KNU Central Committee member Phado Aung San
crossed over to the government side with more than 200 of his men
in Hpa-an, the country's Kayin State, as part of KNU's surrender.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, a total of 17 anti-government ethnic armed groups in
the country have made peace with the government, leaving the KNU,
led by Bo Mya, still in insurgency on the Myanmar-Thai border
although four rounds of peace talks have been held between them.
</P>
</TEXT>
