<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Expatriate Workers Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The number of Sri Lanka's new
expatriate workers in the first half this year was over 70,600, 10
percent more than the corresponding period last year, Labor
Ministry officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
A record foreign exchange remittance of 1.08 billion U.S.
dollars has been sent by expatriate Sri Lankans in 1997 compared
to 770 million dollars in 1996. This year the amount is expected
to increase to 1.2 billion dollars, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Around 1.05 million Sri Lankans are employed abroad, most of
them working as housemaids in the Middle East countries such as
Saudi Arabia, Syria, Egypt, Jordan, Lebanon, Oman and the United
Arab Emirates while others are employed in Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
As they bring in such a large amount of foreign exchange, the
government has launched welfare schemes for them, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly the Peoples Banks in collaboration with the Bureau
of Foreign Employment has commenced a loan scheme for expatriates
to either build a house or set up business.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Foreign Employment plans to provide overseas
employment opportunities for some 1.2 million Sri Lankans by the
year 2,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
