<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukranian Currency Depreciates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Ukranian currency, the hryvnya,
is depreciating rapidly due to the sagging Russian ruble.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar was traded at 2.1435 hryvnyas in cross-bank
transactions on August 14, rising to 2.236 on August 20. In the
past two days, some commercial banks even bought one U.S. dollar
with 2.25 hryvnyas.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the commercial banks, the National Bank of
Ukraine urged them to stop illegal purchase of foreign currencies
at a premium price.
</P>
<P>
The central bank governor, Victor Yuchenko, said the exchange
rate of hryvnya against the dollar would probably break the
ceiling of the currency corridor -- 1.8-2.25 hryvnyas to the
dollar, which was jointly set by the government and the central
bank for this year.
</P>
<P>
Observers expect that Ukraine is likely to raise the ceiling of
the currency corridor as Russia did, which would accelerate the
hryvnya's fall and price rises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
