<HEADLINE> Staff Work Flat Out to Handle Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- A deluge of donations has put a
great deal of pressure on civil affairs departments throughout
China, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Extra staff have been drafted to work day and night to
guarantee that donations can reach flood victims as quickly as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's Bureau of Civil Affairs is carrying out simultaneous
reception, storage and dispatch of donations.
</P>
<P>
By yesterday, the Ministry of Civil Affairs and local civil
affairs departments had received 363 million yuan (43.7 million
U.S. dollars) of donations -- 228 million yuan of funds and 135
million yuan of materials such as medicines, mineral water, bags
and clothes.
</P>
<P>
The ministry had dispatched 131 million yuan worth of relief
materials to the flood-hit areas by yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Canada announced on Wednesday it would provide 200,000 Canadian
dollars (132,000 U.S. dollars) in additional emergency relief aid
to flood victims in China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, medical workers are working round the clock along
the rivers to guard against epidemics.
</P>
<P>
On the Songhuajiang River in Heilongjiang province, northeast
China, 2,244 medical workers have been dispensing medical aid and
helping to prevent the spread of epidemics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
