<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Release Social Security Fund for Unemployed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Ministry of Thailand
is planning to release 10 billion baht (250 million U.S. dollars)
of its Social Security Fund to finance the costs of further
education and living for the jobless, the Nation newspaper said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Deputy Labor Minister Jongchai Thiangtham
as saying that the plan had the preliminary backing of Labor
Minister Trairong Suwankhiri, who will present it to the cabinet
for approval.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, which will draw its financing from the 53
billion baht (1.3 billion dollar) Social Security Fund, an
eligible unemployed person or laid-off worker could access 50,000
baht to 60,000 baht (1,250 to 1,500 dollars) in yearly loans or an
average of 5,000 baht (125 dollars) a month.
</P>
<P>
The rate of interest for the loan is yet to be decided,
Jongchai said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the government released 5 billion baht (125 million
dollars) from the Social Security Fund in a bid to ease the
liquidity crunch plaguing medium and small-size businesses, via
loans extended through commercial banks and Small Industry Finance
Corporation bonds.
</P>
<P>
Jongchai said the ministry will also begin offering
psychological and labor counselling to white-collar workers who
have lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Association of Thai Construction Industry president
Jaroon Janjamratsaeng predicted that if the government's recent
financial sector reform package fails to ease the liquidity crunch
of the construction sector, the lay-off figure of the industry
would rise to 200,000.
</P>
<P>
Unemployed people in Thailand had already exceeded 2 million,
or 7 percent of the total work force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
