<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Catching Tax Evaders in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Enwei Pharmaceutical Factory, a
branch of Chengdu's Enwei Group, a leading producer of women's
hygiene products, will have to pay 54.8 million yuan (6.6 million
U.S. dollars) in overdue taxes and a fine of 6.48 million yuan for
bad tax practices.
</P>
<P>
The story has caught the attention of the Chinese press in the
past two months. It resulted from the company's overuse of tax
breaks for overseas-funded enterprises between 1994 and 1995. Its
overseas partner, a Hongkong investor, did not provide the
required investment until the end of 1995. Hongkong investors also
enjoy the preferential terms given to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The group will also have to pay overdue taxes of 46.74 million
yuan for the Enwei Shiheng Pharmaceutical Factory which was
registered in August 1990 but dissolved in August 1994.
</P>
<P>
Enwei Shiheng made the same mistake of asking for tax breaks
for a Sino-overseas joint venture, even after its overseas
partner, a Hongkong firm, withdrew 1.4 million of its 1.5 million
Hongkong dollars of investment one week after putting the money in
place.
</P>
<P>
A group spokesman says they will go along with the decision and
pay the overdue taxes and fine.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese press has gone after the group in recent months,
accusing it of evading 100 million yuan in taxes in two years, to
which the group responded angrily, calling it exaggerated
reporting and saying it had adversely affected sales. 
</P>
</TEXT>
