<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 20 -- The following are major
economic news briefs in Latin American countries:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- A cow has given About 135.37 liters of milk
from its four milkings in 48 hours, which set a new national
record in Argintine.
</P>
<P>
The record was established during a contest of milk cows held
in the province of Santa Fe. The previous mark was 129 liters of
milk in the same time of milking.
</P>
<P>
The milk cows contest organized every year by the Rafaela Rural
Society is the oldest in Argentina and has been held
uninterruptedly for 78 years.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Finance Minister Maritza Izaguirre denied Wednesday
an imminent devaluation of bolivar and establishment of an
exchange control.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan government is committed to reestablishing an
equilibrated economic environment and the passing of the necessary
laws to retain the credibility and confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Panamanian government invested more than 5.4
billion U.S. dollars in health, education and housing projects in
last four years, announced President Ernesto Perez Balladares.
</P>
<P>
The president said in a message to the country that during his
term of office, started in 1994, 82,000 housing units, five hospitals
and dozens of health centers in the urban areas have been
constructed.
</P>
<P>
The government intends to offer Panamanians a more dignified
and comfortable life through these projects.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- A total of 88,615 new motor vehicles were sold
during the first seven months of the year, 4.5 percent less than
in the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Chevrolet heads the list of cars sold with 17.8 percent of the
total, followed by Hyundai with 10.8 percent and Nissan with
10.3 percent, according to the National Automotive Association of
Chile statistics.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombia does not arouse the interest of
foreign investment funds but there are big expectations about the
performance of the economy in the medium and long term, according
to a poll taken at the second quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
The study covers 32 emerging markets in six different regions
and one of the conclusions of the study is that the expectations
of the investment funds managers toward the emerging markets are
at their lowest point since the start of the southeast Asian
crisis in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The poll, published Thursday by the international consulting firm
Burson-Marsteller, reports that the investment in Latin America
fell 18 percent during the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Russian financial crisis affects the Brazilian
exports, mainly in the purchasing of sugar and coffee but its
sequels are not serious.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Agricultural National Confederation president Antonio
Ernesto de Salvo said that Brazilian exports to Russia last year
were 761 million dollars, only 1.44 percent of the total of its
sales abroad.
</P>
<P>
Sugar and coffee are some of the main products exported to
Russia, which amounted last year to 274 million and 120 million
dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rican coffee production will drop some
200,000 46-kilogram bags during the 1998-1999 harvest, 6.3 percent
compared to the same period of 1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
These data came out of the first estimate made by the Coffee
Institute (ICAF) for 1998-1999, which began to be harvested in
July this year and will end in March or April of 1999.
</P>
<P>
ICAF executive director Guillermo Canet explained that the
coffee production is cyclical, meaning that on a period increases
and in the next diminishes.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The Chilean balance of trade had a big deficit of
518.3 million dollars in July, the biggest of the year, the
central bank reported.
</P>
<P>
This amount was the result of a 14.5 percent drop in exports,
which totalled 1.216 billion dollars and a 9.8 percent increase in
the imports.
</P>
<P>
In this way, the trade deficit accumulated in the first seven
months of the year amounted to 1.629 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
LIMA -- Several Canadian firms will invest six billion dollars
in Peru in the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Presently the Canadian investments in Peru that surpass two
billion dollars are in mining and energy.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade reached 393.3 million dollars in 1997, of which
259.6 million dollars were Canadian exports and 134.3 million
dollars were Peruvian exports to Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
