<HEADLINE> Capital Flight Surges Sharply in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- As a region-wide recession looms
over the horizon, hot funds that flew out of the Philippines
increased by 76 percent during the first six months this year.
</P>
<P>
Data from the Securities and Exchange Commission showed that at
least 730 million pesos (16.9 million U.S. dollars) of investments
left the country during the period as against 414.1 million pesos
(9.6 million dollars) a year ago, Business World reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Painting an even more bleak picture, the vacuum left by
volatile portfolio investments are not being replaced by fresh
capital.
</P>
<P>
The Securities and Exchange Commission reported that new
investments from new and existing companies took a 42.2-percent
dive to 48.21 billion pesos (1.12 billion dollars) in the period.
</P>
<P>
However, the data showed that there was only a 3.5 percent
increase in the number of companies which were forced to cease
operations to 59 from 57 in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the research department of the Securities and
Exchange Commission, the ongoing Asian financial crisis and the El
Nino weather phenomenon caused investors to temporarily stop
putting up new businesses in the country, in an attempt to cut
their losses during the slump.
</P>
<P>
The data also showed that the number of new business entities
which registered with the commission fell by 18.1 percent to only
9,309 from 11,367 in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
