<HEADLINE> Young Priests Help Keep Taoism Alive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Increasing numbers of young
well-trained Taoist priests are helping to boost the popularity of
the 1,800-year-old religion in China, today's China Daily quoted
Zhang Jiyu, deputy secretary-general of the China Taoist
Association, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Zhang made the remark when addressing the opening session of
the association's sixth national conference yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The problem of China's Taoist circles being dominated by older
people has existed for a long time.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the 1990s, the Taoist Theological Institute
of China and two training classes in Shanghai and Qingchengshan
Mountain, in southwest China's Sichuan Province, have trained more
than 400 Taoist priests. These priests form the backbone of Taoist
temples and associations across China.
</P>
<P>
However, the problem of a predominance of aged Taoist priests
still exists, said Ye Xiaowen, director of the State Bureau of
Religious Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Ye suggested that local Taoist associations should organize
training courses for Taoist priests with the help of the China
Taoist Association.
</P>
<P>
China's Taoist temples, numbering more than 1,600, are in great
need of staff to look after them.
</P>
<P>
At present, the country has 133 local Taoist associations above
the county level and more than 25,000 Taoist priests, including
members of both the Quanzheng and Zhengyi sects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Bankruptcy Court Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Thursday opened the first commercial court under the new
bankruptcy law.
</P>
<P>
The new bankruptcy law, which took effect Thursday, is expected
to filter out inefficient businesses in an attempt to create a
feeling of security without ignoring the rights of debtors, Antara
News Agency Friday quoted Justice Minister Muladi as saying.
</P>
<P>
It is also aimed at paving the way for a resolution of the
country's 64 billion U.S. dollars in corporate foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been the hardest hit by the regional currency
turmoil with the rupiah (national currency) losing about 80
percent of its value against the U.S. dollar, making it virtually
impossible for companies to repay their foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
Under a previous bankruptcy law that dated back to 1905 during
the Dutch colonial times, creditors had little leverage over the
debtors. Because of the law, not even one company has declared
bankruptcy despite the fact that about 70 percent of Indonesian
companies are now technically insolvent due to the dramatic fall
of the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
The court and the new law are part of sweeping reforms the
Indonesian government has agreed to in exchange for the 43 billion
U.S. dollar bail-out package led by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
When opening the court, Muladi said, "This is a historic and
significant move. It will help us get rid of inefficient firms
which will in turn boost investor confidence in the country and
boost the economy."
</P>
<P>
The court will settle bankruptcy cases in public hearing,
allowing a maximum of 30 days from the time of filing for
settlement.
</P>
<P>
There is also a 30-day appeal period.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, creditors are allowed to send debtors into
bankruptcy nine months after they file a claim.
</P>
<P>
Fifty cases are ready to be filed with the newly established
commercial court, the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai People Making Donations In Spite Of Stifling Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's people were sweating
in the oppressive heat but still doing their best to provide
relief goods for flood-ravaged parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Companies that produce much-needed goods like drugs, chemicals,
sandbags, rubber dingies and life jackets have been working day
and night in 39 degree Celsius temperatures, and air and railway
service to disaster areas has been normal.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Pharmaceutical Co. Ltd. has donated antibiotics
and drugs worth one million yuan and Shanghai has responded to
orders from the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters for emergency goods, according to Mayor Xu Kuangdi.
</P>
<P>
At least 160 trains carrying relief goods and over 4,000
personnel have left Shanghai for the flood areas.
</P>
<P>
Recent municipal statistics show good industrial performance in
July in Shanghai with an output value of 48.7 billion yuan, a
year-on-year growth of 9.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Major industrial output has increased in the automobile, tire,
steel boat and generator sectors, as well as in agriculture.
</P>
</TEXT>
