<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Businessmen Want Technology from Foreign Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Thai businessmen urged the
government to force foreign companies to transfer technology and
management techniques to local firms as the country has
liberalized the Foreign Business Law, the Bangkok Post reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Khemadhat Sukondhasing, secretary-general of the Federation of
Thai Industries (FTI), was quoted as saying that the FTI wants
foreign firms to agree to its proposals regarding the number of
local staff employed by the companies.
</P>
<P>
The FTI suggests that during the first three years of
operation, some 80 percent of the middle-level management of
foreign-owned businesses would be Thais.
</P>
<P>
It also wants at least 40 percent of executives to be Thais
during the first five years.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet Tuesday approved an amendment to the Foreign
Business Law, under which restrictions governing foreign ownership
and participation in 33 industries are to be eased.
</P>
<P>
The FTI will present its proposal next week to a committee
drafting the amendment set by the Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Khemadhat said the technology transfer proposal would benefit
Thai people in the long-term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
