<HEADLINE> Sampras, Rafter Beaten in Pilot Pen Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- American Pete Sampras and
Australian Patrick Rafter, who were bidding to gain the top place
in the world rankings, surprisingly lost to little-known rivals
at the Pilot Pen tennis tournament in Connecticut, the United S
tates Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, trying to regain his number one ranking, came out
flat against Indian qualifier Leander Paes and lost 6-3, 6-4 in
74 minutes. At the same time, Rafter, No. 3 and second seed here,
fell to No. 16 Guillaume Raoux of France 7-6 (10-8), 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Sampras lost to Rafter in three intense sets Sunday in the
final of the ATP championship in Cincinnati and the players
eagerly spoke of a rematch.
</P>
<P>
"I knew he was coming in a lot and would be frustrating to
play," Sampras said after losing to the 100th-ranked Paes. "He
played well but I felt I was very flat. I think playing three
weeks in a row has taken its toll a little bit emotionally. I
give him credit."
</P>
<P>
Sampras can end Marcelo Rios' latest reign as the No.1 player
if the Chilean loses Thursday night at the RCA championship in
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
The rankings, released next Monday, most likely will be the
basis for seedings for the U.S. Open in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The second-seeded Rafter had a chance to grab the top spot but
succumbed to Raoux, whom he had beaten last week.
</P>
<P>
"I wasn't moving well today," said Rafter, who had a
career-best 11-match winning streak stopped. "Everything seemed a
lot quicker, the ball was flying. I was a little bit flat
mentally."
</P>
<P>
Five of the remaining seeds advanced to the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
Fourth seed Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands dispatched
Israeli Harel Levy 6-2, 6-4, and sixth seed Tim Henman of Britain
rallied past Italian Davide Sanguinetti 4-6, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Fifth seed and defending champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov
eliminated Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil 6-4, 6-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
