<HEADLINE> Khartoum Factory Burnt down After U.S. Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The Al-Shifa Pharmaceutical
Factory on the northern outskirt of Khartoum was leveled to the
ground in a U.S. bombing attack Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
A huge fire caused by the air strike was raging in the factory,
which is located just five kilometers away from the presidential
palace in downtown Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said at least 10 residents living near the factory
were seriously injured in the attack and their condition was very
serious. They were dying, the witnesses added.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said that factory workers on the night shift
were all killed.
</P>
<P>
But police declined to give any information on casualty.
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately known how many workers were at the
factory when a U.S. bomber attacked.
</P>
<P>
Policemen and firefighters sealed off the site, keeping
reporters and residents, who gathered to see what was going on,
from entering the factory.
</P>
<P>
Nobody was allowed to take photos.
</P>
<P>
A witness said he heard thundering explosions just seconds
after he saw a plane flew over the roof of his house at about
19:30 local time.
</P>
<P>
He said he thought the plane must have crashed before he
arrived at the scene and saw a three-story building of the
factory was reduced to ruins and burning.
</P>
<P>
The factory was built in 1980s and it was the largest
pharmaceutical factory in Sudan, producing and processing
antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the attack, U.S. President Bill Clinton said in a
televised address that he ordered air strikes at what he called
"terrorist-related" bases in Sudan and Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He alleged that the groups attacked by the U.S. forces Thursday
had played a key role in recent bombings on the U.S. embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The air raids came a week after the United States ordered the
withdrawal of U.S. diplomats from Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese President Omar Hassan al-Bashir condemned the
U.S. attack, describing it as "a provocation to the Sudanese
people."
</P>
<P>
Some Sudanese were reported to have taken over the evacuated
U.S. embassy compound after the bombing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
