<HEADLINE> Brazil To Resume Wheat Import from United States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Brazil may soon lift its
ban on United States wheat imports imposed two years ago to
prevent disease contamination of local crops.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Agriculture Minister Francisco Turra and U.S. Senator
Max Baucus met to discuss the purchase of U.S. wheat by Brazil,
Brazilian newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
"We want Brazil to open its market to our wheat," said Baucus,
adding that the U.S. had a big surplus of wheat which could be
exported to Brazil and the cereal had never threatened Brazilian
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Brazil stopped importing U.S. wheat in 1996, suspecting that
diseases affecting wheat plantations in the United States could
contaminate its grain.
</P>
<P>
Turra said that Brazil's wheat output is 2.7 million tons a
year, but the domestic wheat consumption is 8.5 million tons per
year.
</P>
<P>
Argentine and Canada also are Brazil's main wheat suppliers.
</P>
</TEXT>
