<HEADLINE> Brazilian Public Debt nears 40 percent of GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's public debt
reached 334.8 billion reals (some 291.13 billion U.S. dollars) at
the end of last may, accounting for 36.9 percent of its gross
domestic product (GDP), press reports said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Demosthenes Madureira De Pinho Neto, director of international
affairs of the central bank, said that the public sector liquid
debt could reach 40 percent of the GDP very soon.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank said that the internal debt began to skyrocket
in 1996, the second year of the government of President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso. By December of 1997, public debts had climbed to
308.4 billion reals, or 34.5 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1995, the public sector internal debt stood at
208.5 billion reals, or some 33.3 percent of the GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
