<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smallest Thermometer Developed in Finland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A university research group in
Finland has developed the world's smallest thermometer, and it is
ready for commercial production, reports said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The thermometer, the first commercial application of
nanoelectronic technology, consists of a nanosensor about one
thousandth of a millimeter and electronic measuring equipment.
</P>
<P>
The sensor is a linear array of nanoscale metal islands
separated by thin oxide layers, forming a chain of junctions that
change with temperature in a unique way.
</P>
<P>
The extremely small size of the sensor opens up new
possibilities for applications, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The prototype of the nanothermometer was originally developed
in 1997 by Professor Jukka Pekola, who headed Jyvaskyla
University's nanophysics group.
</P>
<P>
Its commercial application was achieved by a doctoral student
in the group, Juha Kauppinen, who improved the design of the
sensor.
</P>
<P>
The physicists have established a company called Nanoway to
take charge of the production and the marketing of the
thermometer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuadoran Exports Drop in First Semester </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Sluggish world oil and banana
market has decreased Ecuadoran exports for more than 16 percent in
the first half of this year, the country's Central Bank said in a
communique Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ecuadoran export were down 429 million dollars in the first
half of this year to 2.166 billion U.S. dollars, from 2.595
billion in the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
the Central Bank attributed the decrease mainly to the weak
export of oil products which only reached 430.4 billion dollars in
the first semester down from 673.7 million dollars in the same
period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Banana sales also dropped this year, down from 690.4 million
dollars in 1997 to 596 million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
The exports of cocoa, tuna fish, and natural flowers, among
other products, also suffered losses during the first half of this
year. 
</P>
