<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Justifies Its Military Strikes at U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Thursday told the U.N. Security Council that its military strikes
against targets in Afghanistan and Sudan were conducted under
the United Nations Charter.
</P>
<P>
The move is widely seen here as an apparent effort to head
off any U.N. actions.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Security Council, Bill Richardson, U.S.
Ambassador to the United Nations, said Washington had obtained
convincing information that the organization of Osama Bin Laden
was responsible for the August 7 bombings of the U.S. embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said the Bin Laden organization maintained "an
extensive network of camps, support facilities in Sudan, which
have been and being used to mount terrorist attacks against
American targets."
</P>
<P>
"In particular, U.S. forces struck a facility being used to
produce chemical weapons in Sudan and terrorist training and
basing camps in Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
Richardson said the attacks were conducted only after
"repeated efforts to convince the Government of Sudan and the
Taleban regime in Afghanistan to shut these terrorist
activities down and to cease their cooperation with the Bin
Laden organization."
</P>
<P>
"That organization has issued a series of blatant warnings
that 'strikes will continue from everywhere' against American
targets and we have convincing evidence that further such
attacks were in preparation from these same terrorist
facilities," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States, therefore, had no choice but to use armed
force to prevent these attacks from continuing," Richardson added.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, in a brief statement
issued by his spokesman's office, condemned terrorism in all its
forms and expressed his concern at the U.S. military strikes.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he had been informed by Washington minutes after
the strikes took place and awaited further details. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protecting China's Oldest Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 21 (Xinhua) -- More than 800 very old trees in
the city of Hangzhou in China's Zhejiang Province, which is known
for its West Lake, are getting government protection.
</P>
<P>
There are 60 species that are several hundred years old, and
the oldest, a gingko, is 1,400 years old.
</P>
<P>
Each of the trees has a stone tablet alongside it with the
tree's name, age, and health situation.
</P>
<P>
The city government has spent over 200,000 yuan (24,000
U.S. dollars) on the tablets and establishing files for each of
the trees since 1984, says a local official.
</P>
<P>
When the city built a new road this year, it had to include a
big detour to give way to two very old trees.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the city's green coverage rate is 44
percent, as a result of people's increased awareness of the need
for protection in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paraguayan President Faces Impeachment in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Several Paraguayan
political parties Thursday demanded an impeachment against
President Raul Cubas, for the release of General Lino Oviedo last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary sources said today that the resolution draft was
signed by the heads of the caucuses of the Colorado, Liberal, and
the National Encounter Social Democratic parties.
</P>
<P>
The resolution accuses Cubas of inadequately discharging of his
duties, referring to the recent freeing of Oviedo, who had been
sentenced to 10 years in prison for attempting a coup against
former president Juan Carlos Wasmosy in April, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Cubas, who assumed the presidency last Saturday, ordered the
release of Oviedo, an action that provoked a political crisis in
his own party and in the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The motion calls for the punishment of Cubas and his Ministers
of Defense and Justice for exempting Oviedo by decree from serving
his 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
The decision of Cubas met with condemnation from the congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
