<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Launches Plans to Catch Drug Cheats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Olympic leaders in Lausanne on
Thursday announced multi-million dollar plans to catch drug
cheats around the world, reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Accordint to reports, Juan Antonio Samaranch, president of the
International Olympic Committee (IOC), said the idea for setting
up a new drug testing agency would be put to international sports
federations and Olympic chiefs at a key doping conference next
February.
</P>
<P>
The IOC presently carries out drug tests during the Olympic
Games but the responsibility for the more efficient out-of-
competition tests is presently in the hands of international
federations and national bodies.
</P>
<P>
The new agency would improve on the current system by putting
out-of-competition testing under one umbrella.
</P>
<P>
Not all countries and international federations carry out the
tests, which are much more efficient at catching athletes who use
serious drugs like steroids than competition tests.
</P>
<P>
The agency will be funded by the billions of dollars that the
IOC receives from television rights for the Games.
</P>
<P>
IOC marketing chief Dick Pound, who is responsible for the
financing of the project, said the IOC expected at least $40
million per year to be spent on the out-of-competion testing
alone.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's decision was taken after the IOC's executive board
meeting heard the depressing story of doping at this year's Tour
de France from leading race official Jean-Claude Killy.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was called after the Tour de France scandal and
high-profile positive tests in other leading Olympics sports like
swimming and athletics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
