<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Removing Illegal Signboards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's Municipal Government
decided recently to tear down all illegal signboards and
advertisements on its streets.
</P>
<P>
Among the first group of signboards to go last week were a
number of signs on the Asian Television Building and Asian TV
Shopping Center.
</P>
<P>
The number of signs on city streets and on medial strips have
gone down since early August. Some organizations or companies have
used improper places to put signposts, signboards and
advertisements without getting permission from government
departments. These signs have increased the risk of traffic jams
or accidents, a government official says, and some drivers have
complained that they obscure the traffic and roads.
</P>
<P>
Some shelters along streets will also be removed to improve the
appearance of the city and provide better traffic conditions, he
said. The work has been done in 573 places and at least 350 units
or individuals have been fined for putting up illegal structures.
</P>
</TEXT>
