<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President and Party General Secretary Jiang Zemin
has concerned himself with the anti-flood battle along the two
major rivers in northeast China.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Jiang placed two calls to Wen Jiabao, vice-premier
and head of the State Flood Control and Drought Relief
Headquarters, to ask about the flood situation on the Nenjiang and
Songhua rivers. Jiang also issued a series of important directives
to Wen.
</P>
<P>
-- China's Supreme People's Court yesterday dismissed the
appeal by Chen Xitong, former secretary of the Beijing Municipal
Committee of the Communist Party of China, and affirmed the
original judgement.
</P>
<P>
-- While the sixth flood crest flowed through the middle
reaches of the Yangtze river yesterday, the flooding situation on
the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers caused concern.
</P>
<P>
A new flood crest on the Songhua river is pressing toward
Harbin, a major industrial city and capital of Heilongjiang
Province. A large numbers of soldiers and civilians are pledging
their lives to safeguard the city.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Zhu Rongji yesterday morning phoned Wang Maolin,
secretary of the Hunan Provincial Committee of the Communist Party
of China (CPC), inquiring about the flood situation there.
</P>
<P>
Zhu urged flood-fighters to abide by flood-control regulations,
patrol the river dikes round the clock and deal with dangerous
situations at any cost.
</P>
<P>
-- A China-made Long March 2C carrier rocket launched two
iridium satellites made by the U.S. Motorola Corp. at 7:01
a.m. yesterday (Beijing time) from the Taiyuan Satellite Launching
Center in north China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
China has fulfilled the contracted launching tasks of all the
iridium satellites into orbits. The current launch of iridiums
aims to make up the satellite communications network.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The third dyke protecting the Daqing Oilfield has withstood
the first rush of the Nenjiang River floods, temporarily quelling
the fears of millions of residents.
</P>
<P>
-- China has issued regulations to step up management of human
genome resources and promote international cooperation in the
field.
</P>
<P>
Without approval from the scientific and health administrations
of the State Council, no domestic or foreign individuals or work
units can be allowed to collect, develop, trade in or export
anything related to human genome resources, according to the
regulation issued yesterday by the Ministry of Health and the
Ministry of Science and Technology.
</P>
<P>
-- A Chinese official refuted rumors the nation's currency
will be devalued, and reaffirmed the yuan will remain solid.
</P>
