<HEADLINE> Australia Supports US Strikes Against Afghanistan, Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Australia said Friday it
supported U.S. strikes against Afghanistan and Sudan Friday,
describing the attacks as defensive acts by a nation protecting
its own citizens.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Friday on Australian Broadcasting Corporation radio in
Melbourne, Australian Prime Minister John Howard said the actions
were clearly prompted by the bombings of U.S. embassies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
U.S. intelligence officials said the targets of the raids were
six military-style camps in Afghanistan and a pharmaceutical plant
in Sudan believed to produce a key ingredient in nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
But Sudan denied the charge, the radio reported.
</P>
<P>
"My advice is that the strike was based upon very strong ...
evidence." Howard said. 
