<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ to Quicken Pace in Selling State Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 21 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government is
expected to quicken its pace in selling state-owned assets.
</P>
<P>
A Wellington-based newspaper Friday quoted newly-appointed
Treasurer and Finance Minister Bill Birch as saying that the
government will look at further asset sales now that it is no
longer constrained by the coalition with NZ First.
</P>
<P>
In the past 21 months, the New Zealand government has been a
coalition one formed by the NZ National Party and NZ First. But,
on the issue of handling the state-owned assets, the two political
parties have always disputed with each other.
</P>
<P>
The National Party with Prime Minister Jenny Shipley as its
leader advocates a greater involvement by the private sector in
the areas of business now controlled by the government. Shipley
once said: "Where the private sector can do it better, we will
allow them to do that."
</P>
<P>
As the minority partner in the government, the NZ First, with
then deputy prime minister and treasurer Winston Peters as its
leader, always has objections to the National's privatization bid.
</P>
<P>
The public disputes between Shipley and Peters took place when
the latter walked out of a special Cabinet meeting on August 12 as
a decision was about to be taken to sell the government's
shareholding in the Wellington International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The event of "walkout" led to the dismissal of Peters from his
post in the government and the breakup of the coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
Because of the splitting of the NZ First with a number of its
ministers and Parliament members resigning from the party and
voicing their support to Shipley on August 18, the National Party
will be allowed to continue in power as a minority government.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper "The Dominion", Birch, who is also
deputy leader of the National Party, said Thursday that the
government would set out clearly early next month what its
priorities and objectives were in the wake of the coalition's
collapse.
</P>
<P>
Birch said that it was possible that the government might
record a budget deficit next year, with its tax take hit by the
slowing-down in the economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that the forecasts of his Treasury would be "broadly
consistent" with projections issued Thursday by the Reserve Bank,
New Zealand central bank, which forecast the economic growth of
the country of only 0.1 percent in the year to next March.
</P>
<P>
However, Birch hinted that the Reserve Bank's expectation of a
strong rebound in 1999 and 2000, with growth rates of more than
four percent projected, might be "too optimistic". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
