<HEADLINE> Christie Attacks IOC Meeting on Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Former Olympic 100m champion
Linford Christie of Britain attacked the International Olympic
Committee (IOC) on its meeting which deals with the doping crisis
in sports.
</P>
<P>
The sprinter, who is now at the European Championships as a
coach, recently won a libel case over false drug allegations.
</P>
<P>
He told Radio 4's Today programme on Thursday: "We should be
concentrating on the championships and not being worried about
all these stupid meetings, to be honest."
</P>
<P>
The former sprinter also criticised the sport's governing
bodies:"They make their rules and nobody asks the athletes what
is going on so I just think it's insignificant."
</P>
<P>
Christie said the problem (of doping) was being exaggerated
and also criticised current attitudes towards athletes.
</P>
<P>
"If they win, it's great, but if they lose, people are on
drugs. It's a lot of rubbish," he said.
</P>
<P>
The IOC's executive board decided in a meeting in Lausanne on
Thursday that four task forces would be set up to investigate
drug abuse in sport before the matter is considered fully at a
world doping conference next year.
</P>
<P>
The task forces will consider what the committee considers to
be the four main areas of concern before the conference next
February, in which all sports will be asked to adopt common rules.
</P>
<P>
The four points are the protection of athletes' health, the
political and legal aspects of anti-doping campaigns, education
of competitors and the financial aspects of the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
