<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Industry Groups Call for Y2K Act Passage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Semiconductor Industry
Association (SIA) on Thursday urged government support for a
bipartisan legislative initiative which will enable companies
share information on solutions for the Year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the Administration and Congress, the San
Jose-based SIA and over 50 other major business groups called for
quick action on an act authored by Reps. David Dreier (R-CA) and
Anna Eshoo (D-CA), according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The bill encourages companies to exchange Y2K information
without fear that the information will subsequently be used
against them as evidence in civil suits.
</P>
<P>
"With only 500 days left before the onset of the Y2K
phenomenon, the time for congressional action on this issue is
now," said the letter.
</P>
<P>
Other signatories of the letter include the National
Association of Manufacturers, American Bankers Association,
Information Technology Industry Council, Motor and Equipment
Manufacturers Association, and the Alliance of American Insurers.
</P>
</TEXT>
