<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yorke Joins Manchester United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Manchester United has completed
a signing in a club record transfer fee with Aston Villa striker
Dwight Yorke on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released by the club, the transfer
fee is totalled at 12.6 million pound (20.51 million U.S.
dollars). United said that 6.6 million pounds was payable
immediately, followed by four quarterly instalments of 1.5
million over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
The Trinidad and Tobago player later appeared at a news
conference with United manager Alex Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
"Of all the strikers who've played against us in the last few
years he was the one who gave us the most problems," said
Ferguson, who had chased his man since last year.
</P>
<P>
"He's got two good feet, he's brave and he's got good endur
ance. He can beat a man and score goals so all the parts add up."
</P>
<P>
Yorke, who had two years on his contract at English premier
league rivals Villa, signed a five-year deal.
</P>
<P>
It came before a 2200 GMT European transfer deadline,ensuring
he can play in this season's Champions' League.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old said although he had nine "fantastic years" at
Villa he was desperate to come to Manchester once he first heard
of their interest and was not worried about the price tag or the
competition for places.
</P>
<P>
"I've played here against some great players and one day I
hoped I would be here to play with them," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But now I'm here I don't expect to walk in without
competition for places because there are so many good players
here. I will be working extremely hard to get a place and then
keep it," he added.
</P>
<P>
The signing topped United's transfer record set in May when
they paid PSV Eindhoven 10.75 million pounds for Dutch
international defender Jaap Stam.
</P>
<P>
United also signed Swedish international Jesper Blomqvist from
Parma for 4.4 million pounds in July and Ferguson said the big
money buys were now complete.
</P>
<P>
"I have quite a considerable squad and I am covered in all
areas. But I may end up with some unhappy players and that may
mean things change, but that is football," he said.
</P>
<P>
Villa, who had offered Yorke a new five-year contract and a
higher basic wage than he would get at United, had initially
demanded 16 million pounds for a player pursued by the northern
club since last September.
</P>
<P>
Villa's chairman Doug Ellis said that 12 million was always
the club's minimum value and he added that he was personally sad
to see the player leave.
</P>
<P>
"We were prepared to resist all of Manchester United's efforts
to sign Dwight until recent events made us change our mind," he
said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
"It has become apparent in recent days that Dwight Yorke
wanted to join Manchester United and would not sign an extension
to his remaining two year contract."
</P>
<P>
Ellis said United had increased their offer late on Wednesday
with a "few add-ons subsequent to that". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
