</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference hours following the U.S.
actions, Albright said those responsible could not escape the long
arm of justice.
</P>
<P>
"We will not be intimidated," Albright told reporters. "Today
the United States is asking every nation to stand publicly against
those who perpetrate, finance or otherwise support terrorism."
</P>
<P>
"We're asking governments to join us in taking the actions
necessary to deter and defeat terrorist acts and we recognize that
this is a long-term struggle," she added.
</P>
<P>
"There may in fact be retaliatory actions -- we are very
concerned about that, we have issued high-threat warnings at our
embassies -- but we are very concerned about what is going on
internationally which is why we are gathering international
support," she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Administration said the raids were targeted at groups
believed to be responsible for deadly bombs which exploded outside
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania on August 7, killing more
than 260 people and injuring some 5,000.
</P>
<P>
"Together decent people everywhere must send the message to
terrorists everywhere that they can hide, but they cannot escape
the long arm of justice," Albright added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
