<HEADLINE> Clinton Tells Motivation for Strikes on Afghanistan, Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Thursday that he had ordered attacks on
"terrorist-related" bases in Afghanistan and Sudan because there
is imminent threat to U.S. national security.
</P>
<P>
"Today I ordered our armed forces to strike at
terrorist-related facilities in Afghanistan and Sudan because of
the imminent threat they presented to our national security,"
Clinton said from the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. intelligence indicated that a "gathering of key
terrorist leaders" was planned at the site in Afghanistan for
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Missiles launched against Sudan came from Navy vessels in the
Red Sea, and the missiles launched on Afghanistan came from
ships in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the strikes, Clinton made a speech at a
hastly-called news conference before leaving for Washington from
his cut-short vacation on the island of martha's Vineyard,
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
He said he acted on intelligence information that pinpointed
"one of the most active terrorist bases in the world" in
Afghanistan and an industrial plant in Sudan that was believed
to make agents for chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said his order to strikes was based on the unanimous
recommendation of his national security team.
</P>
<P>
"The countries that persistently host terrorism have no right
to be safe havens," said Clinton, who interrupted a Martha's
Vineyard vacation to rush back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
He said the facilities attacked by U.S. Tomahawk cruise
missiles were linked to Osama bin Laden, a Saudi millionaire
whom U.S. officials believe to be a major sponsor of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Clinton did not say whether the mission had succeeded.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen said earlier U.S. forces
alone were involved in the attacks on what he called a terrorist
training and support compound in Afghanistan, 94 miles south of
Kabul near the Pakistani border, and on the Shifa Pharmaceutical
plant in Khartoum, the capital of Sudan, which was suspected of
making agents for chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the motivation driving the attacks was "our
absolute obligation to protect the American people from
terrorist activities."
</P>
<P>
He said the administration believed it had to act quickly
after learning that more terrorist attacks might be forthcoming.
</P>
</TEXT>
