<HEADLINE> U.S. Air Force Plans Small Satellite Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States Air Force
researchers are working on tiny satellite operations to replace
large ones for more reflexibility and less vulnerability, the
Defense News said in its latest issue.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force and the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration (NASA) have begun laying the technological
groundwork for such missions starting early next century, the
weekly said in its August 17-23 issue.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force early this year launched TechSat21, a two-phased
effort that would culminate in a three-satellite flight experiment
in 2003, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Objective is to demonstrate that the functions of large and
complex spacecraft can be broken up among smaller, collaborating
spacecraft, it added.
</P>
<P>
Techsat21 demonstration spacecraft would be about 70 kilograms
apiece, compared with today's operational military satellites that
are as heavy as tons.
</P>
<P>
Distributing the functions of a large satellite among several
smaller ones could offer improved mission flexibility and
survivability, said Alok Das, technical adviser to the space
technology and integration division of the space vehicles
directorate of the Air Force Research Laboratory at Kirtland Air
Force Base in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
He said, if the mission is radar imaging, for example, the
satellite could fly in a formation optimized to detect moving
targets on the ground. Meanwhile, it could be better for spotting
airborne objects and suited for imaging small stationary objects
on the ground.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
