<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy in Lagos Suspends Visa Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The United States embassy in
Lagos announced Thursday the suspension of non-immigrant visa
services in Nigeria as a security precaution and the suspension
is expected to last until Friday.
</P>
<P>
The embassy announced the measure in a statement, but the
statement did not mention a reported bomb scare which took place
at the U.S. Embassy Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Independent sources said that a gardener at the embassy
discovered Wednesday an object wrapped with wire in a black
cellophane bag hidden under the flower hedges close to the
entrance lobby of the embassy's main building.
</P>
<P>
The gardener informed a local security staff of the object,
who later drew the attention of the Regional Security Manager and
the American Marines who immediately evacuated all visa
applicants and members of staff from the building.
</P>
<P>
The embassy later invited security agents and members of the
Nigeria Police Bomb Disposal Unit who picked up the object
suspected to be a bomb.
</P>
<P>
The bomb scare incident has led to a step-up in security
measures around the embassy.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of visa services at the embassy was reportedly
connected with alleged bomb threats against U.S. missions in some
parts of the world following two recent bomb explosions at the
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, which killed more than 250
people. 
</P>
