<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Canada's Top Court Rules Against Quebec </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Canada ruled
here Thursday that Quebec does not have the right to separate
unilaterally, which represents a legal victory for the Canadian
government.
</P>
<P>
In its historic ruling on the Quebec issue, the top court said
the French-speaking province can't separate unilateral from Canada
under the Constitution of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The nine-judge court also ruled unanimously that Quebec does
not have the right to separate under international law.
</P>
<P>
But the court noted that if a clear majority of Quebecers vote
to get out of Canada, then the federal government and the rest of
provinces would have the obligation to negotiate with Quebec and
amend the constitution so that Quebec could leave.
</P>
<P>
The ruling has been a key part of Ottawa's unity strategy since
it almost lost a referendum on Quebec's independence in October
1995.
</P>
<P>
Ottawa is hoping that Thursday's ruling by the top court will
persuade middle-ground Quebeckers to support the unity of Canada.
</P>
<P>
It also sent a strong message to hardcore separatists in Quebec
that a vote for sovereignty would mean a prolonged and painful
process.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government said it is very satisfied and pleased
with the ruling Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The court has made a "balanced and carefully-considered
decision" and Ottawa will respect it, Canadian Justice Minister
Anne McLellan told a news briefing here.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien praised the court for
having "well served all Canadians by bringing clarity to
fundamental rules which must guide our democratic life."
</P>
<P>
"The court has confirmed that any possible process of
independence must proceed in a manner that respects shared values
that include federalism, democracy, constitution and the rule of
law, and respect for minorities," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"It (the ruling) deserves the respect of all Canadians,"
Chretien noted.
</P>
<P>
Ottawa asked the court for its opinion on three deceptively
simple questions. Can Quebec unilaterally declare independence
under domestic law? Does international law give Quebec a right to
secede? If two laws conflict, which prevails?
</P>
<P>
The court ruled that Quebec does not have the right to go
unilaterally under either domestic or international law, and that
there is no conflict between the two.
</P>
<P>
Despite this, the separatist Quebec government, which refused
to take part in the reference, also put a positive spin on the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
"The Supreme Court recognizes the democratic legitimacy of the
project and the process that could lead to the sovereignty of
Quebec," Quebec Intergovernmental Affairs Minister Jacques
Brassard told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Gilles Duceppe, leader of the sovereigntist Bloc Quebecois
party of the federal parliament, said the decision confirms
Quebec's position that it has the right to negotiate separation.
</P>
<P>
"We have repeated that for more than 25 years already. This
really repeats what we said," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian market reacted positively to the court ruling,
giving the Canadian dollar a quick boost when the ruling was
released in the morning. The dollar ended the day at 65.28 U.S.
cents, only slightly weaker than Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
