<HEADLINE> "Millennium Bug" Summit to Be Held in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A global summit meeting on the
"millennium bug" problem, organized by the World Bank, is
scheduled to take place in London in October, local media reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be the first of its kind in looking at the
"millennium bug" from a global perspective.
</P>
<P>
Alongside the World Bank, the International Chamber of
Commerce, the International Telecommunications Users Group, and
the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD)
are involved in organizing the gathering.
</P>
<P>
It will bring together top-level government and business
representatives from all over the world to discuss last-ditch
efforts to tackle the millennium compliance problem.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that British Prime Minister Tony Blair, thought
by the organizers to be "perhaps the most outspoken world leader
on the subject", has been invited to address the summit.
</P>
<P>
The "millennium bug" problem, caused because early computers
expressed years with just the final two digits rather than four,
is estimated to cost between 300 billion and 600 billion U.S.
dollars worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
