<HEADLINE> Russia Tries to Wrest Arms Market in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia has launched a major
offensive to wrest a share of Latin America's military aviation
market away from the U.S. manufacturers that dominate it, reported
the latest edition of the Defense News Weekly.
</P>
<P>
Top Russian Air Force commanders, arms dealers and
manufacturers joined hands on August 11 at the Yuri Gagarin Air
Force Academy near Moscow last week to show fighters and
helicopters for Latin American military officials, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
It was the first such conference in Russia to attract military
attaches from most of the Latin American embassies in Moscow and
senior national defense officials who oversee imports of aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The magazine said that Russia is trying to interest Latin
American countries in Su and MiG-series fighters, as well as Mi-
and Ka-series helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Brazil boasts the largest Air Force in Latin America with 1,200
aircraft, and is expected to buy up to 100 fighters by 2005,
according to the "Military Parade" survey.
</P>
<P>
Colombia is seeking to buy spare parts for the 10 Mi-17
multipurpose helicopters it has purchased from Russia while
Peru, in particular, has displayed interest in buying up to
eight MiG-24 combat helicopters.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Air Force estimates that Latin American countries
will spend up to one billion U.S. dollars in each of the next five
years to overhaul military aircraft, although most current fleets
are largely U.S. or French made, the magazine quoted Russian
officials as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
