<HEADLINE> Philippines Launches War Against Illiteracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has ordered related government agencies to launch a war
against illiteracy and also to provide support to the artists in
the country, the Philippine News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We shall declare war on illiteracy and promote reading at the
lowest grades," Estrada was quoted as telling a meeting on
illiteracy Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Estrada pledged greater government support for artists,
craftsmen and writers.
</P>
<P>
Since assuming the presidency in July this year, Estrada has
launched war against criminality, hunger, poverty, official
corruption, and malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
To help his administration wage war against illiteracy, Estrada
called for the formation of a volunteer corps of young men and
women who will reach out for the illiterates -- young and old
alike -- and teach them the joy of reading.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said it will be his administration's long-term goal to
build a public library in every town and city, which he envisions
to become part of the core of the civic community. 
