<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Intensify Anti-Corruption Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has passed an ordinance
that is intended to help crack down on corruption.
</P>
<P>
A decree promulgated by the government on August 17 will
guide the implementation of the ordinance, the Vietnam News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the decree, officials in positions of power will be
required to declare their property interests, including houses,
land and other property worth more than 50 million dong (about
3,600 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The move will help competent agencies and organizations to
better manage officials and prevent corruption.
</P>
<P>
The decree said it would not inquire into the origin of
declared property. The ordinance is scheduled to become effective
as of September 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
