<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Directly Involved in Congo War: Mugabe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe Thursday accused Rwanda of being directly involved in
efforts to topple President Laurent Kabila of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Mugabe told reporters that a fact-finding mission which
returned from central Africa had reported that Rwanda is involved
directly and indirectly in the ethnic Tutsi revolt against the
15-month-old government of Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency quoted the Zimbabwean president as
saying that Rwanda, a former ally of the DRC, has sent troops
into eastern Congo as pointed out by residents in Goma.
</P>
<P>
The information was provided by a verification committee set
up by a regional leaders meeting on the Great Lakes crisis in
Victoria Falls, Zimbabwe two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The committee was headed by Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Stan
Mudenge who returned Wednesday from the fact-finding mission to
the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe was speaking soon after his meeting with Ugandan
Minister of Foreign Affairs Amama Mbabazi, who brought him a
special message from Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni on the
Congo situation.
</P>
<P>
"I may not say so about Uganda," noted Mugabe. "But the people
of Goma in the DRC were saying the Rwandan soldiers were there
and their trucks were coming there and going."
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean president, who also chairs the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) organ on politics, defense and
security, said that the verification committee's report was being
finalized for publication soon.
</P>
<P>
Nine SADC defense ministers who met in Harare earlier this
week agreed that the region should support the embattled DRC
government and bring back peace and order to the central African
country of more than 40 million people.
</P>
<P>
This decision has, however, brought a rift between some SADC
member states such as South Africa and Zimbabwe, with President
Nelson Mandala preferring diplomacy to solve the problem while
Mugabe supported a regional initiative to prop up Kabila's
government.
</P>
<P>
"We are involved in accordance with the decision taken and
recommendations by our defense ministers," Mugabe said, adding
that "each country will support the DRC according to its
capacity."
</P>
<P>
"If South Africa does not want to participate, then fine. We
will participate as Zimbabwe is working together with other SADC
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the apparent rift between himself and Mandela,
Mugabe said: "No, I don't think there is any rift. No-one is
compelled within SADC to go into a campaign of assisting a
country beset by conflict."
</P>
<P>
Mugabe and Mandela have differences over the running of the
SADC organ on politics, defense and security, which Mandela
thinks should fall under SADC structures.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, however, refused to disclose logistics of how the
interested SADC countries would intervene in the two-week-long
revolt in democratic Congo which Kabila has been claiming all
along was being sponsored by Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on reports that the rebels were saying they were
prepared to have talks with Kabila, Mugabe said that "the rebels
will talk peace and act war... They would obviously say things
they want the international community to hear. We did that
during the war because we knew what we wanted."
</P>
<P>
"A threat to a member of SADC is a threat to the region."
Mugabe said. "Loss of peace and stability to the DRC is a loss of
peace and stability to the region and I'm glad the OAU is
supporting our initiative."
</P>
<P>
He said he had just received a message from the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim
offering support to the SADC decision to help the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan foreign minister said that his government
supported the rebels' initiative for peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"We do welcome it because we want to solve the political
problems in Congo. We have to take every measure possible to
ensure the situation gets back to normal," said Mbabazi.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to state categorically that Uganda is not
involved in the Congo revolt," he said. "Congo is an important
neighbor to us in the region as we feel concerned that it is
unstable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
