<HEADLINE> Disease Brought Under Control in Flooded Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The incidence of diseases in
China's eight flood-affected areas is lower than that of previous
years, Yin Dakui, vice-minister of Health, said here today.
</P>
<P>
No widespread breakout of epidemic diseases has been reported
so far and the spread of disease has been brought under control,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 13,790 medical teams with 80,000 health workers have been
sent to flooded areas. They came from the Ministry of Health as
well as from the provinces of Hebei, Guangdong, Fujian, Shandong,
Sichuan and Guizhou and the municipalities of Beijing, Tianjin and
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen medical departments under the Ministry of Health held
a meeting today to coordinate the supply of medicine to
flood-afflicted areas.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of badly needed medicine should be shipped any
day now to Hunan, Hubei and Jiangxi -- provinces heavily hit by
floods.
</P>
<P>
In Hunan Province, more than 200 medical teams are patrolling
the embankments and going door-to-door to assist flood victims.
</P>
<P>
When 120,000 people in Gong'an County were found suffering from
13 kinds of diseases, more than 300 medical workers were sent
there to inoculate local residents against epidemic diseases of
various kinds and spread 20,500 kilograms of disinfectant.
</P>
</TEXT>
