<HEADLINE> Manila Confident of Meeting Growth Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
confident that the country will post a 2-3 percent growth in its
gross national product (GNP) despite the prolonged Asian financial
crisis, Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu told reporters that the prospects of the Philippine
economy remain bright and the country can attain its economic
growth target.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to the projection of an International
Monetary Fund (IMF) resident representative that the country would
be lucky if its GNP could grow by one percent.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, IMF resident representative Heri Lorie was quoted as
saying the Philippines' GNP growth target will have to be revised
from 2-3 percent to a much lower figure, due to the poor
performance of the agriculture sector and the lingering regional
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines was able to secure a 1.02 billion U.S. dollar
emergency fund facility in March this year after sealing a
two-year precautionary agreement with the IMF prescribing a 3
percent GNP growth for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said the government need not revise its growth target.
He expressed optimism that there would be a turnaround in terms of
agriculture, since the country is expecting the results of the
efforts made in addressing the drop in agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural output dropped by a substantial 7.15 percent
during the first half of this year, its worst record in the last
20 years. The drop has been attributed primarily to the effects of
the drought caused by the El Nino weather phenomenon and the
regional currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
"That's the reason why we are doing some pumpriming to create
more economic activities. Maybe they should understand our
situation (is) better than the other Asian countries," Espiritu
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, President Joseph Estrada himself said the
Philippines is expecting one of the best economic prospects in the
region and is "the only one among the countries hit by the crisis
which will have a positive growth this year."
</P>
<P>
"Our GNP is expected to grow by a respectable two to three
percent in 1998 and four to five percent next year," Estrada
insisted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
