<HEADLINE> U.N. Suggests Truce Extension in S. Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General's
Special Envoy to Sudan Tom Vraalsen said Thursday that his
proposal on the six-month extension of the current truce is being
considered by the main warring sides in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The current three-month cease-fire in Bahr el Ghazal Province
in southern Sudan, starting on July 16 due to the seriously
spreading famine, will end in six weeks from now.
</P>
<P>
John Garang, the leader of the rebel Sudan People's Liberation
Army (SPLA), has indicated that he would agree to extend the
cease-fire "if there is a need," Vraalsen told a press conference
here.
</P>
<P>
The extension "would happen," the Khartoum government answered
Vraalsen in a vague manner, assuring that it will consider.
</P>
<P>
During his visit starting August 11 to Khartoum and parts of
war-torn southern Sudan, Vraalsen held talks with Sudanese
Foreign Minister Mustafa Osman Ismail, two other cabinet
ministers and Garang subsequently.
</P>
<P>
Vraalsen said during his visit, he was also trying to expand
the truce to cover all war-torn areas in Sudan. Now the
cease-fire is only limited in Bahr el Ghazal, where people suffer
most from the famine.
</P>
<P>
However, in response, Garang was quoted by Vraalsen as saying
that this needs "a much bigger political settlement" through
negotiations between SPLA and the Moslem-led Khartoum government.
</P>
<P>
"A solution has to be found... The world expect them (Sudan's
warring sides) to take responsibility to their people," Vraalsen
said, calling for more regional and international efforts to stop
prolonged civil war in the largest African country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the famine situation is still very serious
in Sudan which has seen a bloody civil war since 1983 when SPLA
started fighting for more autonomy and religion freedom in the
Christian and animist-dominated south.
</P>
<P>
"Food needs (in Sudan) will continue to be very great through
next April," Vraalsen told reporters, adding that the starvation
claimed some 70 lives per day in Wau, a main town in Bahr el
Ghazal.
</P>
<P>
"South Sudan is facing its most severe food crisis for 10
years," said a statement from the U.N. Operation Lifeline Sudan
(OLS), estimating that about 1.2 million Sudanese need urgent
food assistance.
</P>
<P>
More than one million people are estimated to have died in
fighting and famine while more than more million people have been
displaced during the 15-year Sudanese war, one of the world's
longest, unresolved conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
