<HEADLINE> Greek Parliament Approves Civil Defense Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Greek Parliament Thursday
approved a civil defense bill which is mainly aimed at organizing
local civil defense forces in border areas to provide support in
emergency situations in times of peace and war.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill tabled by Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos, women in the country's border regions will be
obliged to serve in civil defense units for the first time in
Greece, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Civil defense units will be set up in each municipality or
community according to available manpower, in addition to national
guard units.
</P>
<P>
Participation in the civil defense units will be on a voluntary
basis for young men and women aged 16-18, and for men and women
above 65 and 50 respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, it will be mandatory for men aged 18-65 except those
serving in the armed forces, national guard and security corps and
those registered in reserve forces, and for women aged 18-50,
except women who were pregnant, and mothers of children up to 12
years old or mothers of large families. 
</P>
