<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Finds Stress Impairs Memory Retrieval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Stress may affect people's memory
by making it harder to recall information, American scientists
reported Thursday in Nature, the international science journal.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at the University of California, Irvine, have
demonstrated that stress and glucocorticoids, the hormones
produced in response to stress, impair rats' retrieval of
long-term spatial memory.
</P>
<P>
Their study shows that rats have impaired performance in a
water-maze spatial task after being given footshock 30 minutes.
The stressed rats were unable to find their familiar way to a
platform.
</P>
<P>
Non-stressed rats who were injected with glucocorticoids also
couldn't reach the platform, the scientists have found.
</P>
<P>
The researchers concluded that these new results indicate that
besides the effects of stress and glucocorticoids on acquisition
and consolidation processes, which is well-known from animal and
human studies, glucocorticoids also affect memory retrieval
mechanisms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
