<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Figures Show Britain's Economy Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Official figures released today
confirmed that Britain's economy is slowing down, dashing
economists' earlier expectations that the growth rate would be
upgraded.
</P>
<P>
According to the Office for National Statistics, total UK
output grew by 0.5 percent in the three months to July compared to
the previous quarter and that the economy is growing at an annual
rate of 2.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
That is down from a year on year increase of 3 percent in the
first three months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The news came as a leading indicator of Britain's consumer
industries fell to a two-year low of 102.7 in July.
</P>
<P>
A slump in consumer confidence, rising interest rates and
slower retail sales are considered behind the fall. That is the
fourth consecutive month the indicator had fallen and economic
growth is likely to continue to slow over the remainder of the
year and the first half of 1999, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
Neil Parker, economist at Royal Bank of Scotland, said: "We
have seen another fall (in consumer expenditure)... I think that
is very important in that it does show consumers are becoming more
cautious as the economic slowdown continues."
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending slowed in the second quarter, with the
service sector also showing signs of coming off the boil after a
period of rapid growth, according to the figures.
</P>
<P>
However, the figures offered some hope to the country's
beleaguered manufacturing industry, whose output edged up 0.1
percent in the second quarter, having fallen during the previous
six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
