<HEADLINE> Burkina, Ghana Agree to Expand Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Burkina Faso and ghana have
agreed to expand their cooperation in the fields of energy,
transport, livestock, trade and communications, according to a
report reaching here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a joint communique issued in Accra Wednesday
as saying that economic bodies of the two countries were urged to
work harmoniously for the realization of the decisions of the
eighth session of the ghana-Burkina Faso Joint Commission for
Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The communique released at the end of the Burkinese President
Blaise compaore's three-day visit to Ghana reiterated the earlier
decision of the two countries to set up a joint committee on the
management of water resources of the Volta basin.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings and Compaore called for
talks between the two West African countries on energy supply "to
ensure power supply to Burkina Faso."
</P>
<P>
The two leaders urged transport departments of the two
countries to improve the corridor for the smooth transport of
goods to and from Burkina Faso and to cooperate in combating
cross-border crimes.
</P>
<P>
They appealed in the communique to the international community
to provide the necessary humanitarian and economic assistance to
the people of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents expressed concern about the situation in
Guinea Bissau and called on the Economic Community of West
African states (ECOWAS) Committee of Seven on Guinea-Bissau to
exert every effort to achieve a peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, President Compaore who toured the Tema Port
said Wednesday that Burkina Faso is prepared to take advantage of
facilities offered by the Tema Port to channel its imports and
exports through Ghana.
</P>
<P>
This year, Burkina Faso has already imported 7,000 tons of
rice through the Tema Port. 
</P>
