<HEADLINE> Soldiers Intensify Efforts to Protect Daqing, Harbin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the flood-control effort enters a critical stage, the
Shenyang Military Area Command has issued an urgent call to mobilize
soldiers and armed forces to overwhelm whatever difficulties exist
and fight to the end to win the anti-flood battle.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains have caused the worst flooding on the Nenjiang
and Songhua rivers. The high water is a threat to the safety of
Daqing, where China's largest oil field is located, and Harbin,
capital of Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The water level of the Songhua River measured at Harbin reached
an all-time high today, with a large mass of farmland and a large
number of houses on the north bank submerged by water. Traffic on
some highways has also been halted.
</P>
<P>
In Daqing, flooding has remained critical. The 50,000 soldiers,
though worn out after long hours of labor for many consecutive
days, are continuing to work to their limits to counter floods and
protect the major embankments.
</P>
<P>
This morning, another 2,800 armed policemen were sent to Daqing
to guarantee the safety of the oil city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
