<HEADLINE> Tarawneh Formally Appointed New Jordanian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan issued two
royal decrees Thursday to accept the resignation of Prime Minister
Abdul Salam Majali and appoint Chief of Royal Court Fayez
Tarawneh to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to Majali following the issue of the decrees,
King Hussein, who is hospitalized in the U.S. for cancer
treatment, said he would choose a new government that "serves the
people's interests in a way that satisfies our conscience," the
official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
Majali and his cabinet ministers Thursday pledged to cooperate
with the new government to ensure a smooth transfer of power.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh is now making contacts and consultations to form
the new government and a preliminary list of new cabinet
members is expected to be produced soon.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh, 49, has served as Ambassador to the United States and
Foreign Minister in Majali's government. He was also one of the
members of the Jordanian team that negotiated Jordan's 1994 peace
treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
He has a strong family background. His father Ahmad Tarawneh,
had served as cabinet ministers, the parliament's Deputy Speaker
and chief of Royal Court from the 1950's to the 1970's.
</P>
<P>
Majali offered resignation late Wednesday due to the complaints
about the economic policy of his 18-month-old government and the
accusation of negligence in the July water pollution in the
capital, that caused several deaths and widespread protests.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Majali at the Royal Court Thursday, Crown Prince
Hassan urged the outgoing prime minister to cooperate with
Tarawneh to ensure the smooth transfer of power.
</P>
<P>
The Regent also expressed thanks and appreciation to Majali and
his government for their efforts in serving the country and the
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
