<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Asia Strives For Well-being of Children, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 20 (Xinhua) -- In South Asia, where children
aged under 16 account for about one-third of its total population
of 1.2 billion, notable achievements have been made in efforts for
their survival, development and protection.
</P>
<P>
"The primary focus of the social sector for the member
countries has been the conditions of women and children," said
Kunzang C. Namgyel, director at the Kathmandu-based Secretariat of
the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC).
</P>
<P>
"This has been one of the principal areas of cooperation
identified by SAARC from its very inception," she told Xinhua in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
At their second summit in 1986, one year after the
establishment of the seven-nation grouping, SAARC leaders
recognized that meeting the needs of the children was the
principal means of human resource development, and decided that
children be given the highest priority in the national development
planning.
</P>
<P>
A regional consensus was reached at two ministerial conferences
in 1986 and 1992, on sustainable measures to realize the rights of
children to survival, development, protection and participation.
</P>
<P>
A third ministerial meeting on children held in August 1996
adopted a resolution setting a number of goals to be achieved by
2010, including establishing a sustainable social and physical
environment in both rural and urban settings, and reducing under-5
child mortality rate to below 35 per 1,000 births and maternal
mortality rate to 100 per 100,000 births.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also called for enabling all children of primary
school age to complete school at the required level of learning
and the elimination of the evil of child labor from the region.
</P>
<P>
In order to generate greater awareness in the region, the
member states of SAARC -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka -- observed 1990 as the "SAARC Year
of the Girl Child," 1991-2000 as the "SAARC Decade for the Girl
Child" and 1993 as the "SAARC Year of Disabled Persons."
</P>
<P>
In addition, both national and regional plans of action have
been adopted on children, girl child and the disabled persons. And
all the member countries have ratified the U.N. Convention on the
Rights of the Child.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the non-governmental organizations in the region are
doing a lot in complementing the governments' efforts. SAARC also
works closely with a lot of international agencies like the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) which has been involved in
complementing the efforts of the member countries, Director
Namgyel noted.
</P>
<P>
"There's a lot of advancement made in this field," she said.
</P>
<P>
When making a mid-decade review in December 1996 of the
implementation of the plan of action for the SAARC Decade of the
Girl Child, a SAARC Technical Committee found that member
countries had made considerable progress in the areas of health
and nutrition and education and literacy.
</P>
<P>
In terms of single state, Bangladesh had run a highly
successful expanded immunization program with immunization of 12
to 23-month infants being nearly universal.
</P>
<P>
Enrollment in primary education there was 79.5 percent for
girls and 81.6 percent for boys, and allocation of funds for
education had increased to three percent of GDP from two percent.
</P>
<P>
In Bhutan, women were treated equal to men under the law and
there was no discrimination against the girl child. The national
plan of action included policies and strategies focusing on
drawing women and girls into the mainstream of the development
process.
</P>
<P>
The Bhutanese government provided equal opportunity to both the
sexes to avail them of the educational facilities at all levels,
and vocational training was launched for school dropouts.
</P>
<P>
India had done well in reducing child mortality rate from 177
per 1,000 births in 1980 to 109 per 1,000 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
And in that country, enrollment of girls in primary level had
increased from 41.5 percent of total enrollment in 1990-91 to 43.2
percent in 1995-96, and 63 percent of enrolled girls completed
primary education.
</P>
<P>
In the Maldives, girl child had equal chances of survival,
growth and development without discrimination in health care. The
infant mortality rate there was 31 per 1,000 births.
</P>
<P>
Primary education was available for all girls in the atolls and
at least 80 percent of girls of primary school age had seen
completion.
</P>
<P>
Nepal had achieved the goal of one-third reduction in infant
mortality rate. Female literacy rate of 23 percent had been
achieved while the target was 33 percent, and there was a 71
percent rise in budget allocation for education.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government launched a social action program in
1993 to look after child and mother's health and sanitation. And
enrollment in 1995 was 66 percent for girls and 91 percent for
boys in the country.
</P>
<P>
In Sri Lanka, 12 out of 13 children survived the first year of
life and life expectancy for females had also increased.
</P>
<P>
Education was free from kindergarten to university for both
boys and girls. Dropout rates were less for girls in every
province in the island country.
</P>
<P>
However, malnutrition and trafficking in girl child, among
others, remained the serious concerns of the member countries.
</P>
<P>
At their 9th summit in May 1997, SAARC leaders decided to
examine the possibility of launching an initiative on nutrition
which aims to promote availability of food of essential
nutritional value to individual household.
</P>
<P>
Namgyel said the SAARC Technical Committee on Health had come
up with a number of proposals in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the member countries are strengthening their
national policies on nutrition, she said. "We have noticed that it
is treated more as a national problem, and not just as a sectoral
problem."
</P>
<P>
At the 10th summit held last month in Colombo, Sri Lanka, SAARC
leaders agreed to sign the Regional Convention on Combating the
Crime of Trafficking in Women and Children for Prostitution at
their next summit in 1999 and suggested that the scope of the
convention be broadened to cover purposes other than prostitution.
</P>
<P>
They also recommended the exploration of the feasibility of
establishing a Regional Fund for Rehabilitation of Victims of
Trafficking in Women and Children for Prostitution on a voluntary
basis.
</P>
<P>
Namgyel said the member states are now working on a Convention
on Regional Arrangements on the Promotion of Child Welfare in
South Asia in launching SAARC Decade of the Rights of the Child
From 2001 to 2010.
</P>
<P>
"We're hoping that by the next summit we'll also have this
draft convention ready for the member countries to sign," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Minister, U.S. Ambassador Discuss Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Minister of State for
international cooperation Kiddu Makubuya Thursday discussed with
U.S. Ambassador to Uganda Nancy Powell the worsening situation in
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador delivered a message of the U.S. government
on the current situation in the DRC, a press release from the
Ugandan Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides shared the fear that the armed conflict between
troops loyal to DRC President Laurent Kabila and the ethnic Tutsi
soldiers, which has caused untold sufferings to the civilian
population, has been deteriorating so fast that it is getting out
of control and can easily spill over to neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that concerted efforts should immediately make to
bring about a cease-fire and find an eventual peaceful resolution
to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has been concerned about the situation in
the DRC. The ambassador had previously met with Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni in northern Gulu district over the
issue.
</P>
<P>
According to British Broadcasting Corporation reports, the
rebel forces have occupied some other towns in the southwestern
part of the DRC, having cleared last obstacles on their way to
the capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
The southern African countries seem to be split over the
situation in the DRC. Some countries such as Zimbabwe pledged to
support Kabila militarily while others, like Botswana and South
Africa, prefer to take a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been accused by Kabila of formenting the rebellion
to oust his 15-month-old administration, a charge Ugandan Foreign
Ministry vehemently denied at once. 
</P>
