<HEADLINE> Golan Settlement Expansion Sparks Debate in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Israel's plan to expand
settlements on the Golan Heights sparked a fierce debate Thursday
in which major opposition leaders condemned it as "provocation."
</P>
<P>
A ministerial committee headed by the hawkish National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon approved Wednesday the plan
to build 4,800 new housing units in four settlements in south of
the Golan Heights, which Israel captured from Syria in 1967.
</P>
<P>
Former Prime Minister Shimon Peres, of the leading opposition
Labor party, on Thursday called the plan to build 4,800 units in
four settlements in the Golan Heights as an "unnecessary and
irritating provocation."
</P>
<P>
Yossi Sarid, leader of another dovish opposition party Meretz,
urged Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, regarded as a moderate,
to foil Sharon's plan, saying he should resign if he fails to keep
the plan from being carried out.
</P>
<P>
Sarid said that Mordechai has repeatedly appealed to Syria to
come back to the negotiating table, so he would lose his
credibility if he does nothing to prevent the settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai reportedly said earlier this week that Israel should
withdraw from the Golan Heights, but the depth of the withdrawal
depends on the level of security it obtains from Syria.
</P>
<P>
Sharon has denied that the expansion would undermine the
resumption of peace talks with Syria, saying that it is not
building new settlements but only expanding the existing ones.
</P>
<P>
But Sarid dismissed this claim as "old bad tricks."
</P>
<P>
"There is no difference between establishing new settlements
and enlarging existing settlements," he was quoted by Israel Radio
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, however, defended Sharon's
decision Thursday, saying the development of existing settlements
was always the policy of his government.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the expansion, Israel was ready to renew peace
talks with Syria at any time, Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
Experts have warned that the expansion decision would have
severe consequences at a time when Syria was weighing the
positive and negative aspects of renewing talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Haaretz quoted an official Syrian newspaper as
saying Thursday that peace talks with Israel would never resume
without an irrevocable Israeli commitment to a full withdrawal
from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian peace talks have been suspended since early
1996 after making considerable progress on an informal promise made
by the previous Labor government on a withdrawal from the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
While the Netanyahu-led government has repeatedly called on
Syria to resume the talks without any preconditions, Damascus
insists that they should be restarted from the point where they
were left off -- namely Israel promises a full pullout from the
Golan Heights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
