<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nature Is Harming Ozone Layer: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have found evidence
suggesting that nature's impact on ozone layer is far bigger than
people thought, The Times newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nearly a fifth of the damage to the ozone layer is being caused
by natural emissions, with the fungi alone releasing 160,000 tons
a year of ozone-killing chemicals, the researchers concluded.
</P>
<P>
It may mean that the thinning of ozone layer and the appearance
of holes over the Poles could, over hundreds of thousands of
years, be triggered by natural emissions rivalling man-made
pollutants.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe our use of CFCs is not as catastrophic as we tend to
think, given that natural processes produce similar compounds."
David Harper of Queen's University, Belfast, one of the
researchers, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The research is part of an international effort to uplanet, The Times said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
