<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supplies Ahmad Gowaili
said Egypt has increased its wheat self-sufficiency from 20
percent two decades ago to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government target in the immediate future is to become 75
percent sufficient in wheat production, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gowaili, addressing a meeting of students at Cairo University
on Wednesday night said foreign currency reserves at the Central
Bank are now enough to cover the country's imports for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
But he said Egypt should continue to broaden its policy of
agrarian reform and increase wheat and corn production.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt said it is implementing the Arab free trade
zones ahead of schedule in a bid to open new markets for its
products, the Middle East News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Arab free trade zones will be completed by the year 2008 as
stipulated in resolutions adopted by the 1996 Arab Summit in
Cairo. In the next 10 years, customs tariffs will be reduced by 10
percent each year.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt along with several Arab countries did not wait for the
10-year phased period and started immediately to reduce customs,"
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supplies Ahmad Gowaili said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Agreements to this end were reached with Morocco, Tunisia and
Bahrain to do away with customs tariffs within five or seven years
at most, he said.
</P>
<P>
Similar agreements were under negotiations with Lebanon,
Jordan, Syria, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The United Nations Sanctions Committee has approved
seven contracts for Jordanian companies to supply 7 million
U.S. dollars worth of goods to Iraq under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
According to the seven contracts, Jordan will supply Iraq with
veterinary drugs, eggs, fodder concentrates, medicines and milk
powder.
</P>
<P>
This increased the total number of Jordanian-Iraqi contracts
approved by the U.N. to 10, valued at 594,567 dollars, in the
fourth stage of the program.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- There are 28 hotels under construction in Jordan. The
building boom is a result of investors' expectation of a huge
influx of tourists into the kingdom by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
At least 7 million tourists and Christian pilgrims are
expected to buy regional package tours that include Israel,
Egypt, Palestine and Jordan in the coming few years.
</P>
<P>
The new hotels have to be completed by that time to meet the
high wave of tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo Rebels Favor Cease-fire Talks: Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A leader of Congo (K) rebels
said Thursday he is willing to negotiate a cease-fire in a war
with President Laurent Kabila and appealed to South African
Leader Nelson Mandela to help, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Wamba Dia Wamba, Head of the rebel Congolese Democratic
Coalition, said in Goma in eastern Congo that it is up to
regional leaders to work out a cease-fire to be followed by talks
with Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready for a cease-fire. We are ready for negotiations
with Kabila because we believe the problems of the Congo are
political and beg a political solution," Wamba said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Mandela appealed for talks between the warring sides
in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Wamba said the rebels would favor Mandela's mediation because
other countries in the region had already taken sides.
</P>
<P>
But he warned that the prospects for a political solution
could be jeopardized if Kabila continues his "random arrests and
sporadic killings of Banyamulenge ethnic Tutsis."
</P>
<P>
"We appeal to Mandela to use his weight to stop Kabila from
the widespread killings of Tutsis in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers of Congo's ethnic Tutsi community staged a mutiny on
August 2 in east and west Congo to oust Kabila, who seized power
in May last year after a seven-month bush war which toppled late
dictator Mobutu Sese Seko. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
