<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Stands Firm on Missile Deal: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said Thursday that his government is standing firm on the
decision to buy and deploy Russian-made anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
"For the time being, the decision of the National Council (on
buying the missiles) is still valid," Clerides told reporters upon
return from his vacation.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot National Council is the top advisory body for the
president on handling the protracted Cyprus problem. It insists on
deploying the missiles unless significant progress is made in the
peace talks with the Turkish Cypriots or demilitarization of the
divided island is agreed on.
</P>
<P>
"The government has no plans to postpone the arrival of the
S-300 missiles," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus clinched a deal with Russia early last year to buy the
surface-to-air S-300 missiles, which are expected to be delivered
in November.
</P>
<P>
The deal has sparked strong protests from Turkey, which has
vowed to block the delivery of the missiles and threatened to
launch preemptive strikes if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been split into the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north
and the Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus to protect
the Turkish Cypriot minorities, who unilaterally declared in 1983
the breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized
only by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
