<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0345 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Polio Drive Successful in Somalia: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The largest ever anti-polio
campaign has successfully ended in the central and southern
regions of Somalia despite rampant banditry, a senior health
official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Health Authority (JHA) coordinator, Dr. Mahamud
Dufle, said that the vaccination campaign against polio has been
a total success.
</P>
<P>
Dufle told reporters that almost all of the scopes behind the
vaccination drive had been achieved with what he called the
courage and honest activities by hundreds of Somali volunteers
with the aim of eradicating polio from Somalia and from the earth
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Even though the latest vaccinated figures are not available in
Mogadishu, more than 180,000 children under the age of five years
are believed to have been given two drops of the vaccine against
polio plus vitamin A for the children between 6 months and five
years.
</P>
<P>
Similar successes against polio have been reported in the
towns of Jowhar and Merca and the regions of Galgudud, Bay,
Bakol, Gedo and Lower Jubba.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the southern port town of Kismayo, 500 kilometers
south of Mogadishu, said that more than 24,000 children under
five had been vaccinated during the campaign in the past five
days.
</P>
<P>
According to JHA, the vaccine planting body, more than 400
volunteers had been operating in Mogadishu alone while at least
2,600 others had been working for the campaign in central and
southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
One of the vaccination campaigners was shot dead Wednesday
near the town of Balad, 30 kilometers north of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The eyewitnesses said that the man was killed when he was
carrying a loudspeaker asking the fathers and mothers to bring
their children for free vaccine against polio in the health
centers and posts created for this campaign.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the killing is reported to have been a banditry
act carried out by an unidentified gunman who shot the volunteer
after the latter refused to drop down the loudspeaker.
</P>
<P>
The gunman took away the microphone. And the vaccination
campaigner died of hemorrhage.
</P>
<P>
This incident just shows how serious the banditry activities
are in Mogadishu and its surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
As planned by the World Health Organization (WHO) and the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), more than 900,000 Somali
children under five had to be vaccinated in the central and
southern regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
Dufle said that the Somalis owe a lot to the UNICEF in their
part of the campaign in the public awareness and mass
mobilization programs and to WHO which has offered all of the
related supplies including the vaccine itself.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the campaign will start on September
13-17.
</P>
<P>
This campaign has been inaugurated by faction leader Ali Mahdi
Mohamed who dropped the first two drops of the vaccine into the
mouth of a two-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was also participated by Mr. Ali Ma'ow, the last
small pox victim survivor in the world.
</P>
<P>
He has been telling the Somalis not to become again the last
victim of polio in the world as he happened to have become the
last victim of small pox during its eradication program in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Top Banking Official Descries Isolation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A top official of the Russian
central bank on Thursday criticized Western banks of isolating the
Russian banking system.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Aleksashenko, first deputy chairman of the Central Bank
of Russia, said the Western banks had taken a number of
inappropriate measures against their Russian counterparts
following Moscow's announcement of a 90-day moratorium on debt
repayments to foreigners, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He listed such moves as a halt on current payments and transfer
of funds on the instruction of Russian banks and the suspension of
deposits on Russian banks' accounts.
</P>
<P>
"We will try to explain to representatives of foreign banks
that this is not normal business practice and we hope that they
will reconsider their approach," Aleksashenko said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted a break-down in recent months of cooperation
between Russian and foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
"It seems to us that this is a process of Russian banks being
pushing out of international cooperation," Aleksashenko said.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed confidence that the problems between the
Russian banks and their overseas counterparts would be solved
eventually.
</P>
<P>
He believed that all the problems would be smoothed out in
talks scheduled to start here next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Aleksashenko said CBR Chairman Sergei Dubinin had sent a letter
to heads of central banks of the Group of Seven industrialized
nations and Switzerland, explaining the situation in Russia and
clarifying the measures taken by the government.
</P>
<P>
Already, nonresident investors are expressing fear that they
would be discriminated against in terms of future exchange of GKO
T-bill and OFZ federal loan bonds for new ruble-denominated
securities issued by the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the Regent European Securities investment
company warned that if nonresidents are discriminated against,
Russia's access to international capital markets would be hampered
for a long time, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
However, Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov said earlier that
the government would redeem 113 billion rubles (16.2 billion U.S.
dollars) worth of GKO and OFZ bonds this year.
</P>
<P>
Interfax said up to 14 billion to 20 billion rubles (about 2 to
2.86 billion dollars) will have to be spent on the redemption and
servicing of GKO and OFZ bonds before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko met Thursday evening with more than 50 officials from
foreign investment banks and companies such as Deutsche Bank,
Citibank, Chase Manhanttan, JP Morgan and Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
"The topic that we have to discuss today is very difficult for
us," he said before the session, which was also attended by
Russia's chief negotiator with international lending agencies
Anatoly Chubais, Finance Minister Zadornov, Central Bank Chairman
Dubinin and Boris Fyodorov, the newly appointed deputy prime
minister in charge of macroeconomics and state debts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The output of sea fisheries in Tunisia amounted to
33,403 tonnes during the first five months of this year, as
compared with 31,446 tonnes during the corresponding period of
last year, an increase of 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Tunisian daily "Al Sabah" attributed the increase to the
rise in production of blue fish, which amounted to 10,090 tonnes
during that period.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The volume of Tunisian exports during the first six
months of this year were valued at some 3,205 million U.S. dollars,
whereas imports stood at 4,753 million dollars, a trade deficit of
24 percent, or 1,548 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to a source at the Tunisian Ministry of Commerce, the
deficit is basically due to a slowdown of exports of olive oil and
energy material, and an increase in imports of equipment and
machinery.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Foreign investment in Israel plummeted to 1.04
billion dollars in the first half of the year, a 36.6 percent drop
from 1.64 billion a year ago, and a sharper 50.7 percent fall from
2.11 billion in the second half of last year.
</P>
<P>
Real foreign investment, which is directly spent on the
purchase of Israeli assets, dropped even more drastically by 72
percent from 1.027 billion dollars in the second half of
1997 to 285 million in the first half of this year, according to
official statistics seen here Thursday,
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, financial investments (purchases of Israeli equities
 on either the Tel Aviv or foreign stock exchanges) in the first
half of 1998 dropped by 18 percent to 753 million dollars from 918
million during the same period of last year and by 30.2 percent
from 1.07 billion in the second half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's processed food exports plunged by 12.4
percent in dollar terms during the first half of 1998 compared
with the parallel half of 1997, the first time in seven years that
such a sharp drop has been posted.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Manufacturers Association said the reasons
for the decline include lower exports to Eastern Europe,
intensifying sectoral competition from other countries, and the
fact that the local manufacturers are focusing too much on the
domestic market.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A delegation from Shanghai, China has told the
Israeli government that it is prepared to construct a Tel Aviv
subway system, its coordinator, Linda Tse, told The Jerusalem Post
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The group, headed by a senior official in the Shanghai
Municipal Government, includes nine top executives from the city's
Urban Rail Transit Construction Co. and the deputy director for
business development at the Shanghai Alliance Investment Company.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon and his senior
aides this week presented many of Israel's projects currently in
their planning stages to the team from Shanghai, viewed as one of
the most efficient and capable cities in terms of infrastructure
development.
</P>
<P>
The delegation's week-long visit follows Sharon's trip last
month to China, during which he recommended Chinese companies
consider investing in Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Sanctions Against Iraq to Remain in Place </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations met on Thursday to conduct the periodic review
of sanctions against Iraq, but no agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the meeting of the Security
Council, Council President Danilo Turk said the sanctions review
showed that the necessary conditions for lifting the sanctions
against Iraq do not exist in accordance with Security Council
Resolution 687 of 1991.
</P>
<P>
Turk said the members of the Council reiterated that the
decision by Iraq to suspend its cooperation with the United
Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) and the International Atomic
Energy Agency is totally unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Turk said the members of the Council viewed with extreme
concern the continuing refusal by the Government of Iraq to
rescind its decision.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under UN sanctions since its invasion of kuwait
in 1990. Under Security Council's Resolution 687 which was adopted
in 1991, the sanctions against Iraq will not be lifted until it
has destroyed all its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
This is the 40th such review which is held every sixty days as
required by the Security Council Resolution of 687 of 1991.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced to suspend cooperation with UNSCOM and IAEA
after the disarmament talks between UNSCOM and Iraq's Deputy Prime
Minister Tareq Aziz collapsed on August 3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
