<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Killed in Building Collapse in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Four workers were killed and two
others missing Thursday in western Turkey when a building under
construction collapsed.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported that the
incident occurred in the city of Bursa, capital of Bursa Province,
330 kilometers west of Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The building collapsed when the concrete was poured into its
third floor, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
It added that that four bodies had been recovered from the
debris and two others were feared to be still buried inside.
</P>
<P>
But it did not specify the cause of the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Index, Volume of Russian Stocks Dash to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Russian blue chips slid 3-6
percent in another slim day of trading Thursday while the
RTS-Interfax composite ruble index fell 5.09 percent to 22,87, a
record low.
</P>
<P>
Russian Trading System volume stood below 4.8 million dollars,
the lowest this year, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The RTS1-Interfax index, which does not include shares of
Gazprom, Russia's largest oil and gas company, was down 4.01
percent from Wednesday's close to 86.57.
</P>
<P>
Market watchers believe stock prices will continue to fall to
the end of the week as the market nervously waits for government
clarification on the restructuring of its ruble-denominated GKO
treasury bills into new Finance Ministry securities.
</P>
<P>
Without the GKO market, stock trading was virtually ground to a
halt, Dmitri Sitrotinin, of Alfa-Kapital Brok, said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian market can only function with the support of
foreign investors, and without them small speculators cannot break
the downward trend, Interfax quoted Sitrotinin as saying.
</P>
<P>
By closing on the RTS Thursday, Unified Energy Systems of
Russia was at 0.06/0.0585 dollar, down 6.3 percent in volume of
10.67 million shares; Lukoil was at 5.045/5.2 dollars, down 3
percent on 700,000 shares; Mosenergo was at 0.029/0.029 dollar,
down 2 percent with 3 million shares traded. Rostelecom dropped 6
percent to 0.9/0.95 dollar with 40,000 shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Gazprom shares plunged Thursday, forcing trading to be
suspended twice in the afternoon. Gazprom closed at 0.93 rubles,
down 17.7 percent from Wednesday's close. 
</P>
