<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Police Hunt Man for Swindling Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Police in the Arusha
Region in north Tanzania are searching for a man who swindled a
total of 4,000 U.S. Dollars out of three foreign tourists earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
Josiah Mwesiga, the Arusha Regional Police Commander, said
Thursday that Mutta had been notorious for cheating tourists,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Mwesiga said the latest victim was an Australian citizen Nilei
Brenape, who complained that on August 5 Mutta took away 3,400
U.S. Dollars from him and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
Mutta, who met Brenape in Mombasa of Kenya, had promised to
guide Brenape to visit Tanzania's Manyara Lake, Ngorongoro crater
and Mount Kilimanjaro. They concluded the deal but Mutta
disappeared when they arrived in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Mutta also cheated two Dutch tourists of about 370 U.S.
Dollars meant for visiting Ngorongoro but he vanished with the
money.
</P>
<P>
"Police are fed up with this shameful behavior of Mutta," he
said, adding that they are hunting him.
</P>
<P>
Mutta has more than 10 pending cases in courts of swindling
tourists but they failed to proceed because the complainants are
short of time in Tanzania after visiting scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
It has also been alleged that Mutta conspired with the court
judges and police in the past to cover up all the pending cases.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Daniel ole Njoolay, the Arusha Regional
Commissioner, told reporters that the government has laid
strategies in dealing with such kind of "flycatchers" who
swindled tourists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
