<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Launches Project to Do Away With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's project to
combat rinderpest is a success and one which will serve as an
example in the fight against cross-border diseases, the Ethiopian
Ministry of Agricuture said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Haddera Gebru, Head of Animal and Fishery Resources
Development and Hygiene Technology Supervision Department of the
ministry, told local reporters that 55 million cattle were
inoculated in three rounds between 1989 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Cattle in most part of the country have been inoculated
against the disease which has significant economic impact by
causing cattle catastrophe, she said.
</P>
<P>
Gebru said 7,762,350 Birr (1.1 million U.S. Dollars) is
allocated for the execution of the project in 1998/99 fiscal
year, and 77 percent of the money is obtained through foreign aid
while the remaining is allocated by the government.
</P>
<P>
Some 750,000 cattle in 20 frontier towns of southwestern
Ethiopia will be vaccinated in 1998/99, she added.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia stands first in Africa and tenth in the world in its
livestock resource, which includes 33 million cattle. Hides and
skins export is the country's second largest export item next
only to coffee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
