<HEADLINE> China Stands for Comprehensive Review of Iraqi Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- China sees a
comprehensive review of the Iraq issue as necessary and urges an
early resumption of dialogue between Iraq and U.N. agencies on
arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary for the Security Council to have a
comprehensive review of the Iraqi Issue as proposed by the (U.N.)
Secretary-General (Kofi Annan)," said Sheng Guofang, Chinese
Deputy Permanent Representative to the United Nations on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It is also necessary for the council to give an objective
evaluation of the progress made in disarmament in Iraq, in line
with the stipulations in U.N. resolutions concerned, he told
reporters after the council met for a periodic review of sanctions
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Sanctions, imposed since 1990 after the Iraqi invasion of
Kuwait, cannot be lifted until the U.N. Special Commission for
disarmament in Iraq, or UNSCOM certifies that Iraq has dismantled
all its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
A standoff emerged on August 5 between Iraq and UNSCOM after
Iraq decided to suspend cooperation with UNSCOM, charging that the
latter is serving U.S. interests to prolong sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Annan has asked the council to comprehensively review the whole
question by engaging Iraq more closely to find ways of resolving
the differences.
</P>
<P>
The council should talk with Iraq directly and the dialogue
between UNSCOM and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)
on one hand, and Iraq on the other, should resume as soon as
possible, Sheng noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
