<HEADLINE> IOC to Set up Task Forces to Investigate Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic Committee
(IOC) officials have decided to set up four task forces to
investigate drug abuse in sport following the doping scandal at
this year's Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
The four task forces will address respectively the issues of
the protection of athletes' health, the political and legal
aspects of anti-doping campaigns, education of competitors and the
financial aspects of the problem, according to the decision made
at the IOC executive board's meeting Thursday in the Olympic
capital of Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
The four working groups, expected to begin work by mid
September, will prepare the works of a World Conference on Doping
in Sport which shall take place in Lausanne on February 2-3, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The IOC said that it would immediately begin to consult with
all major organizations and institutions concerned, including
governments, in order to start the preparation of the conference
and the establishment of the working groups. 
</P>
