<HEADLINE> Turkish President Calls for Social Tolerance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel Thursday called on the Turkish people to create an
environment of toleration in order to maintain national peace
and stability.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ground breaking ceremony of Istanbul
University's School of Theology, Demirel said that both the
secular system and freedom of religion are protected by the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
"There is no contradiction between being a secularist and
being a Muslim," he said.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said that 99 percent of Turkey's population are
Muslims but the state is a secular one which has all the features
of modern democracies.
</P>
<P>
He noted that viewing secularism as an antithesis of freedom
of religion would only undermine the country's democratic basis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Turkish president said that the discussions
concerning secularism and religion should be conducted properly so
as not to intensify the social divide.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's powerful military has been urging the government to
take tough measures against the religious radicals and remove
pro-Islamic politicians from their government posts.
</P>
<P>
Last summer, the coalition government headed by former Islamic
Welfare Party's leader Necmettin Erbakan was forced to step down
for the alleged attempt to weaken the country's secular system.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the Welfare Party was banned by the
Constitutional Court because of the same reason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
