<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl's Rival Unveils Ruling Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Gerhard Schroeder, chancellor
candidate of the Germany's main opposition Social Democratic Party
(SPD) Thursday pledged to usher in a new era of modernity and
social justice in Germany in case of an election victory in next
month's national vote.
</P>
<P>
Riding over a consistent lead over German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl in opinion polls, Schroeder Thursday presented a short-term
ruling program which he promised to implement within 100 days if
he could defeat Kohl's center-right ruling coalition in the
general elections on September 27.
</P>
<P>
Highlights of Schroeder's plan includes a tax reform and a new
"Alliance for Jobs" to combat Germany's high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
According to Schroeder, his tax reform plan would yield a 10
billion mark (5.6 billion U.S. dollar) annual tax cut with
Germany's top income tax rate being trimmed to 49 percent from 53
percent and the lowest rate to 21.9 percent from 25.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although less dramatic than the 30-billion-mark
(17-billion-dollar) tax cut plan proposed by Kohl's government,
the SPD said that their reform package was more feasible given
Germany's financial reality and would bring more social justice.
</P>
<P>
With unemployment standing at near post-war record highs,
Schroeder on Thursday also vowed to resurrect the "Alliance for
Jobs," an joint effort by trade unions, employers and the
government to reduce unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 initiative launched by Kohl's government fell apart
during its first year amid union opposition to a series of welfare
reform proposals by the government.
</P>
<P>
Under his 100-day ruling program, Schroeder did promise to
revoke some cost-saving social welfare and economic reforms
introduced by Kohl's government, including that concerning sick
pays and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
By doing so, Schroeder said that the SPD wanted to restore the
rights of employees.
</P>
<P>
Under his European policies, Schroeder said that he would push
for more European-wide efforts to combat unemployment after
Germany assumes the rotating European Union presidency in January
next year.
</P>
<P>
The SPD ruling program was unveiled as polls show that the
election race has tightened as campaigns enter the so-called "hot
phase" in the final weeks.
</P>
<P>
Although still lagging in opinion polls, Kohl's Christian
Democratic Union (CDU) party has managed to boost its support rate
to about 38 percent currently while Schroeder's SPD is at between
41 percent and 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
Kohl has been German chancellor since 1982 and is running for
an unprecedented fifth term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0362 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
