<HEADLINE> IOC Plans to Establish New Drug Testing Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) has proposed to set up a new drug testing agency
to fight against doping in sport.
</P>
<P>
The new organization, the Olympic Movement Anti-doping Agency,
will be in charge of coordinating worldwide efforts to carry out
surprising out-of-competition tests during training, the IOC
executive board decided at a meeting Thursday at IOC headquarters
in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the meeting, IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch
told reporters that he hoped the new agency would improve on the
current system by putting all out-of-competition testing under one
umbrella.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch said that the IOC would propose the creation of an
Olympic movement anti-doping agency to a World Conference on
Doping in Sport scheduled next February in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
The agency will be funded by the billions of dollars that the
IOC receives from television rights for the Games. It will also be
responsible for introducing top-class drug-testing laboratories in
more countries.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch said the IOC also wanted to introduce a mobile
drug-testing laboratory to be used at major championships in
countries which did not possess IOC-accredited facilities.
</P>
<P>
The proposal still needs support of international sports
federations and national Olympic committees.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch said the IOC was confident of getting international
federations to agree to its new medical code at the conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
