<HEADLINE> Kiriyenko Pledges Transparency in Dealing with Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko on Thursday pledged total transparency in dealing with
foreign investors, the government information service said.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made during Kiriyenko's meeting with more than
50 foreign investors and businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was part of the government's efforts to convince
foreign investors to stay in Russia in the face of an effective
ruble devaluation.
</P>
<P>
The government and the central bank will promptly respond to
investor's questions sent to an Internet site maintained by the
Interfax news agency (http://www.interfax-news.com), the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Topics discussed during the meeting included protection of
investors' rights and interests, the outlook for the central
bank's monetary policy in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko told the representatives from such foreign investment
banks and companies as Deutsche Bank, Citibank, Chase Manhanttan,
JP Morgan and Merrill Lynch that that developments on the Russian
financial market had forced the government and the central bank to
make tough decisions to stabilize the situation.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the announcement Monday that raised the
ceiling of the ruble's exchange corridor from 6.3 rubles to the
dollar to 9.5 rubles to the dollar and a 90-day moratorium on debt
repayments to foreigners as well as converting ruble-denominated
GKO T-bill and OFZ federal loans into new securities.
</P>
<P>
Some fear that nonresident investors would be discriminated
against in terms of such conversions.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's meeting was also attended by Russia's chief
negotiator with international lending agencies Anatoly Chubais,
Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov, Central Bank Chairman Sergei
Dubinin and Boris Fyodorov, the newly appointed deputy prime
minister in charge of macroeconomics and state debts. 
</P>
