<HEADLINE> Cohen: U.S. not to Allow Sanctuary for Terrorists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said on Thursday that Washington sent a very clear
message by air-striking on a base in Afghanistan and on a plant in
Khartoum, Sudan, that the United States will not allow sanctuary
for terrorists.
</P>
<P>
"We recognize these strikes will not eliminate the problem. But
our message is clear: There will be no sanctuary for terrorists
and no limit to our resolve to defend American citizens and our
interests... against these cowardly attacks," Cohen told a news
briefing.
</P>
<P>
The strikes were taken place at 1:30 p.m. EDT (1730 GMT) at the
order of President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"I ordered this action... because we have convincing evidence
these groups played the key role in the embassy bombings in Kenya
and Tanzania," Clinton said at a hastily-called news conference
before cutting short his vacation to return to Washington. "Today
we have struck back."
</P>
<P>
"The United States launched an attack this morning on one of
the most active terrorist bases in the world. It is located in
Afghanistan and operated by groups affiliated with Osama bin
Laden," Clinton said, referring to the Saudi-born millionaire
suspected of involvement in the Agust 7 Africa bombings, which
killed more than 250 people, including 12 Americans, and wounded
over 5,000.
</P>
<P>
"We also struck a chemical weapons-related facility in Sudan,"
Clinton said. "Our target was the terrorists' base of operation
and infrastructure. Our objective was to damage their capacity to
strike at Americans and other innocent people."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would provide more information about the
attacks later on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cohen indicated that there may be other operations "that might
be required."
</P>
<P>
Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
confirmed the strikes were made at 1:30 p.m. EDT
</P>
<P>
"At 1:30 p.m. Eastern Daylight Time, simultaneous military
strikes were carried out against known terrorist training
facilities in remote regions of Afghanistan and an industrial
facility in Khartoum, Sudan," Shelton told the news conference,
where Cohen made the warning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
