<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Prepares to Move Staff From Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is
preparing to move its staff members out of Afghanistan for
security reasons, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations is preparing to move U.N. staff from
Afghanistan, should they wish to do so, and that will be done on
an individual basis," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. employees have been told of a warning by the U.S.
embassy in Pakistan that all non-Moslem foreigners working in
Afghanistan should leave because of safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
Citing security reasons, Eckhard declined to disclose a
specific number of U.N. staff members in Afghanistan, saying there
were nearly "a couple of dozen" U.N. staff members in the Asian
nation.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. statement came shortly before U.S. President Bill
Clinton announced he had ordered U.S. strikes there.
</P>
<P>
All nonessential travels by U.N. personnel inside Afghanistan
had been frozen in a bid to reduce the risk to the staff members.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, "the United Nations continues to operate inside
Afghanistan," the spokesman said, adding that the world body "has
not received any threat." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
