<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0370 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's New Cabinet Sworn in Before Crown Prince </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Amman, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's new, 23-member cabinet
was sworn in here Thursday before Crown Prince Hassen, who was
deputizing for King Hussein, the official Petra news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Former Chief of Royal Court Fayez Tarawneh became prime
minister and defense minister, and 10 out of the 23 ministers had
served in the previous government headed by Abdul Salam Majali.
</P>
<P>
Majali's government resigned Wednesday after being criticized
for negligence and mismanagement of the economy, whose growth rate
was actually less than 1 percent according to figures released by
the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
Fayez Rarawneh, 49, once served as ambassador to the United
States and minister of foreign affairs in Majali's government. He
was also one of the members of the Jordanian team that negotiated
the 1994 peace treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Ilah Al Khatib, a liberal politician who was ambassador
to Qatar and Egypt, was appointed new foreign minister. The change
is believed to have no influence on the country's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The most prominent feature of the new cabinet is the inclusion
of a majority of technocrats.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein, who is in the U.S. for cancer treatment, wrote a
letter to the new prime minister saying he expects the new
government to fulfill the tasks its predecessor failed.
</P>
<P>
He listed the tasks as being transparent with the public,
pursuing precision of statistics figures, combating poverty and
tapping the potential of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The government's decisions should be "precise, fair and
objective and based on scientific facts, data and precise
statistics," the king said.
</P>
<P>
He said Jordan will continue supporting the Middle East peace
process and work with the Palestinians' legitimate leadership
until they regain their rights and establish their own state on
their national soil.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Tarawneh pledged to work for reform; enhance freedom,
democracy, justice and equality; tackle the problems of poverty
and unemployment; and provide all support for the armed forces to
defend the homeland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
