<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0371 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky Ends Second Grand Jury Testimony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Monica Lewinsky finished her
second appearance before the grand jury probing a presidential
affair and alleged cover-up, her spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
"She answered all questions truthfully and completely,"
spokeswoman Judy Smith said. "Ms. Lewinsky is now looking forward
to beginning the process of rebuilding her life."
</P>
<P>
Smith said Lewinsky expected the appearance to be her last
before the grand jury but "will continue of course as necessary to
fulfill her obligations to the Office of Independent Counsel."
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky entered a side entrance of the courthouse Thursday
morning, and left through the same door five hours later.
</P>
<P>
Her second appearance was used to test Clinton's account of
their relationship, including how she came to return gifts the
president gave her, as well as specifics of their sexual
encounters, news reports quoted sources familiar with the
investigation as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky testified she and Clinton agreed that she should hand
over to his secretary, Betty Currie, gifts he had given the former
intern, sources familiar with her account said. Mrs. Currie
retrieved the gifts after a subpoena in the sexual harassment
lawsuit against Clinton raised the possibility that Lewinsky would
be asked to reveal the gifts to Paula Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
Testimony about the gifts could be central to prosecutors'
efforts to build a case that Clinton attempted to obstruct
justice. Clinton was asked about the gifts during his testimony,
legal sources said, but they would not discuss his answer.
</P>
<P>
Several sources said Wednesday the DNA sample from Clinton went
to prosecutor Kenneth Starr's investigators so it could be used in
an FBI analysis of a dress that Lewinsky said was stained from a
sexual encounter with the president, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky, 25, turned the dress over to Starr's office three
weeks ago after she reached an agreement to testify in exchange
for immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Attorney General Janet Reno on Thursday reaffirmed
her confidence in Clinton as the leader of the administration. "In
all my dealings with the president, he has been to me a person
dedicated to the issues of government," Reno said in response to a
reporter's question. But Reno declined to comment on the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry, who is with the vacationing
president at Martha's Vineyard, Mass., Wednesday dismissed any
suggestion that Clinton should resign, saying the president was
"confident that he enjoys the trust of the American people."
</P>
</TEXT>
