<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0373 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-20 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wrapping Bread Causes Controversy in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 20 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish government's order to
wrap all bread products in paper packages is threatening to cause
a shortage of bread supply in this country.
</P>
<P>
Thursday is the deadline set by the government on all bakeries
in the country to put bread in paper packages for hygienic
reasons, or they will fined or closed.
</P>
<P>
To inspect the implementation of the order, Agricultural
Minister Mustafa Tasar inspected a bakery in Ankara on Thursday
and wrapped bread personally after putting on gloves.
</P>
<P>
He said that bakeries and retail stores selling bread without
packages would be fined 100 million Turkish Liras (363
U.S. dollars) to 6 billion Turkish Liras (21,834 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Tasar also reminded the local governments that they should
close bakeries that produce bread under unsanitary conditions.
</P>
<P>
But people doubted if it is possible to wrap millions of loaves
of bread by hand in a short time as the bakeries and stores do
not have the necessary packaging machines.
</P>
<P>
About 7 million loaves of bread are being produced daily in
about 40,000 bakeries nationwide, and lots of bakeries which do
not have wrapping machines usually send their products to stores
unwrapped.
</P>
<P>
Other problems also emerged for those bakeries that have bought
new wrapping machines. Some of the packed bread products got
extremely soft and stuck to the nylon wrappers, because they were
wrapped immediately after production.
</P>
<P>
One of the biggest problems is that the newly baked products
have to be left out to cool for six hours before they can be
packed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0374 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Fall with Renewed Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 20 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets dipped on
Thursday, weighed down by renewed concerns about the global
economy and with a poor Wall Street opening.
</P>
<P>
London shares fell in a lacklustre trading day, as the FTSE
index slipped 26.9 points, or 0.5 percent, to 5,667.4, ending a
four day run on rises.
</P>
<P>
Traders remain concerned about the continuing financial
problems in Asia and Russia, according to market analysts.
</P>
<P>
"This market cannot keep going in a straight line," said one
sales trader. "Especially with all the negative factors from
overseas still in the background."
</P>
<P>
In addition, a poor start on Wall Street due to a series of
disappointing news from computer stocks, hindered the FTSE's
performance.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares maintained moderate losses for most
of day before the latest round of news of Russian financial
turmoil hit the blue-chip Dax index in the last two hours of
trading.
</P>
<P>
The 30-share Dax index ended the session down 108.19 points or
1.93 percent at 5,488.22. In electronic trade, which continues for
a half hour after floor trading, the Xetra Dax finished 115.17
points or 1.8 percent lower at 5,486.76.
</P>
<P>
The market had been trading some 55 points higher when a
Russian central bank deputy said some major banks could fail
within the next few days. The news sent Frankfurt and other
markets reeling.
</P>
<P>
German banks, which are heavily engaged in Russia were hit and
their shares extended an already weak performance. Deutsche Bank
ended at 130.90 marks, down 3.7 percent, and Dresdner Bank was at
89 marks, down 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Paris stocks closed 0.93 percent down, as investors were as
well unsettled by a slip on Wall Street and new concerns about the
Russian economy moved in to take profits after the market's recent
rebound.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip Cac 40 index closed down 38.23 points or 0.93
percent at 4,087.49. Volume was moderate around 8.9 billion
francs.
</P>
<P>
"People heard the news from Russia, saw the Dow slip again, and
got worried," said one broker. "There is a lot of concern out
there which we think is likely to prompt further losses tomorrow."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
