<DOCNO> XIE19980821.0377 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Entry to NATO Not to Be Regarded as Favor Made to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Romania's entry to NATO ought
not to be regarded as a favor made to it by the North Atlantic
Alliance as "we have something to offer," the national Rompres
news agency Thursday quoted Minister of National Defense Victor
Babiuc as saying.
</P>
<P>
Present Thursday at the National Political Management School
that opened courses in a Black Sea resort called Techirghiol, the
defense minister said that Romania had "a strategic position of
interest for NATO" and "it is a link that is still missing in the
alliance's southern flank."
</P>
<P>
If Romania is admitted to NATO, it could back, alongside
Poland, the statehood of Ukraine that tries to find its own
identity, said Victor Babiuc.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, the economic aspect is also of interest, and it
is related to the use of the Caspian crude and natural gas
reserves and their transport to Europe. The biggest Black Sea
commercial port Constanta is in Romania with an airport built, and
Romania has railways, pipelines and refineries, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Romania was the first country that signed up for the Partnership
for Peace plan and according to specialists, the results of
cooperation of the Romanian military with NATO forces were
excellent, said Victor Babiuc.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that the program of interoperability with
NATO was implemented. It includes 44 criteria and all of them will
be met by the year 2001. The Romanian Army initiated in 1997 the
creation of a Rapid Reaction Force, that will be 5,000-6,000
strong by the year 2000, said the defense minister.
</P>
<P>
For three years, the army had at its head a civilian dignitary,
and the National Defense Ministry counted more and more civilians,
which is required by NATO from the candidate countries, added
Babiuc. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
