<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2042 GMT, August 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel has approved a plan to expand four
settlements in the southern Golan Heights, the largest expansion
in the Golan since the Likud government came to power in 1996,
Israeli newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A ministerial committee headed by National Infrastructure
Minister Ariel Sharon approved the projects Wednesday to build
2,300 housing units and 2,500 vacation units in the four
settlements.
</P>
<P>
Sharon denied Wednesday night that the expansion would
undermine the resumption of peace talks with Syria, saying it
meant only expanding existing settlements. (BC-Israel-Golan
Heights-Settlements)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz Thursday
turned down a request by the chief U.N. arms inspector Richard
Butler to resume arms inspections, the Iraqi News Agency (INA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special Commission for disarming
Iraq, sent a letter to Aziz asking Iraq to allow the resumption of
arms inspections that Iraq suspended on August 5.
</P>
<P>
INA quoted Aziz as responding that "Butler and some elements in
the Special Commission are not international officials but serve
the U.S. policies to maintain the sanctions on Iraq by following
its orders." (BC-Iraq-UNSCOM)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Thirteen people were killed and seven others
seriously injured when a home-made bomb went off in an Algerian
town Thursday, the Algerian News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The blast occurred in the Al-Khamis town in Ain Al-Dofli
Province, some 146 kilometers southwest of Algiers.
</P>
<P>
Algerian security forces and ambulances rushed to the site of
bombing to conduct rescue operations and search for clues to the
explosion. (BC-Algeria-Bombing-Killings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak Thursday met with
U.S. Senator Chuck Hagel to discuss enhancing bilateral trade and
breaking the deadlock in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting in the northern port city of Alexandria,
Hagel, chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on International
Economic Policy, Export and Trade Promotion, said the U.S. is keen
to promote trade cooperation with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Hagel, who arrived here Thursday after visiting the Palestinian
self-rule areas, is on a Mideast tour that will also take him to
Lebanon, Syria and Saudi Arabia. (BC-Egypt-US-Mubarak)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's new, 23-member cabinet was sworn in Thursday
before Crown Prince Hassen, who was deputizing for King Hussein,
the official Petra news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
