<HEADLINE> Kenya to Install Monument for Nairobi Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 20 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi proposed Thursday to put up a monument in memory of those who
died in the August 7 bombing in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
"August 7 -- the day of the blast -- will forever remain the
darkest day in our history," Moi said at a public prayer meeting
at Uhuru Park in central Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the government would not stand by and watch
Kenyans becoming victims of international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"In this respect, I have directed an immediate review of all
security and public safety procedures to conform with the level
of the country's threats," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the office of the president in charge of issuing
official figures about the blast, the death toll of the Nairobi
bombing is 247.
</P>
<P>
Among the nearly 5,000 injured, Moi said 50 will remain
permanently blind.
</P>
<P>
He said that neither he nor U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright could figure out why this should have happened to Kenya
and Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
