<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Convictions in East German Doping Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Berlin, August 20 (Xinhua) -- A Berlin court Thursday handed
down fines on two sports doctors and one swimming coach in the
first-ever convictions concerning sports doping practice in former
East Germany.
</P>
<P>
Ulrich Suender, a doctor of the former East German TSC Berlin
club, was fined 27,000 German marks (about 15,000 U.S. dollars)
for causing bodily harm to as many as 17 female teenage swimmers
by giving them performance-enhancing drugs between 1978 and 1989.
</P>
<P>
Another doctor, Dorit Roesler, and a swimming coach of the TSC
club, Peter Mattonet, were also fined about 4,000 dollars each in
connection with the doping case.
</P>
<P>
All of them were said to have pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
German media reports said that the convictions would set a
precedent for another about 90 ongoing doping-related lawsuits
against former East German sports officials.  
</P>
</TEXT>
