<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 21 (Xinhua) -- Weaker United States and Tokyo
share markets propelled the Australian bourse lower Friday with
heavyweight stocks giving up ground amid slim trading volumes.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index ended 23.5 points softer at
2635.0, but some late buying lifted it off its lows of 2620.3.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei 225 index came off 93.21 points at 15,298.20 with
sentiment pressured by the collapse of trading company Okura &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 81.87
points easier at 8611.41 on profit-taking ahead of Friday's
options expirations and overseas news such as rising speculation
that major Russian banks are about to default.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index slipped 43.7 points to 4655.7 while
the all resources index pulled back 6.7 to an even 1000.0.
</P>
<P>
News Corp ended 5.3 cents lower, its preferred shares decreased
seven and Telstra, which releases its annual results next week,
closed steady at 4.53 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Pioneer International slipped six cents with 12.75 million
changing hands. AMP, which also posts its first half yearly
results on Monday as a listed entity, ended six down, while
National Mutual lost six.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished 4.8 points weaker at 984.0, as bullion
was trading in Sydney 25 U.S. cents better at 284.40 per ounce.
</P>
<P>
Australia's big four banks all closed softer, with NAB losing
nine cents, Westpac falling 16, CBA shedding 10.4 and ANZ sliding
28. The banking index dropped 63.1 points or one percent to
5874.1.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 247.66 million shares valued at 758.94
million Australian dollars (447.77 million U.S. dollars), with
falls outpacing rises by 545 to 369 with 383 stocks steady.
</P>
</TEXT>
